<HTML>
<TITLE>Cybernetics-Introduction</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BACKGROUND="backgrnd/vbar2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#0000FF" LEFTMARGIN="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<P><A HREF="index.html"><IMG
SRC="images/torcher2.gif" ALT="Return to AEF Home Page" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="0" HSPACE="12" WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="59"></A>

<IMG
SRC="images/library.gif" ALIGN="TOP" VSPACE="16" HSPACE="18" WIDTH="345" HEIGHT="34">
</P>
<P><IMG
SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="1000" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"></P><HR><H3 ALIGN=center>Improved Air Campaign Planning Through Cybernetics and Situation Control </H3>
<P><CENTER><B>by David R. Stinson</B></CENTER><HR>

<H4>INTRODUCTION</H4>
<P>
"The first day of the Information Age was that day when our dependence upon computers and
communications systems and high-tech gadgetry exceeded our ability to live without them."1
The Air Force has been in the information age for many years.  The military certainly cannot
function without the computer and communications systems that support information processing
requirements at tactical through strategic levels of the air, land, sea, and space forces. 
Information provides a significant advantage over any potential adversary.  Recently, a
widespread realization of this fact has created a new focus in the area called information warfare. 
<P>  
This paper explores one aspect of information warfare--an aspect that does not gain the front
page attention given to hackers, viruses, the Internet, and other high technology dangers or
targets. The focus of this paper is the requirement to glean decision-making information from the
glut of data available to today's combat commander in a timely manner.  This information is
needed to support near-term planning and decision making.  This capability directly impacts
many vital combat and combat support functions.  For example, building the Air Tasking Order
requires a large data synthesis effort to support this time-sensitive, decision-making function.  
When explaining information warfare, Major General Kenneth A. Minihan, Air Force Assistant
Chief of Staff for Intelligence, talks about information dominance.  In an interview with the
Journal of Electronic Defense, General Minihan defined information dominance with a series of
statements on what information dominance is and is not.  The following are a few of the 'is'
statements: 2
<P>"It is a way of increasing our capabilities by using that information to make right decisions, and
applying them faster than the enemy can." 
<P>"It is a method of using all information at our disposal to predict (and affect) what happens
tomorrow, before the enemy even jumps out of bed and thinks about what to do today."  
<P> "Most of all, information dominance is a mindset.  It is the attitude needed to make ourselves a
powerful weapon on the battlefields of the 21st century."
Before proceeding further, it is helpful to understand the impetus for this research and resulting
paper.  The Air Force has always been interested in developing or uncovering new technologies
to improve its war fighting capability and to understand the capabilities of other militaries.  One
particular area that has been studied for many years is the Russian use of cybernetics and
situational control.  In particular, the National Air Intelligence Center, in cooperation with the
Defense Intelligence Agency, has shown interest in this area.  A full understanding of what the
Russians have accomplished in cybernetics, from both a theoretical and practical perspective, has
not been well understood.  With the break up of the Soviet Union, there has been increased
access to the Russian people and their ideas.  Thus, now is the time to determine through more
interaction and study, whether the Russians have, indeed, developed unique techniques or
technologies which may be employed in military applications to improve information warfare
capabilities.    
<P>While Russia has made great strides towards democracy and an open society, no one can predict
with certainty the future of Russia and the other countries that made up the Soviet Union.  Now
is the time to take advantage to learn more from the Russians.  This window of opportunity may
not always be open.
<P>Cybernetics, the concept of feedback control, is not well understood by many people.  The 'cyber'
part of the word is now being used as a prefix with many words--cyberspace, cyberwar,
cybersphere, and others--to connote a link to computers and high technology.  However, the
original concept of cybernetics--information feedback for control--goes well beyond the
application of computer systems.  Cybernetics provides a conceptual framework to maximize the
use of information in warfare--it provides part of the "mindset" that General Minihan mentioned. 
This paper reviews the field of cybernetics and explores the usefulness of cybernetics as a model
to improve information utilization for military decision making.  It reviews Russian work to
develop and apply the concepts of cybernetics in situational control.
<P>However, the original concept of cybernetics--information feedback for control--goes well
beyond the application of computer systems.
While cybernetics offers a framework for designing and operating feedback control systems,
tools and techniques are required to enable systems to improve feedback and its analysis in the
decision making process.  The Russians have attempted to do this through situational control. 
This paper reviews the Russian field of situational control and the application of semiotic
modeling to improve feedback in cybernetic control systems.  If situational control improves
feedback control, the same techniques could be used to improve the information flow to combat
commanders.  

<HR>
