</P>
<P><IMG
SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="1000" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"></P><HR><H3 ALIGN=center>Improved Air Campaign Planning Through Cybernetics and Situation Control </H3>
<P><CENTER><B>by David R. Stinson</B></CENTER><HR>

<H4>THE AIR COMMANDER'S PROBLEM</H4>

Today's military commander faces an extremely complex environment.  Complexity is the result
of many factors: vast changes in the world's political environment over the recent past, declining
resources, ever increasing implementation of high technology to conduct warfare, vast amounts
of data available to help in the decision process, and others.
<P>Combat can be viewed as a complex adaptive process.  An adaptive system uses its resources to
adapt to disturbances from the internal and external environment to survive and reach its goals. 
Complex adaptive systems can be categorized as stationary or non-stationary.  Stationary
systems are those in which variables change in time, but the function relating them is constant. 
They can be represented by quantitative models through the use of differential equations and
other mathematical modeling techniques.  The solar system is a stationary system.  The
relationships and movements of bodies in space can be predicted with the laws of orbital
mechanics (Newton's Laws).  The functions that define these movements do not change with
time.  On the other hand, in non-stationary systems both the variables and the functions that
describe the relationships between them change with time.  It is impossible to use traditional
mathematical or operations research models to explain or model non-stationary systems. 
"Systems with human components, such as military organizations, are non-stationary, and
axiomatic models cannot be used to predict their behavior."3
<P>Combat is a non-stationary, adaptive process.  Military organizations are goal seeking--the goal
being to defeat the enemy or satisfy the particular mission requirements at hand.  A combat
commander must employ the resources at his disposal to reach mission goals while responding to
disturbances caused by the enemy  or other sources.  While some subsystems of combat are
stationary, the complexity of combat cannot be represented by algorithms.
<P>So how does a commander deal with this complexity and uncertainty, the fog of war, and make
the timely, accurate decisions required to accomplish his mission?  One method is to use models
to generate the information he needs.
<P>

<B>Military Planning/Execution Model</B><BR>
Figure 1
<P>
The model shown in Figure 1 has been used by military planners and operators in some form or
another over the ages.  The model outlines the four basic steps to military planning and
execution.  The following description of these four steps comes from Sound Military Decision
written at the Naval War College in 1942. 4 
<OL><LI>The selection of its correct military objectives, the ends toward which its action is to be
    directed under varying circumstances; (This step is depicted as the first two blocks in Figure 1.)
    <LI>Planning the detailed operations required;
    <LI>Transmitting the intent so clearly as to ensure inauguration of well coordinated action;
    <LI>The effective supervision of such action.</OL>
<P>These four basic steps remain valid today and are not likely to change.  Step 4, the supervision of
the planned action, is particularly important as the pace of combat increases.  This military
planning and execution model represents the complex system in which a commander makes
choices.  The major differences faced by today's commander compared to commanders of the
past are the data glut and the time constraints that influence each step of this decision making
model.
<P>
<B>The Data Glut</B>
<P>
The data problem can be viewed from three perspectives:  the immense amount of data, the
different sources of data, and the need to assimilate these data in a timely manner.  In other
words, how does a commander exploit data to improve his decision making--what can be done to
provide the right information in the right form?
<P>
<B>Amount of Data</B>
<P>An extraordinarily large amount of data are required to understand all facets of society--from business to the
military.  According to Schwartau in Information Warfare: Chaos on the Electronic
Superhighway, "Estimates are that the data storage requirements of a large corporation will soon
exceed one petabyte or one billion gigabytes." 5  If a large corporation's requirement is that
staggering, imagine the amount of data required to control an air component or joint task force
composed of several nations and military services--similar to the coalition established in Desert
Storm.
<P>Information or knowledge is the distilled version of the pertinent part of that data in a form that
helps a decision maker choose among alternative courses of action.
<P> "As was obvious in the Iraqi conflict, we now live in the age of the electronic battlefield.  Less
obvious to many was the fact that we also live in an age where conflict of any kind creates a
desperate need for huge volumes of information.  The modern battlefield commander requires
information as never before, and not just about enemy numbers, location, movements, readiness,
weapons capabilities, control structures or awareness of friendly actions, but also about his own
forces and allies."  6  In writing about the computer and communications requirements of Desert
Storm in The First Information War, Alan Campen explained that every aspect of the war was
automated.  By the end of Desert Storm there were more than 3,000 computers in the war zone
linked to systems in the United States. 7
<P>
<B>Types of Data</B>
<P>
The commander and his staff are not only faced with huge amounts of data and information, they
are also faced with many different types and sources of data and information. It is important to
make a clear distinction between data and information or knowledge.  Data are the raw,
unassimilated inputs from sensors, open sources, management information systems, and others. 
Information or knowledge is the distilled version of the pertinent part of that data in a form that
helps a decision maker choose among alternative courses of action.  Data are captured and
produced by all the support functions such as logistics, personnel, readiness, intelligence,
maintenance, etc.  These data are collected and processed on many different automated systems,
like the 3,000 computers mentioned above--this presents an extremely complex integration
requirement that has been tackled many times in the past.
<P>The intelligence support function provides one example of the increases in types of data required
in modern conflict.  Intelligence already produces vast amounts of data from the various INTs
(human intelligence, signal intelligence, communications intelligence, and others) to provide
critical input to the commander's decision process.  The tasks of understanding what information
is required and collecting that information is much more difficult since the end of the cold war. 
During the cold war, the who and what of the enemy was more defined.  Now, with the major
changes that have occurred in the world political environment, there is much more uncertainty
with which to deal.  One of the results of this change is the increasing reliance on open sources.  
"Unclassified open source information has been shown to be a substitute for and a complement to
more expensive, or unavailable, classified intelligence." 8  According to Alvin and Heidi Toffler
in War and Anti-War, new types of information are required to cope in the new world
environment.  For example, "Fighting terrorism, in particular, requires extremely fine-grained
information and new, computerized techniques for getting it."  9
<P>The intelligence community faces the ever increasing problem of data fusion with larger amounts
of data and new sources and types of data.  "The biggest challenge to the intelligence community
is the processing of vast amounts of data, filtering, storing, and manipulating it." 10 Although
intelligence provides a vital part of the information required by commanders to make decisions,
it is just part of the picture.  The data fusion problem that must be tackled by the commander and
his staff, with inputs, in the Desert Storm example, from 3000 computers processing all his
operational and support functions, is huge.  The problem will continue to grow with new sources
and new types of data.  The Tofflers predict new ways that data will be collected.  For example,
they talk of the day when  "fleets of low altitude robots the size and shape of model planes" will
send back sensor data. 11
<P>
<B>Timeliness</B>
<P>
The third ingredient of the commander's decision making challenge is the need for timeliness in
the face of these vast amounts and types of information and rapid change in the situation.  This is
best illustrated by a model developed by Colonel John Boyd called the OODA Loop.  OODA
stands for Observe, Orient, Decide and Act.  Figure 2 depicts the OODA loop.  The point of this
diagram is that success in conflict goes to the side who can get inside the opponent's decision
loop.  The OODA loop was originated to describe the actions of a pilot in a tactical environment. 
However, the principle is basic to decisions at any level: tactical, operational, or strategic--a
decision maker must be able to observe and orient (assimilate data) quickly enough to make
good, timely decisions.  The decision maker must maintain this capability as a continuous
process.
<P> 
The intelligence community faces the ever increasing problem of data fusion with larger amounts
of data and new sources and types of data.
<P>
                                                                                                                   Source:
<B>Colonel John Boyd</B>
<P>
OODA Loop
Figure 2
<P>
<B>Analysis</B>
<P>"Knowledge, in short,  is now the central resource of destructivity, just as it is the central
resource of productivity. . . .  Nor was there ever a time when knowledge was unimportant in
war.  Nevertheless, a revolution is occurring that places knowledge, in various forms, at the core
of military power." 12
<P>The above quotation from War and Anti-War conveys the importance of information in waging
war.  A major part of the commander's challenge to make timely decisions is really a challenge of
extracting knowledge or information from the glut of data.
<P>There has always been a strong focus on collecting and disseminating data.  However, the
processing or analysis function that culls and transforms the relevant data from the mass
available and turns relevant data into information has not received equal focus or support.  This
conclusion has been reached by many who follow the defense community.  The following quotes
are examples:
<P>"Modern computer and sensor technology has been focused on acquisition of data--not its
synthesis for decision makers. 13
<P>"The ability to employ multiple sensors is only a result of improvements in physical
technologies; without a corresponding improvement in the ability to effectively process the
combined sensor data, no gain in information will result."14
<P>"The under exploitation of information technology includes long neglect of analysis vs.
collection; shortage of analytical process modeling; limited application of computer based
analytic methods..."15
<P>Military activity occurs at four levels: political, strategic, operational, and tactical.16 Decision
making at each of these levels is different--subject to many different influences and factors. 
There is great potential for payback from improvements in turning data into information at the
operational/ campaign level.  The focus of the recommendations in this paper is on the
operational/campaign level for the following reasons.  Improvements would benefit the CINC or
Air Component Commander by helping him deal with the high degree of complexity.  At the
tactical level, an Air Force fighter pilot has a wide range of tools at his disposal to react to threats
quickly and keep his decision or OODA loop shorter than the enemy.  Highly advanced avionics
with heads up displays and other technologies feed information to him on the immediate threat. 
Much care is taken to provide the right amount of information so as not to overload the pilot's
ability to process the information; the goal is to provide just what is needed.  In addition to the
numerous systems supporting a pilot, much of the pilot's ability to react comes from expert
training developed through years of flying.  Thus, a large part of his reaction to a particular
situation is driven by the pilot's intuition developed through training and experience.
At the strategic and political levels, decision making is extremely complex and, by necessity, the
models used are the decision maker's mental models. Aside from the tremendous amount of
information that defines the strategic and political environment there are many influences that
muddy the decision making process even further.  At these levels the decision maker is faced
with political, economic, religious, and many other influences that increase the complexity to
extremes.  However, at the operational level the most critical component is a total grasp of the
operational situation--"situational awareness."  This could also be defined as the summing up of
what's going on at the tactical level. 17
<P>The flow of information in the decision making process at the operational/campaign level must
be improved.  The operational level is an extremely complex environment where the need to
quickly gain knowledge of the combat situation is critical.  It is an environment that seems ripe
for improvement as shown by the following quote:
<P>"Although computerized tasking systems were used during 'Desert Storm', much of the planning
function was conducted as it had been for decades: with paper charts and grease pencils. . . .
What was needed, USAF decided afterwards, was a common mission planning system to help
commanders, pilots and crew coordinate missions for every aircraft across the inventory." 18
This is indicative of the opportunity for improvements to turn the vast amount of data available
from the 3,000 computers mentioned above into more usable information to help the commander
make quick choices. The Air Tasking Order (ATO) is an example of the type of decision making
that can benefit from improved information dominance.  There are many possible examples
where better information could improve decision making in a combat environment--the ATO is
used as just one example. 
<P> The ATO is the single integrated tasking document that directs all air activity against the enemy. 
It was used to run much of Desert Storm. 19 As reported in Airpower in the Gulf, Norman
Friedman claimed that the ATO decision cycle was too slow.  He said, "A more aggressive and
determined enemy might have done much better by exploiting its inherent lags." 20 The ATO is
the result of an extremely complex planning process.  It's production requires the synthesis of a
large amount of data on the current situation in a timely manner.  Anything that could improve
the quality and or timeliness of information processing  would improve the ATO process and
would certainly be advantageous in an air campaign.  
<P>
<B>Solution</B>
<P>
Anything that could improve the quality and or timeliness of information processing  would
improve the ATO process and would certainly be advantageous in an air campaign.
So, what can be done to improve decision making in the complex system environment of combat,
where time sensitive planning and decision making is required while handling this glut of data? 
One possibility is to improve the information that is used by those combat decision makers.  Ever
since computers were invented, people have been working on ways to better process data and
present information.  There is no single solution to the data glut problem.  There are, however,
several proven and promising technologies which, when implemented within the framework of a
feedback model, have the potential of improving the commander's understanding of the situation. 
This improved understanding can lead to better decisions.  The framework in which to view these
technologies is feedback control--cybernetics.  The technologies come from areas such as
artificial intelligence, semiotics, complexity theory, fuzzy models, and others.
<P>Before proceeding to explain cybernetics and potential techniques or technologies that may help
implement Air Force decision support systems, the relationship of cybernetics to information
warfare will be explored.


<HR>
