<TITLE>Cybernetics-Information Warfare</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BACKGROUND="backgrnd/vbar2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#0000FF" LEFTMARGIN="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<P><A HREF="index.html"><IMG
SRC="images/torcher2.gif" ALT="Return to AEF Home Page" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="0" HSPACE="12" WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="59"></A>

<IMG
SRC="images/library.gif" ALIGN="TOP" VSPACE="16" HSPACE="18" WIDTH="345" HEIGHT="34">
</P>
<P><IMG
SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="1000" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"></P><HR><H3 ALIGN=center>Improved Air Campaign Planning Through Cybernetics and Situation Control </H3>
<P><CENTER><B>by David R. Stinson</B></CENTER><HR>

<H4>INFORMATION WARFARE</H4>
<P>

The concept of Information Warfare has recently come of age throughout the military services. 
It is so new that definitions, concepts, and doctrine are in the developmental stage; even the term
'information warfare' has not totally gelled.  This section of this paper will take a quick look at
information warfare.  The purpose is not to provide a thorough survey of the developing doctrine,
capabilities, threats, or technologies.  Rather, the purpose is to put the rest of this paper into the
perspective of information warfare and highlight the role cybernetics and the implementing
technologies described in this paper have as part of information warfare.  
<P>
<B>Definition</B>
<P>
The following is the current Air Force draft definition: "Information Warfare:  Any action to
deny, exploit, corrupt, or destroy the enemy's information and its functions; protecting ourselves
against those actions; and exploiting our own information operations." 21 The Defense Science
Board Summer Study Task Force on Information Architecture for the Battlefield (1994) says,
"Information Warfare is a term which has come to represent an overarching integrating strategy
to recognize the importance and value of information per se in the command, control, and
execution of military forces and in the implementation of national policy." 22
<P>The Air Force  currently has placed the following missions under the information warfare
umbrella: psychological operations, military deception, security measures, physical destruction,
technical operations, and electronic warfare.
<P>Psychological operations use information to affect the enemy's reasoning
Military Deception misleads the enemy on our capabilities or intentions
Security Measures include Operations Security (OPSEC - keeping the enemy from learning
about our military capabilities and intentions), Communications Security (COMSEC), and
Computer Security (COMPUSEC).
<P>Physical Destruction destroys information system elements through physical attack ranging
anywhere from conventional bombs to electromagnetic pulse weapons.
<P>Technical Operations is the use of computers and communications to directly attack the
adversary's information functions (acquisition, transmission, storage, or transformation of
information).
<P>Electronic Warfare denies information to the enemy.
<P>
<B>Current Focus on Information Warfare</B>
<P>
It is easy to get caught up in all the jargon and special terms used to describe information warfare
and its various components.  Looking at the basics, the Tofflers describe the information
requirement succinctly:  "Any military--like any company or corporation--has to perform at least
four key functions with respect to knowledge.  It must acquire, process, distribute, and protect
information, while selectively denying or distributing it to its adversaries and/or allies." 23
"Any military--like any company or corporation--has to perform at least four key functions with
respect to knowledge.  It must acquire, process, distribute, and protect information, while
selectively denying or distributing it to its adversaries and/or allies."
<P>In Information Warfare, Schwartau outlines four strategic goals of information warfare.  These
goals include theft of information, modification of information, destruction of information, and
destruction of the information infrastructure.24  All four of Schwartau's strategic goals are
focused on the handling or mishandling of information. They do not address the difficult process
of developing information from data.   Much of the material that I have reviewed on information
warfare looks at vulnerabilities (offensive and defensive) from the point where data has already
been developed into or is assumed to be useful information.  Hackers, viruses, encryption,
deception, communications infrastructure, Internet vulnerability, Desert Storm bombings of radar
sites--those are the areas that have been in the news and have brought much of the focus on
Information Warfare.
<P>This focus is definitely necessary--there are extreme vulnerabilities to the military in the above
examples and there is great potential to gain military advantage by exploiting the enemy's
vulnerabilities in the same areas.  However, it is important not to forget the other basics--the vast
advantage that can be gained through enhanced processing and understanding of the data that is
available to military decision makers.  Historically, as in the earlier examples of Desert Storm,
communications and computer systems have provided substantial advantage to military
operations.  Another example, in keeping with the ATO discussion earlier, is the Computer
Aided Force Management System (CAFMS) that was used in Desert Storm to produce the ATO.
The task of creating the ATO in the required time frames without this processing power might
have been impossible.  25   Using information processing capabilities in operational functions
such as this is a key component of information warfare.
<P>The Defense Science Board lists three "interlocked aspects of Information Warfare". 26
<OL><LI>The design and leveraging of one's own system to provide decision makers with actionable information.
<LI>The protection of those information systems from disruption, exploitation and damage.
<LI>The employment of offensive techniques such as deception, electronic jammers, munitions and advanced technologies to deceive, deny, exploit, damage or destroy adversary information
    systems.</OL>
<P.The first point captures the need to provide better information for decision makers.  Reflecting
back on the Tofflers' four knowledge functions (acquisition, processing, distribution, and
protection), it is easy to see that each function is vital.  The failure of any one is like breaking the
link in a chain.  However, it appears that the processing function has not received the same
degree of focus as the other functions.  Improvements in this Processing function may provide
the key to "actionable information."  Perhaps the ultimate capability in information warfare is the
ability of a commander to pierce the fog of war.  It is this aspect of information warfare where
cybernetics fits.
<HR>
