<TITLE>Cybernetics-CYBERNETICS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BACKGROUND="backgrnd/vbar2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#0000FF" LEFTMARGIN="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<P><A HREF="index.html"><IMG
SRC="images/torcher2.gif" ALT="Return to AEF Home Page" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="0" HSPACE="12" WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="59"></A>

<IMG
SRC="images/library.gif" ALIGN="TOP" VSPACE="16" HSPACE="18" WIDTH="345" HEIGHT="34">
</P>
<P><IMG
SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="1000" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"></P><HR><H3 ALIGN=center>Improved Air Campaign Planning Through Cybernetics and Situation Control </H3>
<P><CENTER><B>by David R. Stinson</B></CENTER><HR>

<H4>CYBERNETICS</H4>
<P>

Cybernetics is a term that evokes recognition in many people, but with an unclear meaning.  As
mentioned in the introduction, the cyber part of the word has taken on a life of its own.  Lately,
'cyber' has been used as a prefix to denote the use of advanced computer and communications
technology in almost any aspect of life--cyberspace, cyberspeech, cyberwar, etc.  For example,
Newsweek magazine now has a weekly section called "Cyberscope" devoted to things "cyber." 
Thus, many people view cybernetics as simply a term that connotes the use of computers.  To
others, cybernetics conjures up the fields of bionics and robotics and futuristic beings called
cyborgs. The origin of the word cybernetics is Greek, meaning steersman, and cybernetics, as a
field, was studied by Ampere in the 1800's.  The modern study of cybernetics began in the 1950's
and 1960's with writings by Norbert Weiner, William Ashby, Stafford Beer, and others. 
However, cybernetics as a separate field of study never reached the prominence of other
scientific fields, but became an integral part of many disciplines.  Cybernetics has become an
umbrella term that is not always used with the meaning upon which the field began.  This section
presents a broad overview of cybernetics summarizing the concepts developed by Weiner,
Ashby, and Beer.  It then explores the application of cybernetics to improve military planning
and execution.
<P>Cybernetics comes from the Greek word cubernhthz, which means steersman or governor. 
Webster's defines cybernetics as "the science of communication and control theory that is
concerned especially with the comparative study of automatic control systems (as the nervous
system and brain and mechanical-electrical communication systems)."  Weiner defined
cybernetics implicitly in the title of his book, Cybernetics, or Control and Communication in the
Animal and Machine.  Murray Eden outlined the basic concepts of cybernetics developed by
Weiner as quoted below.  Eden explains that Weiner's concepts are applicable in every branch of
scholarship.27
<P>"The notion that information can be handled as a mathematical quantity; that this quantity
mediates the transmission of energy and, therefore, can be used to control it; that statistical
uncertainty is itself a quantity related to (and degrading) information; that information can be
used to guide decision making and clarify our own descriptions of real-world phenomena; that
information may be transformed by computation; and that information and control can be
combined to create complex mechanisms that behave as if they were intelligent..."
William Ross Ashby is another one of the pioneers in the cybernetics field.  He wrote two of the
seminal cybernetics books, Introduction to Cybernetics and Design For A Brain.  In his early
studies, Ashby was trying to determine how the brain produces purposeful, intelligent, and
adaptive behavior.  He answered this by developing the concept of ultrastability.  Ultrastability is
achieved by an organism when it adapts to its environment by keeping the essential variables that
define the system (the interaction of the organism with its environment) within limits.  This is
achieved through the application of goal-seeking feedback.  
<P>The focus of Ashby's textbook on cybernetics is regulation and control.  His major concepts of
control are the state of a system, transformations of asystem's state, the black box, and variety.  Ashby was
concerned with how to keep a system at a desired state.  The diagrams at Figure 3 depict a
system T, subject to disturbances D, producing outputs defined by essential variables E, and
regulated by regulator R. 
<P>

<B>Feedback Control Systems</B><BR>
<I>Figure 3</I>

<P>
In the above figures the state of the system is defined by a set of essential variables (E).  The
system (T) undergoes a transformation with each disturbance (D), that acts on the system.   The
goal is to keep the system within predefined limits.  The regulator controls the actions of the
system to respond to any disturbance.  The regulator can receive feedback in two ways depicted
by the two diagrams.  In the diagram on the left (Anticipatory Regulator) the regulator receives
the disturbances at the same time the system receives them.  In the second (Error Controlled
Regulator), the regulator receives information about the resulting changed state of the system. 
The first scheme gives the regulator a chance to react to the disturbances and head off potential
impacts.  The second scheme only allows reaction to an already changed system state.
In dealing with complex systems, Ashby believed that it was impossible to understand the
internal workings of the system.  Rather, the system must be treated as a "black box" where only
the disturbances and resulting outputs of the system could be viewed to understand the behavior
of the system.  Ashby developed the Law of Requisite Variety to handle cybernetic control in
complex systems.  The law stated,  "control can be obtained only if the variety of the controller ...
is at least as great as the variety of the situation to be controlled."  Variety refers to the number of
inputs or states of the system.28
<P>




<B>Stafford Beer's Systems</B><BR>
<I>Figure 4</I>

<P>
The cybernetics concept of feedback has been applied across many disciplines--economics,
management, psychology, political science, sociology, and others.  Stafford Beer, one of the
famous cyberneticians, applied the cybernetics feedback concept to the area of management.  He
labeled cybernetics as "the science of control and communication - wherever these occur in
whatever kinds of systems." 29  Beer categorized systems in a matrix with two dimensions
(Figure 4).  One dimension classified systems into simple, complex, and exceedingly complex. 
The other dimension separated systems as either deterministic or probabilistic.  The focus of
Beer's study was on systems identified in the section of the matrix defined as  probabilistic and
exceedingly complex systems.  He placed such systems as the national economy, a corporation,
or the brain itself into this category.  His goal was to implement cybernetic control in industry
and government.  Beer's book, Brain of the Firm, explained his work to implement cybernetic
control for the government of Chile.
<P>Beer espoused three methods to apply cybernetic control to exceedingly complex systems.  First,
use feedback to make the system self regulating. Second, employ statistics and information
theory to handle the probabilistic, uncertain nature of the system.  And third, apply the concept of
the black box to deal with complexity.  Much of Beer's thought was an extension of Ashby's
ideas brought into the area of management.30
<P>

<B>A Cybernetic Model</B>

<P>
Figure 5 depicts a structural model of a cybernetic or feedback control system.  This model was
developed by Daniel Howland.31  It captures the major concepts of cybernetic feedback
developed by Weiner, Ashby, and Beer.  The following describes the components of this model:
Object of Control:  The object of control is defined by a set of essential variables (E).
Environment:  The environment introduces disturbances (D) that impact the object of control
causing its essential variables to range out of limits.
Monitor:  The monitor displays the current state of the system with information on the essential
variable that describe the object of control in addition to information on the introduction of
disturbances and the application of resources to thwart those disturbances.  In Howland's model,
the monitor is depicted as a graphical display to allow the controller to quickly determine the
status of the system.
<P>Controller:  The controller is the decision maker in the model who initially defines the goal state
of the system through the desired values of essential variables; receives input on the state of the
system from the monitor; and uses the system memory to aid decision making. 
<P>
Regulator:  The regulator takes the actions to employ those resources deemed necessary by the
controller to bring the system back within the EDESIRED limits.
Memory:  The memory holds all past occurrences of actions taken in the system.  These actions
are defined as D-E-R relationships:  a disturbance (D) causes the system to go out of limits (E)
and a resource (R) is applied to reestablish control.  This component of the model gives the
model the characteristics of an artificial intelligence expert system.  The memory holds those
actions that have been taken by past decision makers to bring the system back within limits.  The
memory also depicts Ashby's Law of Requisite Variety--in order for cybernetic control to be
effective the number of actions available to the decision maker (resources) must be as great as
the number of disturbances that can force the system out of limits.
  <P>

<B>Cybernetic Structural Model</B><BR>
<I>Figure 5</I>

<P>


Cybernetics - To What End?<BR>
In Cybernetics: The View From Brain Theory, Michael Arbib characterizes cybernetics as an
umbrella term.  He describes cybernetics as a conjoined study of brain theory and artificial
intelligence and further explains that others use the term to describe the study of complex
systems with the aid of computers.  Much of the original study of cybernetics has moved away
from an association with the word cybernetics into other disciplines which come under this
umbrella.  However, the term still serves an important purpose by bringing together the different
disciplines that cybernetic concepts share.32   Some of these disciplines are mentioned by
Richard Mattessich, "Cybernetics, systems theory, operations research, systems analysis,
computer science, communications theory, information science, artificial intelligence, automata
theory, and so forth, all overlap each other to a greater or lesser extent." 33  
<P>In the same way the term cybernetics pulls together various disciplines to support the control of
complex systems such as Stafford Beer did with industry and government, cybernetics can
provide the same broad focus to the military planning and execution cycle in combat.  The
important concepts provided by cybernetics for the combat commander are: 1) the view of
combat as a complex system and, 2) the vital importance feedback plays in controlling this
complex system.   According to Murray Eden in The Study of Information: Interdisciplinary
Messages, "Cybernetics as a viewpoint has entered into the unconscious of workers in almost
every branch of applied science and the sciences of man."34  In the same way cybernetics plays a
major role in the sciences, it should play the same role in military science.
<P>To many this idea of cybernetics and feedback control in military planning and execution may
seem totally obvious--of course the Air Force uses feedback.  For example, the whole concept of
intelligence is to provide feedback on the current situation.  However, according to General John
Shaud, the Air Force, at the operational level, has had at least two different 
views regarding the granularity and timeliness of feedback.  In an ongoing conventional/tactical
engagement, feedback, to be useful, must be detailed and swift.  In the nuclear/strategic
engagement, knowledge of a successful release was sufficient for operational planners.  The
former is most relevant to the post Cold War era and shows how the cybernetics thread can focus
more importance on planning and improve the process. 35
<P>As explained in the section on the Commander's Problem, combat can be viewed as a complex,
adaptive, and non-stationary process.  There are goals defined by the military mission.  There are
many disturbances--from both friendly and enemy happenings in the hostile environment--that
alter the state of the system.  And, there are resources in the form of troops and weapons that may
be employed to achieve the system goals.  The model (Figure 1) used to control the system is
really a cybernetics control model as shown in Figure 6.  The feedback loop shown highlights the
need for continual feedback to each of the phases of planning and execution.
<P>
<B>Military Planning/Execution - Cybernetic View I</B><BR>
<I>Figure 6</I>
<P>
Figure 7 shows another cybernetic view of combat planning and execution.  This figure
combines the two diagrams, Anticipatory and Error-Controlled Regulators, presented in Figure 7,
into a single model.  A commander must look at combat from both vantage 
points.  To the extent possible, he wants to predict and head off any disturbance or threat
introduced either by the enemy or any shortfall from the friendly side.  Also, he must continually
react to the outcome of actions already taken.  
<P>
<B>Military Planning - Cybernetic View II</B><BR>
<I>Figure 7</I>
<P>


Cybernetics does not offer any new technology that will solve problems such as the more timely
turn-around of the ATO.  However, cybernetics does provide the necessary framework for
improving such a problem.  The framework creates a focus on continuous feedback and planning. 
Development of systems that implement this framework is the key to improving planning and
execution at the operational/campaign level.  Such systems require a broad range of modern
technologies.

<P>
<B>Cybernetic Hierarchical Structure</B><BR>
<I>Figure 8</I>
<P>
Howland has looked beyond the application of cybernetics at just one level of decision making. 
Figure 8 shows the recursive nature of his structural cybernetics model.  In this figure, there are
cybernetic models that represent systems in their own 
environments (perhaps military units at different organizational levels) that feed information to
the levels above and below.  In this example, Howland envisions application at the strategic,
operational, and tactical levels of a conflict.
<P>
<B>Cybernetics - Russian View</B><P>
The field of cybernetics has been viewed differently in the former Soviet Union than in the West. 
It is important to understand this difference to put into perspective some of the Russian work
discussed later in this paper.  Cybernetics was introduced into Russia in the 1950's when the
subject was gaining audience in the United States.  However, at first it was not
followed--cybernetics was viewed as something of little value dreamed up by capitalistic society. 
This turned around almost overnight after Kruschhev called for wider application of cybernetics
during his speech to the 22nd Party Congress in 1961.  Cybernetics became to be viewed as the
science of control which could be exploited by a socialist society 
in controlling its economic and social systems--control that would be ideologically impossible in
capitalist countries.36  
<P>Cybernetics became a widely used term in Russian science.  For awhile, the term was used in the
title of almost any paper that covered a variety of subjects, such as control, time-series analysis,
statistical communications theory, automata theory, and others.  The main theme of cybernetics
that developed in Russia centered around the analysis and modeling of complex systems.  This is
the same view that is applicable to the complex systems environment of campaign planning.  It is
also key to the development of Russian situational control.
<P>

