<P><IMG
SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="1000" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"></P><HR><H3 ALIGN=center>Improved Air Campaign Planning Through Cybernetics and Situation Control </H3>
<P><CENTER><B>by David R. Stinson</B></CENTER><HR>

<H4>RUSSIAN SITUATIONAL CONTROL</H4>
<P>

One of the areas developed in Russia under the cybernetic umbrella was the field of situational
control.  Situational control was devised to handle the control of complex systems where the
traditional, more simplistic cybernetic models were insufficient.  This section of the paper will
describe the stages of situational control that developed from the 1960's through the current time. 
It will also describe the use of semiotics as employed in situational control.  Again, the goal of
this research is to determine whether or not the Russians have developed new theory and more
importantly implementing technologies to help control complex combat environments by
improving information feedback.  By reviewing the development of Russian situational control
and semiotic modeling techniques, insight into answering this question is gained.
<P>Information in this section was taken mostly from two sources.  First, translated versions of the
books on Situational Control written by Professor Dmitri A. Pospelov were used.  Pospelov is a
preeminent member of the Russian Academy of Science.  He has led the scientific development
of situational control.  The complete works of Pospelov have not been translated from Russian to
English.  Second, a conference on cybernetics and situational control was held in March 1995. 
Papers presented at this conference provided much of the information presented.  Before
proceeding with the development of situational control, the following is a short description of the
cybernetics/ situational control conference.
<P>
<B>Cybernetics Conference</B>
<P>To learn more about the Russian situational control and semiotic modeling to control large,
complex systems, a conference was held at the Battelle Memorial Institute.  The conference
included presentations and panel discussions over a week.  The bulk of the presentations were
made by the visiting Russian scientists.  A major goal of the conference was to determine if there
were areas where the Russian had developed theory and applications beyond those of Western
science and to, then, determine what follow-on, joint research programs could be developed to
advance those areas.  After the formal conference period, two days were spent in discussions to
determine follow-on research actions.  These tasks are detailed at the end of this section.
<P><B>Participants</B>
<P>
Attendance at the conference included the Russian delegation, professors from American
universities (Ohio State, Cornell, Drexel, and others), and representatives from various
government activities.  The Russian delegation included distinguished scientists in the fields of
artificial intelligence and mathematics.  The group included Dmitri Pospelov, the author of the
books referenced in this paper.  Also, present was Gennady Osipov, the Director of the Program
Systems Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences.  Other Russian scientists present at the
conference are listed in Figure 9.
<P>

The thrust of this conference was to provide a forum for the Russian scientists to describe their
scientific developments in the complex systems control area.  In order to understand part of the
motivation for their participation in this effort, it is helpful to take a look at the state of science in
Russia.
<P>
With the break up of the Soviet Union, Russian science has not received the funding that it has
historically received over the past many years.  According to an Associated Press story, many
American firms are taking advantage of this disarray in the Russian science establishment by
hiring Russian scientists at bargain prices.  The firms run the gamut from small entrepreneurs to
the largest of American corporations such as Ford Motor.  These companies have hired
individual scientists all the way up to  entire scientific staffs of 200 people. 37
The Russians have talent and knowledge in many scientific and technology areas that exceed and
complement Western capabilities.  For example, according to the same Associated Press article
mentioned above, Russian researchers excel in areas that require advanced computer analysis. 
One reason for this strength is the fact that the Soviet Union always lagged behind in developing
or having access to state-of-the-art computer hardware.  This forced them to compensate with the
development of advanced algorithms. 38 
<P>Interaction with the Russian scientists at the Cybernetics Conference supported this view of
Russian science.  All of the visiting scientists were looking for sources of funding to continue
their individual areas of research.  This drive came from two desires.  One desire that came
through very strongly was the simple love of science and knowledge.  The second was the need
to support themselves in the basic economic needs of life.  It was explained to me that salaries
for scientists in the employ of the government are routinely $50.00 per month.  While some of
the basics, for example, housing and utilities,  are provided, this small sum is not sufficient to
even provide for food.  If not able to find outside funding sources, the Russian scientists are
forced to find employment outside the scientific research field.  
<P>Thus, part of the challenge in understanding the work accomplished by the Russians in the area
of situational control is to understand where work has paralleled Western efforts.
The last perspective on Russian science was explained by Dr. Khoroshevsky during the March
conference.  He described the atmosphere of international cooperation that has existed over the
past decades.  During the 1960's and early 1970's all Russian work in the area of situational
control was conducted in isolation.  There was essentially no contact outside the Soviet Union. 
In the 1970's some contact with the international community began.  However, the contact was
limited to receiving information from outside the Soviet Union.  For example, these scientists
were not allowed to participate in conferences.  In the 1980's, a period of cooperation with
scientists of other countries began. 39  Thus, part of the challenge in understanding the work
accomplished by the Russians in the area of situational control is to understand where work has
paralleled Western efforts.  In some cases different terminology describes the same concepts. 
This together with the normal language differences between Russian and English is a barrier to
be overcome.
<P>
Dr. Alexei N. Averkin - <I>Fuzzy Models in Situational Control</I>                               
<BR>Dr. Oleksandr Citkin - <I>Logic in Situational Control </I>                                     
<BR>Prof. Alexander I. Ehrlich - <I>Integration of Situational Control and Cybernetic Models and Methods for Controland 
                      Management of Complex Systems</I>
<BR>Dr. Vladimir F. Khoroshevsky - <I>Situational Control Software </I>    
 <P>                                                                                                                  
<b>Explanation in Situational Control Systems</B>                                 
<P>Prof. Gennady S. Osipov - <I>Semantic Structures Retrieval in Natural Language Texts</I>
 <P>                                                                                                                  
<B>Semiotic
Modeling</B>                                                    
<BR>Prof. Dmitri A. Pospelov - <I>Overview of Situational Control</I>                                           
Using Natural
Language for Describing Situations </I>                            
<BR>Prof. Alexander A. Zenkin - <I>Cognitive Graphics For Obtaining New Knowledge</I>
<P>

<B>Cybernetics/Situational Control Conference Presentations</B><BR>
<I>Figure 9</I>
<P>
<B>Presentations</B><P>
The presentations provided by the Russian scientists were structured to cover the many areas that
contribute to situational control and semiotic modeling.  Figure 9 shows the topics covered.
<P>
<B>Evolution of Situational Control</B>
<P>
The diagram at Figure 10 depicts the theory of automatic control as described by Dmitri
Pospelov in Situational Control: Theory and Practice. 40  This is a traditional cybernetic
feedback model.  The diagram shows how the man in the loop, the Decision Making Person
(DMP), can control the object when there is a body of knowledge on the object of control.  The diagram shows that there are known
functions that relate the inputs (x,w) to the system outputs (y).  Also a function can be developed
to define the required actions to be taken by the controller given the inputs and outputs.  The
DMP remains in the loop to adjust the control function when desired. 
<P>
<B>Traditional Control System</B><BR>
<I>Figure 10</I>
<P>
 This traditional control model cannot be used to represent systems characterized below. 
Pospelov lists the following characteristics: 41
<P>
<OL><LI>Uniqueness - The object of control has such a unique structure and function that no standard
        model of control can be applied.
    <LI>Absence of a Formalizable Purpose of Existence - It is not always possible to formulate the
        exact purpose of the existence of an object of control.  For example, when looking at the
        existence of a large city, it is practically impossible to precisely formulate its purpose. 
    <LI>Absence of Optimality - Given the above two properties, it follows that it is impossible to
        build an objective control criterion for optimizing the object of control.  The criterion becomes
        subject-dependent on the decision maker.
    <LI>Dynamic - The objects of control change with time.  The control system must be adaptive to
        change with the changing of the object of control.
    <LI>Incompleteness of Description - It is impossible to provide complete information on an object of control.
    <LI>Presence of Free Will - Objects of control include people as part of the system.  People
        function in the system with their own personal goals, which are not always the same as the object
        of control or the decision maker.</OL>
<P>Situational control was developed to analyze systems characterized by the above properties. 
Tools developed to model simpler, stationary systems of traditional cybernetics are not capable
of handling more complex, non-stationary systems. Situational control is focused on control of
systems where it is difficult to describe the specific structure and functioning of the object ,
where behavior of people have an unpredictable impact on the system, and where the system
evolves through time, with increasing complexity.  This is the type of complex system into
which combat can be categorized.
<P>
 
<B>Situational Control Model</B>
<I>Figure 11</I>
<P>
The Situational Control Model at Figure 11 was developed to control these complex systems. 
This model was developed in the 1960's.  The following describes the functions of each of the
components of the above model:
<P><UL><LI>Analyzer - The analyzer receives the messages that convey the description of the current
        situation.  It evaluates each message to determine if anything has occurred in the system that
        requires control.  If nothing of importance has happened, no further action is taken.  If the
        Analyzer determines otherwise the message is forwarded to the Classifier.
    <LI>Classifier - The classifier determines from which of several classes a possible solution may
        come.  The different classes contain "single-step" solutions, which will bring the system back
        into control.
   <LI>Correlator - The correlator holds all the solutions in the form of logico-transformation rules.  It
       determines which solution to apply.  If the correlator cannot narrow its choice to a single rule to
       apply, it passes the choices to the extrapolator.
    <LI>Extrapolator - The extrapolator chooses among several different single-step solutions when more
        than one may apply to a particular situation.  
    <LI>Block of Random Selection - If neither the correlator nor extrapolator can decide on a solution,
        the Block of Random Selection either chooses a solution to minimize impact on the object or
        does not take any action.</UL>
<P>Pospelov explains that this model is the most efficient in situations where the number of possible different
situations is great, while the number of allowable single-step solutions is small.  But it may be
applied, albeit with greater difficulty, to situations which have a great number of allowable
solutions.  In general, situational control amounts to understanding a situation, classifying the
situation, and transforming the situation through single-step actions. Pospelov lists the following
seven characteristics of this early model of situational control:
<P>
<OL><LI>Large up-front cost.
    <LI>Difficulty of describing situation in a language that captures the right amount of information
        to allow classification and lead to the single-step solution.
    <LI>Language must allow qualification as well as quantification of situation.
    <LI>Initial single step solutions must be input by experts.  System must be able to develop new
        rules as it operates.  It must be capable of learning beyond the model initially defined by
        situations and single step solutions. 
    <LI>The results from such systems are inherently better than can be achieved by humans for many
        reasons: no influence from emotions, not effected by stress, nothing is forgotten, all solutions are
        analyzed.
    <LI>When looking at 'real' objects of control, several single-step solutions must be put together to
        solve more complex problems.</OL>   
<P>
Figure 12 shows the scheme of situational control developed in the 1970's.  As can be seen from
the figure, it takes the same basic form as the earlier model with the addition of a knowledge
base, a problem solver, and simulator.  The input at the top of the model from the controlled
object is data to describe the situation.  The output, which goes to the controlled object, are the
actions that are required to control the object. 

<P>
<B>Situational Control Model - 1970's</B><BR>
<I>Figure 12</I>
<P>
A short description of the parts of the model follow.  The coder takes the information (natural
language) that describes the current situation and converts it to a form that can be processed by
the model.  Pospelov calls this the Language of Situational Control.  The analyzer determines if
the situation is out of limits (critical).  The classifier and correlator determine if the situation is
typical and whether a solution already exists from previous experience or a solution can be
developed from previous experience.  The knowledge base holds information on previous
situations.  It is like the database for an expert system.  The problem solver determines the
recommended solution in conjunction with the correlator and simulator.  If the solution is not
known from the knowledge base, the simulator can test solutions. The decoder converts the solution from the
Language of Situational Control.
<P>
Many of the processes described in this situational control model of the 1970's are the same as
studied in Western artificial intelligence.  For example, natural language processing and expert
systems are major artificial intelligence fields. In fact, Pospelov explains that situational control
has much in common with the methods of artificial intelligence. 42  In the March 1995
conference, Pospelov presented Figure 13 and explained the correlation of this situational control
model with the original 1960's version.  Here it is clear that situational control employs AI  and
modeling methods.
<P>
<B>Situational Control Model - 1990's</B><BR>
<I>Figure 13</I>
<P>

<B>Application of Situational Control</B>
<P>One of the major goals of the cybernetics conference was to understand to what extent the
Russians have been able to apply situational control to complex, real world systems.  While some
examples were discussed at the conference, the true success of situational control has not been
adequately demonstrated.
<P>One example described by Pospelov was the control of harbor operations at the Odessa port.  The
situational control system controlled the access of ships to moorings.  Once in the moorings, the
system further controlled the operation of cranes necessary to unload the ships into storage
facilities.  The example was not explained in technical detail, but only in its high-level,
functional concept.  Another example, was the control of operations at nuclear power facilities. 
In this case, the extent of true control versus simple monitoring was not clear. Pospelov also
mentioned other examples of applications that had been accomplished from 1965 to 1985.  These
included control of cement heating in a rotary kiln, control of special drilling equipment in oil
fields, and the control of traffic.  Additionally, Pospelov said that situational control had been
used in a military application to control air battle. 43  Since these examples were discussed in
little detail, further analysis would be required to determine the success of the control systems.
<P>
<B>Semiotics</B>
<P>
Another area where it has been thought that the Russians have made scientific strides is the field
of semiotics.  "Semiotics is the science of signs and their life in society.  Its subject is all kinds of
signs: verbal language, pictures, literature, motion pictures, theater, body language.  Computer
semiotics is a branch of semiotics that studies the special nature of computer-based signs and
how they function in use."44  The first part of this definition presents the traditional view of
semiotics.  It has a very broad meaning--literature on the 
subject spans the gamut from analysis of the theater to linguistics.  The part of the definition that
addresses computer semiotics appears to be relatively new.  This definition approaches the way
the Russians are applying the use of the word in situational control.
<P>The Russians have applied semiotics to aid in the implementation of cybernetic or situational
control models.  The following paragraphs and accompanying diagrams develop the thought
process behind the Russian use of the term semiotics as explained through the work of Pospelov.
45
<P>
<B>Simple Control System</B><BR>
<I>Figure 14</I>
<P>
In the simplest of control systems (Figure 14) there are four components.  The input transformer
provides information about the situation and environment to the decision making function.  In
this simple case the 
decision mechanism is a deterministic or probabilistic function  which determines outputs based
on the inputs.  The output transformer passes the output determination to the object of control.  
<P>
<B>Adaptive Control System</B><BR>
<I>Figure 15</I>
<P>In figure 15 an adapter is added to the control system.  The adapter allows a more complex
solution--different sets of solution functions to be defined in F.  The adapter then chooses the
appropriate solution functions based on the situation of the object of control.
<P>
The next step in building towards semiotic models, a Model Based Control System, adds a
knowledge model to the control system as depicted in Figure 16.
<P>
               
<B>Model-Based Control System</B><BR>
<I>Figure 16</I>
<P>

This knowledge model contains both declarative and procedural knowledge about the object of
control, which is used by the decision making mechanism throughout the control process.
The model-based control system has several shortcomings when applied to complex systems. 
The knowledge model is fixed during the control process, but knowledge about and functioning
of complex objects is always changing.  To accommodate this change, Pospelov uses a semiotic
model.
<P>           
<B>Semiotic Control System</B><BR>
<I>Figure 17</I>
<P>

A semiotic model is defined as a reconstructible knowledge-based system.  As shown in Figure
17, the addition of an Interpreter to the Model Based Control System makes it a Semiotic Control
System.  The interpreter observes and interprets the responses of the object of control and the
environment in respect to the contents of the knowledge-based model (M) and reconstructs the
model.  To accomplish this the interpreter stores facts to find regularities in responses, builds
cause and effect chains, and uses a range of statistical processing.  Under the semiotic scheme the
knowledge based model and interpreter play the central role of controlling the system instead of
the decision making mechanism in the simpler control systems.
   
<P>           
<B>Situational Control - A Multidisciplinary Approach</B>
<P>Now that both situational control and semiotic modeling have been introduced, what is the tie
between the two?  The two terms address the same topic.  Situational control addresses the
function--the control of complex systems.  Semiotic modeling (semiotics) addresses the
technique for implementing situational control.  During the cybernetics conference these two
terms were used interchangeably in many cases.
<P>The key to implementing Russian situational control (semiotic modeling) is the integration of
different sciences and technologies.  This is apparent from looking at the various disciplines of
the papers presented during the conference.  The following disciplines were discussed during the
conference: cybernetics, complex systems, artificial intelligence with specific focus on natural
language processing and expert systems, formal logic, linguistics, cognitive graphics, and others.
I will not describe each of the Russian presentations--that will be provided in the conference
proceedings.  However, the following topics will provide an introduction to the multidisciplinary
approach that is required for situational control.
<P>
The simple definition of semiotics is the science of signs and symbols.  Two topics presented at
the conference, situational control language and cognitive graphics show two ends of the
spectrum in looking at the Russian use of the term semiotics.
<P>
<B>Situational Control Language</B><BR>
<I>Figure 18</I>
<P>
As shown in Figure 18, the goal of situational control language is the representation of the
situation.  The situational control language describes the a situation by taking information from
three sources.  The first two sources are from the situation itself.  First, the object of control is
described in terms of time, space, action, and cause as shown on the left of the figure.  The
second source is the summation of other elements in the situation and its environment as shown
in the upper right of the figure. The third source of information is from the knowledge base that
describes what was known going into the situation, such things as mission and plans. This
representation is continually maintained to reflect the latest state of the object of control in its
environment.  
<P>The situational control language itself is built using a logico-linguistic form that captures
elements to describe any situation, such as: name, entity, relation, imperative (command),
modifier, modality, quantifier, and evaluator.  According to Pospelov, situational control
language can be used to describe a large variety of situations with a relatively simple language. 
For example, with a basic set of less than 400 members any possible relation between an object
and its environment can be described, e.g., to be late, simultaneous, from the right, to move, to
chop, etc.  The explanation of the workings of the Russian situational control language is beyond
the scope of this paper.  However, this is clearly an example of the use of signs and symbols to
capture the understanding of a situation in a form that can be manipulated by a computer.
On the other side of the spectrum of semiotics mentioned above, is the human use of signs and
symbols to gain understanding.  Russian situational control also recognizes this important facet
of semiotics.  The presentation on cognitive graphics by Alexander Zenkin highlights this aspect
of the Russian approach.  The following few paragraphs summarize some of the points that
Zenkin made in his conference presentation. 46
<P>The human is always present in situational control--a human remains in the loop to have the final
say on any action determined necessary by the situational control system.  Thus, efficiency in the
human factors design of situational control systems is a major consideration.  According to
Zenkin, humans can process visual information much easier than other forms of information.
Zenkin made his main point with a picture of a human with only half of the brain present.  He
explained that a human's natural intelligence comes from the unity of the left and right
hemispheres of the brain.  In his picture only the left side of the brain was present.  The left side
provides the logical, mathematical type of thinking.  Zenkin explained that this person with only
the left side of the brain was analogous to artificial intelligence.  With only the intelligence of the
left side of the brain, thinking is deformed.  This applies to situational control, also.  Situational
control requires generating new alternatives/courses of action and, then, deciding between those
alternatives.  This requires creativity, which requires intuition.  Zenkin explained that the key to
the creativity and intuition is visual thinking.  This type of thinking is provided by the right side
of the brain. Cognitive graphics can supplement artificial intelligence by performing some of the
tasks normally provided by the right side of the brain.  According to Zenkin, by employing tools
that accomplish the functions of both sides of the brain, situational control systems can approach
natural intelligence.
<P>Situational control requires generating new alternatives/courses of action and, then, deciding
between those alternatives.  This requires creativity, which requires intuition.  Zenkin explained
that the key to the creativity and intuition is visual thinking.  This type of thinking is provided by
the right side of the brain.
<P>The concept of cognitive graphics was demonstrated by explaining the proofs of several
mathematical laws with pictures. Zenkin used famous mathematical problems, such as Waring's
Problem (1770), Hilbert's Theorem (1909), LaGrange's Theorem (1770), Pall's Theorem (1933),
and others.  Each of these theorems were extremely difficult to prove using the traditional
mathematical logic procedures that have been used over the ages.  The use of computer graphics
has allowed these theorems to be proved by generating graphical images of the mathematical
concepts.  These proofs were accomplished by letting the computer supplement the visual,
intuitive right side of the brain.  Cognitive computer graphics complements man's ability to
generate new knowledge. 
<P>Zenkin presented an interesting analogy to one of the latest technologies, virtual reality.  He
explained that virtual reality is to the physical as cognitive graphics is to the abstract--cognitive
graphics extends the virtual reality concept to the abstract.  In his presentation, Zenkin used
Figure 19 to draw this analogy between the physical and the abstract of cognitive graphics.
<P>
<B>Computer Cognitive Graphics</B>
<I>Figure 19</I>
<P>
<B>Conference Follow-On Research</B>
<P>
At the end of the cybernetics/ situational control conference two days were spent discussing
future collaboration with the Russians.  Several projects were chosen as follow-on efforts.  The
overall goal of these projects is to further understand and have demonstrated situational control
and its components.  The ultimate goal is to apply the concepts of situational control to American
problems of complex control.
<P>First American scientists need translations of the situational control literature.  This requires
translation of Russian works.  The following books were chosen:  A. Zenkin, Cognitive
Computer Graphics, 1991; D. Pospelov, Logico-Linguistic Models in Situational Control, 1981,
and G. Osipov, D. Pospelov, Semiotic Modeling, 1995.
Since this conference sparked interest in some of the American academics, it was decided that a
semiotic modeling and situational control workshop be planned as part of the Large Complex
Systems Workshop at the upcoming IEEE Conference.  This workshop will provide extensive
coverage of situational control.  The audience at this workshop should have a much broader
attendance from American academia.  
<P>Specific areas presented during the conference resulted in the following projects.  A natural
language interpreter will be demonstrated. This prototype interpreter converts natural language to
situational control language.  Much interest was generated by Prof. Zenkin's presentation on
Computer Cognitive Graphics.  Prof. Zenkin will port his software to state-of-the-art computers
and examine additional applications.  The Russians were asked about the relationship between
situational control and Complexity Theory being developed at the Santa Fe Institute.  A paper
will be developed exploring this question and a small workshop will be developed to explore this
issue.  Finally, white papers will be developed by the Russians on many of the topics discussed.
<P><B>Situational Control Summary</B>
<P>The key to the Russian approach to Situational Control is the integration of concepts and tools
from many disciplines.  The preceding topics--situational control language and cognitive
graphics--were just two examples of the tools that the Russians are integrating.  To accomplish
this integration, the Russians have used a team of scientists, each having expertise in the different
disciplines.  This team is led by Prof. Pospelov.  
<P>The disciplines brought together under situational control include systems control, artificial
intelligence, computer science, decision support, fuzzy logic, linguistics, modeling, and others. 
Comments provided by American professors who attended the conference highlight the potential
of the Russian multidisciplinary approach.  One made the comment (after hearing the overview
of situational control presentation) that each of the boxes used in the presentation diagrams
represented entire fields of study in the United States.  Each of the separate fields of study hold
conferences which focus on much narrower topics.  Problems arise when scientists from each of
these fields do not understand the other fields and do not interact with scientists from the other
disciplines to tackle hybrid fields such as situational control.  Another professor supported this
view and explained that situational control was a combination of systems control and artificial
intelligence--intelligent control.
<P>Thus, there is much in common between the tools and techniques used in Russian situational
control and the tools and techniques used in Western sciences, such as artificial intelligence.  
However, more work is required to move past the differences in language and terminology to
fully determine the potential for situational control.  Clearly, the multidisciplinary approach
taken by the Russians is worth further research.

<HR>
