<TITLE>Cybernetics-Conclusion</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY
BACKGROUND="backgrnd/vbar2.gif" BGCOLOR="#C0C0C0" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#551A8B" ALINK="#0000FF" LEFTMARGIN="0" TOPMARGIN="0">
<P><A HREF="index.html"><IMG
SRC="images/torcher2.gif" ALT="Return to AEF Home Page" ALIGN="TOP" BORDER="0" VSPACE="0" HSPACE="12" WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="59"></A>

<IMG
SRC="images/library.gif" ALIGN="TOP" VSPACE="16" HSPACE="18" WIDTH="345" HEIGHT="34">
</P>
<P><IMG
SRC="backgrnd/spacer.gif" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="1000" HSPACE="26" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="4"></P><HR><H3 ALIGN=center>Improved Air Campaign Planning Through Cybernetics and Situation Control </H3>
<P><CENTER><B>by David R. Stinson</B></CENTER><HR>

<H4>CONCLUSIONS/RECOMMENDATIONS</H4>
<P>
The growth of information technology is phenomenal.  The Air Force is definitely in the
information age.  Taking advantage of all the technology of the information age provides huge
benefits as well as huge challenges.  One of the challenges which seems to grow at a very fast
pace is how to deal with the vast amounts of information made available to decision makers from
all the advances of the information age.  For the Air Force, this challenge manifests itself most
importantly in how to transform data into information and sift through the information to make
the extremely important planning and execution decisions required in combat.  The level at
which the most help is needed in this area is the operational/campaign level.  It is one of the most
complex decision making levels and stands to benefit the most from improvements.
<P>Russian situational control should be further studied by the Air Force to evaluate its utility as an
approach to improve control and decision making for Air Force combat at the
operational/campaign level.
<P>Cybernetics provides a framework to address this problem.  Air combat can be viewed as a
complex control problem.  Without question, complexity is a prominent characteristic of warfare,
and information is a resource to resolve this complexity.  "Cybernetics studies the flow of
information around a system, and the way in which that information is used by the system as a
means of controlling itself." 47 There is nothing magical or new in cybernetics.  Rather, the
concepts of feedback and control which define cybernetics have been around for a long time. 
The key is to recognize the importance of building control systems that provide the feedback fast
enough to aid decision makers.  Changes in the world political environment have made the world
much less predictable and more complex.
<P>So, if the answer is to implement better feedback control systems to improve decision making,
then, how it this done?  Or, what technologies can be employed to implement such systems? 
This paper looked at the Russian use of situational control.  The sciences and technologies that
the Russians are using to implement control of complex systems in a variety of requirements (to
include military), are the same as those used in the West.  They include artificial intelligence,
control, modeling, fuzzy logic, and others.  One aspect of the Russian approach stands out--the
merging of all these disciplines into the area called situational control.  A multidisciplinary
approach is necessary when addressing multidimensional problems. 
<P>This leads to the first recommendation. Russian situational control should be further studied by the Air
Force to evaluate its utility as an approach to improve control and decision making for Air Force
combat at the operational/campaign level.  This research should be conducted as a joint effort
with representatives from the operational, scientific, command, control, communications and
computer (C4), and intelligence communities.  Air Combat Command and Air Force Operations
have a vested interest in anything that has the potential to improve operational planning and
execution of the air battle.  Both Rome and Armstrong Laboratories have expertise in the
disciplines such as artificial intelligence.  Other support areas that have a major role in
information warfare--Intelligence and C4 Systems--should be represented in this effort.  Any
work to pursue this should be a joint effort with the other military services.  The potential of
situational control, if reached, is equally applicable to each service.  As has been already
mentioned, the Army is interested as evidenced by research projects they have initiated. 
Additionally, other organizations have displayed interest--the Defense Intelligence Agency and
US Central Command.
<P>The integration of many disciplines to build situational control seems to be the most unique
contribution of the Russian work.  However, the efforts in the individual areas may also provide
new scientific information.  For example, Zenkin's work in cognitive graphics stirred a great
amount of interest in both the academic and the military people present at the cybernetics
conference.  
<P>The second recommendation is to build on the relationship established with the Russian
delegation of scientists.  There is a vast amount of knowledge and talent available to the United
States in Russian science.  Not only has the end of the cold war made this accessible to us, but
the current state of affairs in Russia and with Russian science, in particular, has created an
environment where Russian scientists are looking for opportunities to share their knowledge and
talent.  It is not clear how long such an environment will last.  At a minimum, Air Force
representatives should participate in the follow-on work efforts that resulted from the
cybernetics/situational control conference, such as the upcoming IEEE Conference.
If situational control lives up to its promise, processing and analysis of data to provide timely
feedback can improve decision making and provide substantial gains in warfighting capability.
The third recommendation, which is related to the others, is to include the study of situational
control in the new Information Warfare arena.  The area of situational control fits into that part of
Information Warfare that provides "actionable" information.  If situational control lives up to its
promise, processing and analysis of data to provide timely feedback can improve decision
making and provide substantial gains in warfighting capability.  A major information warfare
goal in is to use information to get inside the opponent's decision cycle and, if possible, control
his behavior with means short of combat.
<HR>
