<HEAD>

<TITLE>Byte City: Life After the Big Change -- PFF</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>


<h2>Byte City:</h2>
<I><B>or,</B></I>
<P>
<I><B>Life After the Big Change</B></I>
<P>
by <a href="/pff/people/sfellow.html#Vlahos">Michael Vlahos</a>
<P>
<blockquote>
<I>Long day.  Ache all over.</I>  She had already kicked off her
shoes.  <I>Where's the boy?  His city screen should be on.  As
soon as learning time's up, he's all over the back streets.</I>
 But she just wants to lie back in her bed, turn to her favorite
stage door hangout;  not join, just watch.  The day was rough.
 Rush delivery behind schedule just because one in a box of tomato
cubes was bruised.  Lying back, she reaches for the navpad.  <I>My
favorite place or something different?</I>  She subscribes to
several byte cities, Metro Disney, Main Street, Maple Avenue,
Opreyville, The Village, City on the Hill (strictly for Sundays),
and even Downtown USA.  <I>Take the keys to our city!  Downtown
USA!  Yeah, it was the biggest, but what a zoo!  Metropolis was
the kinkiest, better save that for Saturday night.</I>  So she
opts for the less stressed out fun of TBA [The Big Apple].  She
cranks up the City Screen;  <I>make it early evening</I>.  The
whole wall, an enormous living rendition of Monet's <I>Water Lilies</I>,
dissolves like fine rain into a great central square.  Times Square.
 But this is not the tired, seedy theme park of today.  No, this
is the halcyon Times Square of the last century!
<P>
<I>Yeah, this was cool.  All that old neon.  City lights!</I>
 She steered herself to a chrome yellow checker, told the agent
where to take her.  AI Agents came with the service, of course.
 Part of being a full citizen of the Big Apple.  She was off,
peering without craning her neck, at the fantasia of old New York,
sort of circa 1939, more fetidly baroque than any single imagination
could ever have encompassed ... spires and ziggurats and lurid
Babylonian bronze entablature, bigger and wilder than any made
by history and humankind.  But she, and a 22 percent share for
this time period, was bedazzled. <I>125th Street, The Apollo --
I'm here!</I>  
</blockquote>
<P>
Welcome to the fourth life of the American city:  our new urban
world;  America after the Big Change.  <I><B>Byte City!</B></I>
<P>
Not science fiction.  Not prediction.  Not the future -- Just
a way of talking about how we get there.  Because getting there
means that something <B>Big </B>happens.  People will exclaim:
 <I>It's a revolution!</I>
<P>
Well, if it's a revolution, then Big Change means upheaval.  Revolution
cannot be rouged and face-lifted into pretty Progress.  Revolution
is not mere improvement.  Revolutions are upendings.  Old ways
actually lie down and die right at our feet, like statues of Louis
or Lenin.
<P>
Everyone says we are living in such a time.  Look at their big
titles for Big Change:  Toffler talks <I>Third Wave</I>, or Drucker's
orotund <I>Transformation of American Life</I>.  But then, nothing
dreadful happens.  Nothing even fantastic happens.  Tomorrow is
wonderful, different, difficult, but a lot like today.  Only more
so, like a straight line on a chart.  And problems?  <I>Weeell</I>,
they can be <I>managed</I>.
<P>
But revolution will force on us the integrity of destruction.
 We can pretend that everything will stay the same even as everything
changes, but revolution will not listen.  Fortunately.
<P>
If this is revolution beginning to hit, then let's talk about
the real thing. That is the reason for <I>Byte City</I>.  Byte
City meets the acid strip dip of Big Change.  It's big enough
to change our lives like the last Big Change.  Remember:  The
<I>Industrial</I> Revolution?  It blew the old world apart, it
made a new one, and it gave us new life.
<P>
And we still think of it as Modern.  Well, get over it.  It's
now the oldest old order around.  Not just <I>Rust Belt</I>, but
<I>Big City</I>, <I>Edge City</I>, the Paramus Mall too.  Dead,
Dead, Dead.  Byte City is a way to kill the old world in our minds
before it's torn up right in front of us.  Byte City is a way
to get to change as big as coal, steam, pig iron, and iron rails
wrought right where we live.
<P>
That wall-plastering, flat-panel <I>virtu-screen</I> is a portal
into a new urban world.  Our gut tells us that this tool literally
pries open a door into a new way of life.  Thinking it through
is like asking a Scot in 1775:  <I>Tell us about the railroad.</I>
<P>
Would he have said:  <I>Sure:  iron horse, new net of cities belching
smoke, it's all coming, I can see it.  O yeah</I>.
<P>
Or would he scratch his head, squint, and say: <I> Sure would
make stagecoaches faster, if they could go on rails.  Heavier
loads too, easier for drays to haul.  But the teams would need
good gravel beds, or they might bust their hooves.</I>
<P>
Byte City's one cut at the time traveler's question to us.  We
might not do any better than our Scottish cousin, but at least
we have his revolution as guide.  The upheaval that would revvv
up <I>his</I> lifetime helps us see the roar that is already growling
in our <I>own</I>.  <I>Byte City</I> is a metaphor of revolution
<I>now</I> we can stack up against revolutions <I>then</I>:
<P>
Like the one that hit Britain after 1815, and the United States
after 1876.  And they help us look ahead because they happened
to people like us.
<P>
<U><I>They are us</I></U>:  near in time, same in space.
<P>
Kinship helps, because we can watch how they got through it, and
we can pace ourselves.  Big Change is history's gauntlet.  We
have to get through it too.
<P>
So their stories may be our own.  But still ours to tell.  Technology
hits, but <U><I>we</I></U> do the transformation;  <U><I>we</I></U>
make the moves;  <U><I>we</I></U> do the change.
<P>
And it all seems to start after big wars of ideas, big heroic
journeys;  finished, only to find a new one has begun, for
<ul>
<B>Britain</B> after the <I>Napoleonic Wars</I>.
<P>
<B>The United States</B> at the end of <I>Reconstruction</I>.
<P>
<B>And us</B>, after the <I>Cold War</I>.
</ul>
<center><B>*.*.*.*.*</B></center>
<P>
<br>
<center>
<I><B>Take me away to paradise</B></I>
<br><I><B>I'm so dammed bored</B></I>
<br><I><B>   ...</B></I>
<br><I><B>Peel me off this velcro seat</B></I>
<br><I><B>  and get me moving</B></I>
<P>
<I><B>--GreenDay</B></I>
</center>
<P>
Start with <I><B>The Driver</B></I>.  <I>Iron horse, locomotive,
train</I>:  The railroad drove change.  And it was more than change's
tool.  It worked into our brain as song and story and myth.  It
became the industrial world's kinetic cathedral.
<P>
Because it had the raw power of faith.  <B>It was the god of destruction</B>.
 Steam was a juggernaut where worshippers of <I>The Modern</I>
threw down their old world, to be crushed under its wheels.  <B>It
was the icon of power</B>. The railroads reeked the highest octanes
of power, Apollo Program stuff, done by billionaire barons and
tycoons.  <B>It was the layer down of judgment</B>.  Its terrible
mix of underworld and the machine--belching cinders, its engine
roaring through the night--told all that <I>The Modern</I> had
no room for the sentimentality of old ways of life [Didn't DOS
do the same?  We, the new, sneered at the pathetic losers who
needed an interface to play].
<P>
But what did the rails make possible?  They made the new city;
 they raised it up as the main place, the place we lived.  People
and industry were joined, and trapped, in bleak sites of mutual
need.  And the rails brought us there.
<P>
And it was, truly, transformation.  The railroad's impact immediately
and visibly moved peoples' lives.  A plaintive cry from the <I>The
Nation</I>, in 1873:
<center><P>
<I>The locomotive is coming in contact with the very framework
of our institutions ...</I>
</center><P>
Contact.  Like the great host of a plague bacillus, or a horde
of lepers.  The end of small town America, Erie Canal America
... <I>&quot;low bridge, coming to a town ... &quot;</I>
<P>
And how it swarmed!  It was fast.  We're so proud of our burn
cycle for CPUs.  But the speed burn of change in last-century
US and Britain should wipe that smirk clean off.  The entire rail
net of Britain was built in just fifteen years, from 1841 to 1855.
 After the Civil War, from 1865 to 1873, thirty thousand miles
were laid here.  Life transformed in the span of one young adulthood.
<P>
Charles Francis Adams, old elite, 1868, clothed his shock in romantic
metaphor, back after five years in the Court of St. James:
<center>
<P>
<I>Had we been Tyrian traders of the year 100 BC landing from
a galley fresh from Gibraltar, we could hardly have been stranger
or the shore of a world, so changed from what it had been ten
years before.</I>
<P>
</center>
His old city was gone.
<P>
<center><B>*.*.*.*.*</B></center>
<P>
<br>
<br>
<center>
<I><B>Swarming City,</B></I>
<br><I><B>City of Dreams ... </B></I>
<br>
<I><B>--Baudelaire</B></I>
<P>
<I><B>Is it concrete all around</B></I>
<br><I><B>Or is it in my brain?</B></I>
<br><I><B>--David Bowie</B></I>
</center>
<P>
And what was the city?  It was:  <I><B>Where We Live</B></I>.
 Think sentimental, think Adams' Beacon Hill;  then think what
took its place.  You have just defined <I>revolution</I>.  Because
revolution made a new city, and the new city was the place where
peoples' lives were upended as they entered.  The city stripped
off old identity.  People naked of meaning jostled and elbowed
their way, packed together in brick and cobbled isometric planes,
until they found something new.  Migrations to the new cities
threw whole worlds together, cramming entire tribes into tenements
by the 7th Avenue El.  Forget the old romance of the bazaar, the
ancient trade city's waterfront teeming with Lascars, Phoenicians,
Tartars, and Greeks.
<P>
That was original city, <I>entrepot</I> city.  Trade made, on
river and sea-nexus, like London or New York.  From its hub spoked
the hinterland network of villages and towns.  How different was
the new net of industrial urbs!  Take a classic of its kind, Springfield,
Ohio. At its height, home for 80,000.  Springfield was a local
industrial hub anchored by three big national plants:  Crowell-Collier,
International Harvester, and Robbins and Myers.  And what remained
of the old agricultural world of Clark County brought its bounty
there in homage to the new city, to the farmer's market in the
neo-Romanesque city hall, stone tower shining city pride just
like 15th century Siena or Bologna.  Oak-shaded Wittenburg was
its civilization-badge, with a football team Ronald Reagan could
have played on, while oysters on ice came every morning by those
rails, fresh from Chesapeake Bay.
<P>
America's whole world was wired by railroad;  cities wired within
by streetcars, and wired without into a national network of cities,
with the former <I>entrepot</I> cities now grown to giant <I>metropoli</I>:
 Chicago, New York, LA.  If we think of the city as a node in
the network of our lives, it is the merest step of imagination
to see what <I>Byte City</I> will be for us.
<P>
The big screen of <I>Byte City</I>, ten or twenty years from now,
is today's railroad, today's god of destruction and creation.
 The railroad was <I>force majeure</I> in English:  it moved people
to the city, moved in goods they wanted, and moved out goods they
made.  The virtu-screen doesn't move anything ... but it brings
everything to us.  The city is in our living room, or wherever
we want it to be.  The portal becomes a vehicle, and like the
railroad before, <I>&quot;it is coming into contact with the very
framework&quot;</I> of our lives.
<P>
<center><B>*.*.*.*.*</B></center>
<P>
<br>
<br>
<center>
<I><B>Two times and it has rendered me</B></I>
<br><I><B>Punch drunk and without bail</B></I>
<br><I><B>Think I'd be safer all alone</B></I>
<br><I><B>Flies in the vaseline we are</B></I>
<br><I><B>--Stone Temple Pilots</B></I>
</center>
<P>
So then the next piece of Big Change:  <I><B>Loss of Order and
Connectedness</B></I>.  The new net clung to the heels of the
rails:  Life cobbling to the factories clustering around each
new depot.  People poured into them, searching first for jobs,
and then for a sense of belonging.  Migrants from farm to slum
could not bring with them their own old net of traditions, the
rooted weave of relationships that was small town America.
<P>
Small town America was our mythic heart.  As Robert Weibe tells
it,
<ul>
&quot;small-town life was America's norm in the mid-seventies
<I>[1870s].</I>  Groups of these towns fell into satellite patterns
about a larger center <I>[the entrepot]</I>, to which they looked
for markets and supplies, credits and news.  But however much
they actually relied upon an outside world, they still managed
to retain the sense of living largely to themselves.  With farms
generally fanning around them, these communities moved to the
rhythms of agriculture: the pace of the sun's day, the working
and watching of the crop months, the cycle of the seasons.&quot;
</ul>
Alien.  Weird.  Wild.  New cities broke rhythm itself by busting
the rule of order.  Nature's rules now knelt to human imagination.
 Cities of wonder -- and inescapable wonderment only added to
their sense of <I>anomie</I>.  It was easier for migrants to take
the filth, disease, and toxicity of the new net than the squeeze
of a reality overwhelming and fantastical.  New building systems
of iron made easy Neo-Classical fantasies that Palladio could
but have dreamed of:  symbolized in Britain by the Crystal Palace
of Victoria's heyday;  then, in America, by the Skyscraper, the
<I>El</I>, and endless canyons of steel.  The landscape itself
disoriented in its strangeness,.  It was both harsh and dreamlike,
as in T. S. Eliot's image from <I>The Wasteland</I>:  &quot;<I>unreal
city, under the brown fog of a winter dawn ...&quot;</I>
<P>
We have all read stories of the city's capacity for <I>anomie</I>:
 like my grandfather coming to New York as a boy, hawking fruit
and flopping in a tenement room with twenty others on the lower
East Side; then the rails to Springfield for a job, and ending
up in the wrong Springfield:  Ohio, not Massachusetts.  There
are so many unspoken stories about those times embedded in our
minds, in the place where myth resides.
<P>
But people could make the warp from farm to factory, cabin to
tenement.  Living conditions and physical alienation were not
the problem:  loss of identity was.  Loss of connection hurt when
people were torn, not from the soil, but from their own defining
labor, the worth that came from work.  For example, the industrial
revolution savaged the place of the craftsman in society.  Pittsburgh,
known before 1860 as the &quot;Craftsman's Empire,&quot; became
in just twenty years a kingdom of steel, where labor replaced
craft.  And the furnaces offered no status equal to what was lost.
<P>
What had been lost was identity itself.  The new world of the
assembly line seemed to reduce men and women to mere auxiliaries
of the machine.
<P>
<center><B>*.*.*.*.*</B></center>
<P>
<br>
<br>
<CENTER><I><B>Take, if you want a slice</B></I>
<br><I><B> If you want a piece</B></I>
<br><I><B> If it feels alright</B></I>
<P>
<I><B>     Don't come over here </B></I>
<br><I><B>       And piss on my gate </B></I>
<br><I><B>          Save it just keep it </B></I>
<br><I><B>                    Off my wave     </B></I>
<P>
<I><B>--Soundgarden</B></I></CENTER>
<P>
Call this a problem of <I><B>More Money, Less Meaning</B></I>.
 Our soft, clean mind mode cringes before their cities of disease
and death.  Death rates in Britain stayed the same from 1820 to
1870, even though life expectancy was soaring in the countryside.
 Why?  Because city air and water was killing so many.  A Southern
slave in 1850 lived twenty years longer than the average Northern
industrial worker.  But that Northerner just shrugged.  Farm life
scraped hard too.
<P>
They liked the money.  Wages were higher in the new cities.  For
young men freed from the farm, <U>a lot more money</U>.  For example,
real wages in U.S. industry grew more than 40 percent between
1865 and 1873.  People could put up with the crazed atmosphere
of the this world:  the weltering, roiling, pinball pulse of the
new city.  They could put up with the disorientation, and they
could put up with the physical abuse.  Because they had more money,
they believed their quality of life was improving.
<P>
Ah, but then come &quot;depressions.&quot;  <I>The Panic of 1873!</I>
 Progress was replaced by uncertainty.  And uncertainty exploded:
<P>
<center>
<I>Will I be paid a good wage, will I be able to raise a family
in a decent place, will I be treated with dignity for what I do?</I>
</center>
<P>
A wave of depressions followed fast on industry's tide.  They
banged home the brittleness of industrial identity.  Lay-off,
throw out -- <I>You'll work for this, right?</I> -- because new
labor had no given status.  Society had no rules, no custom and
taboos, to regulate the new.  Sure, craftsmen and farmers had
stature and place in the old order of things, but this was waning
work.  No one knew what status to give the new work.
<P>
Money is only a parts-maker for status.  Money is always there,
pieces in the machine of meaning:  a badge of rank, a tool of
display;  but cash only helps make the whole work.  Identity is
a mysterious endowment of society.  Money is no substitute.  Money
can prop up identity in doubt, but only for a time.  People need
to know where they stand with each other.
<P>
So money propped up status in the new work -- for a while.  But
when the market cracked, so to did the identity of the new worker.
 Kicked out of work, wages cut;  arbitrary, brutal signs that
told the new workers:  <I>you are no longer what you were</I>.
 <I>Maybe you are no better than a slave</I>.  And old social
compacts were torn up across all old divides.  What happened to
farmers and craftsmen also happened to yesterday's middle management:
nostalgia's fat, jolly traders who thronged the <I>entrepot</I>
cities and fed the small towns.
<P>
Big change ripping up old meaning lived on in folk songs and literature
alike.  Then our memory of the trauma condensed down to a few
quaint characters  What happened to John Henry?  What happened
to Old Fezziwig?
<P>
What happened to them is the story of a <B>spike</B>.  The total
the Big Change --  the transformation -- took decades, but the
stories come out of a time when a single generation took the main
hit.  Before that, change was being accommodated.  Sure, you could
see the stretch marks, but it was still the same old place.  Things
kept changing and changing and changing ... and then ... then
it was suddenly a whole new place.
<P>
<I>Where am I?</I>  This is the spike.  It hits one generation;
they are the <I>before and after</I> people.  Theirs is the moment
of crisis, they are the ones who make the psychic passage from
one world to another.
<P>
The crisis is not physical.  It is not about problems like pollution
or plagues or panics.  The crisis is about a mind jump.  And there
is one group that just can't make it:
<P>
The Old Order. The Ruling Class.  The Elite.
<P>
Whatever the <I>Blue Book</I> cut is on who runs things, throw
it out.  Throw out the book too.  Because establishments are all
about staying <I>established</I>.  When Big Change happens and
they can't see it, they become <I>dis-.</I>
<P>
They still have power.  Sure, like Gorbachev's generals still
had tanks.  Thousands of them.  <U>They had power, but they did
not have authority</U>.
<P>
And authority is about belief.  Elites get to be elites because
people believe in them, and they believe in their ideas.  All
Old Orders were once New Ideas told by people with fire in their
eyes.  And their message was simple:  we know where we are all
going, and we can get you there.  These people become the new
elite because the majority of <I>all the people</I> believe them.
<P>
Elites fail because they forget this is why they are there.  They
come to think that they are there to preserve a world <U>where
they rule</U>.  They come to speak only to themselves, and, while
change is roaring through society, the only people who still believe
them are themselves.  Worse for them, they come to think that
self-belief is what authority is all about.
<P>
And that is when they really lose it.
<P>
<CENTER><B>*.*.*.*.*</B></CENTER>
<P>
<br>
<br>
<center>
<I><B>Who set the standard? Born to be rich?</B></I>
<br><I><B>Such fine examples,.. skinny little bitch,..</B></I>
<br><I><B>Model, role model, some models in blood,..</B></I>
<br><I><B>Get some flesh to stick, so they look like us,..</B></I>
<br><I><B>--Pearl Jam</B></I>
</center>
<P>
History always remembers the moment when a ruling society discovers
it can no longer rule, because it has lost the belief of its people:
 the moment that  <I><B>Old Ideas [and Elites] Lose Authority</B></I>
<P>
How do old elites come to fail in the face of Big Change?  They
make four big mistakes:
<P>
<ul>
<I><B>R</B>uling Elites cannot see the change, in part because
it hits right after a period of triumph for them, a time when
their own authority has been unquestioned.</I>
<P>
<I><B>W</B>hen faced with change, elites try to deny what is happening.</I>
<P>
<I><B>W</B>hen the change cannot be held off, ruling elites try
to control, or &quot;manage&quot; change to preserve their position.</I>
<P>
<I><B>W</B>hen the handwriting is on the wall, many among the
elite embrace the new vision, ensuring survival for many ...</I>
<P>
</ul>
... but it is too late for Old Elite society as a whole. The irony
of it all is that the unraveling begins at the moment the ruling
elite is least disposed to accept it.  It happens at the moment
of their triumph.
<P>
Look at the British ruling class after 1815.  23 years fighting
Napoleon ... now <I>Boney</I> was finally doing time on St. Helena.
 Five coalitions it took to do him in;  an Iliad of a war.  But
when it was done, the British latifundial elite -- you know, rolling
estates and country &quot;homes&quot; big as Versailles -- owned
the world, superpower-care-free as a fox hunt.  And right then,
that instant, it all began to strip itself away.  Why?  Because
the entire energy and effort of British society, of British life,
had come to be written as a great struggle.  The elite's bible
was Bonaparte, where he was the Devil of change and upheaval.
 So when he was banished at last, the ruling class thought:  <I>We
have conquered change itself!</I>  Could they just imagine that
by beating Boney, they would lose their last claim on control
of their own?  <I>No</I>. Their world was swirling around them,
and they thought -- <I>wonder of wonders!</I> -- that their authority
was never more majestic.  Double false pride.
<P>
The same thing was true of the United States, which had just fought
its own foreign war.  It happened to be against our own people,
<I>The South</I>.  Like a well-lathered 16-part miniseries, it
wasn't just a war.  It started in the 1850s, with the rise of
Radical Republicanism.  There was Bleeding Kansas, Abe Lincoln's
election, John Brown's body, the Big Bang Battle Hymn of the Republic.
 And after Appomatox, the saga continued.  Crusading war dissolved
into crusading politics:  the uplifting of the wicked called <I>Reconstruction</I>.
 Good <I>vs.</I> Evil, national energy tasked to ideology, and
speechifying leaders -- for 20 years, from 1856 to 1876, we had
our own Iliad.  While gilt-edged Brit elite sang <I>See the Conquering
Hero Comes!</I>, ours claimed emotional authority from <I>The
Union Forever!</I>  Serial melodrama, year after year, was the
elite theater of authority.
<P>
Cold War sound familiar now?  Was Washingtonian strutting any
different, gloating in its <I>End of History</I> triumphalism?
 Call <I>Johnny Reb</I> and<I> Jean Crapaud</I> bad miniseries,
but they had <U>action</U>.  Cold War was plain bad soap opera.
 Like<I> General Hospital</I>, it got very tedious, lapsing in
the end into a stream of mock crises and snore summits.  But the
Sponsors loved it.  And why not?  The Soviet Union had settled
in like welfare squatters on the first floor of American life.
 Commies consumed attention, they sanctioned elite power.  What
could be more important than 50,000 nukes in your face?
<P>
Fifty years should have ratified forever;  but then, suddenly,
it all went away.  And since then, America has suffered the sordid
spectacle of a ruling elite desperately trying to justify its
right to rule on one hand, while PC-bullying the rest of us to
keep taking orders on the other.
<P>
And while that old elite spent the early 1990s in earnest gush
that America would not make it without more elite control -- <I>We're
in economic decline, we need an industrial policy!  We need to
run the world or it will be a mess!  We need national health care!</I>
-- the rest of society was moving toward the first act of revolution.
<P>
Elites make revolutions happen.  They are why we have revolutions
at all:  because elites try to postpone change.  And while they
get their <I>Best and Brightest</I> to tell us why change is bad,
or why it shouldn't happen unless they regulate it ... it happens.
<P>
And in order for it to happen, change has to overcome elite resistance.
 What old elites achieve is the opposite of what they want.  Their
resistance speeds up the very unraveling of authority that they
fear.  Boom!  They garrotte themselves.. We call the public execution:
 revolution.
<P>
Elites not only make revolution possible, <I>they are its midwives</I>.
<P>
<CENTER><B>*.*.*.*.*</B></CENTER>
<P>
<br>
<br>
<center>
<I><B>Power Lord</B></I>
<br><I><B>Voice cuts like a sword</B></I>
<br><I><B>Black Knight</B></I>
<br><I><B>Ruler of the Hoard</B></I>
<br><I><B>Crowd Roars</B></I>
<br><I><B>As I take my place</B></I>
<br><I><B>Attitude rude dude</B></I>
<br><I><B>--Snap</B></I>
</center>
<P>
So the next movement:  <I><B>Old Elites Fail, New Do Not Lead</B></I>.
<P>
But what does elite failure look like?  Elite failure doesn't
mean inevitable tumbrels and a Terror.  The erosion of the old
order and its authority rushes toward a series of happenings that
end the sway of the old ruling elites, and usher in a period without
leadership.  Those who have made economic revolution are not like
the old order they unseat.  They are not the bureaucrats who rise
to high estate as <I>Masters of the Job Description</I>.  Their
roughshod power comes from making things happen, not trying to
stop them.  That is why their Homeric title would be <I>Breakers
of Bureaucrats, </I>because that is what they do while they make
change happen.  They don't know anything about creating a new
system, they would howl at the prospect of <I>going into government</I>.
 They would say:
<P>
<blockquote>
<I>Let a new path emerge naturally from the new world.  You can't
force a new path.  That's exactly why the old order failed.  They
tried to hold back change.  And if holding back change was the
problem, then change itself is the solution.  The old won't work,
but everything new will.</I>
</blockquote>
<P>
Makers of economic revolution are the necessary agents of change,
but not necessarily the new leaders of society.  Aged elites in
both Britain and the United States flunked the leadership test
when upheaval hit hardest.  Everyone could see that those in charge
blew it.  But the new enterprisers who spearheaded revolution
also failed.  Omission, not commission -- but still failure. 
The standard was theirs to hold.  They just failed to pick it
up.
<P>
The United States and Britain then snagged in midstream, lodged
on a mudbank period of drift in politics, juxtaposed crazily with
the roaring whitewater energies of economic change.  The result:
 the disorder and disconnectedness in peoples lives grew.  Society
itself seemed about to fall apart, while old <I>and</I> new elites,
fearful of the outcome, twitched feebly, with some shaky rattling
of armed authority from above. 
<P>
But feeble gestures only lashed the alienation of the rest from
ruling elites that had squandered their authority.
<P>
How did the elite fail in Britain?  The gentry made a good start
by ignoring what was happening.  Few were actually involved in
business.  There were no landed people who were also corporate
owners in Parliament in 1820, or in 1830.  More tied in with business
as the revolution gathered steam, but gently.  <I>I have  a nephew
in business;  I'm a barrister, you know</I>.  A few might sit
on a corporate board somewhere.  But they let the world pass them
by.  The new Barons--as in Beer Barons, known as <I>The Beerage</I>--were
knocking on the temple doors.
<P>
Then they went out and undercut themselves in style.  If any figure
helped to delegitimate the old order, it was George IV.  Call
him <I>The Prince of Pleasure</I>; let him prove it at 96-course
meals.  Let his friend Beau Brummel offer the only gift of his
regime to society:  the starched collar.
<P>
And this ruling class didn't even try to wonk -- they just let
their policies plain fail.  The politics of that old order are
remembered in the union workhouses, the poorhouse, debtors' prisons,
Luddite loom-smashing, and Redcoats firing on the crowd at Peterloo.
 But political failure was in Britain a far cry from political
fall.  Taking gentry power apart took more than a generation.
 You don't remember?  That's the trouble.  It's so far away now,
like looking at life through dark historical mica.
<P>
The United States?  What failure here?  The pearl of Radical Republicanism
was ground down in the embarrassments of, and backlash against,
a forever unfinished, internal war of ideology.
<P>
Forever repression of the South was failing.  It was failing because
of exhaustion and recognition:  exhaustion over the strain of
beating down our own Reb face in the mirror;  and recognition
that its goals <I>could not</I> be achieved [and so many in the
North, sadly, who did not want them to be achieved].
<P>
But there were <I>undercurrents</I> too, and the undercurrants
that helped kill Reconstruction were more interesting.  Among
them was a gathering in the gut that the <I>Grapes of Wrath</I>
elite -- who had blazed to trample Rebel vineyards -- was giving
way to a group of New Men, <I>Organization Men</I> of the Grant
Administration who cared nothing for America's soul, but plenty
for promises of patronage, and the river of rewards from the new
<I>machine politics</I>.
<P>
And this replacement-Republican elite resisted the claims of the
thronging new workers of the industrial cities.  But the workers
kept claiming, pushed by economic &quot;panic&quot; and depression.
 Their champions began to talk about something called a &quot;moral
economy,&quot; and Ira Steward wrote that<I> &quot;something of
slavery&quot;</I> remained in the North.
<P>
What happened in America in the later 1870s was that the crusading
vision that created Reconstruction was coming home.  It was no
longer held aloft by an elite that once led the grand, rolling
bayonet charge down Cemetery Ridge;  but by regular people, people
who were now forced to defend themselves against the young changelings
of the righteous elite that so recently led them into battle.
<P>
<center><B>*.*.*.*.*</B></center>
<P>
<br>
<br>
<center>
<I><B>maybe afraid of it let's discredit it let's pick away at
it</B></I>
<br><I><B>I want to watch it come down</B></I>
<br><I><B>now doesn't that make you feel better?</B></I>
<br><I><B>the pigs have won tonight</B></I>
<br><I><B>--Nine Inch Nails</B></I>
</center>
<P>
There was a <I><B>Demand for New Meaning</B></I>.
<P>
People began to rebel against their own elite because they felt
betrayed by it, and the people were right.  Grant's New Men seized
fast advantage of industry's stripping of work's status.  And
where the elite firebrands of the 1850s would do anything to give
all Americans full citizenship, their young changelings of the
1870s fought to take it away from all but a few.  The Organization
Men feared full citizenship for all, because they feared it would
mean a workers' world:  the end of their own world.  But turning
on their old ideals, the Republican New Men set out on a corrosive
path, betraying their fathers, denying their heritage, and foretelling
their own, eventual fall.
<P>
Because demand for new meaning would not be denied;  someone was
going to come along and supply it.  And they would lay claim to
leadership.  But first, how was this demand expressed?
<P>
In Britain, early on, there were rural bonfires, from the Luddite
to the Captain Swing disturbances.  But these were the lashings
out of a dying countryside, futile and distant flares of things
to come.
<P>
The real demand could be felt as industry really took root in
Britain, with the migrations in full flood.  Unionism, and then
the Chartist movement were able in the 1840s to put real pressure
on the ruling elite, <I>through politics</I>.  The peoples' demand
-- politely put.
<P>
In the United States, it was more violent.  As Grant's New Men
rose to be <I>Robber Barons</I> in a <I>Gilded Age</I> [what a
turn of phrase on <I>Golden Age</I>!], they defended their civic
order, and their property, by building forts in the heart of every
city.  These arsenals still exist.  What were called armories,
were really castles, strongholds of the robber Barons.
<P>
They were thrown up after the labor rebellions --The Great Strike
of 1877.  They were there so the army and militia could drag out
the guns and sweep the streets.
<P>
Because everyone remembered the whole of Philadelphia's railroad
yards in flames.  If the railroad was the centerpiece of transformation,
the symbol of new elite power, then imagine the elite's shock
as they watched them burn into the night.  Out came the army,
the guns, the grapeshot ... Ergo, the armories.
<P>
And ergo, labor unions.  The number of major unions in America
went from 3 to 21 in the 1870s.
<P>
But as workers mobilized to fight against the elite, society slid
into crisis.  And what is <I>crisis</I>?  It is not <I>coming
apart</I>;  it is the dawning fear that we will unless ... 
<P>
Remember the mind jump from the old world to the new?  In the
gilded age we weren't making it;  and the longer it was ignored,
the harder, our gut said, it would be to get to the other side.
 As Henry Holt wrote in 1895:
<P>
<I>... the large majority of intellectual people </I>[read: elites]<I>
are peacefully sitting on a crust covering a mephitic chasm, or,
as many think, a volcano.</I>
<P>
It was a crisis that the absence of a ruling idea seemed to make
inevitable.
<P>
<CENTER><B>*.*.*.*.*</B></CENTER>
<P>
<br>
<br>
<center>
<I><B>Amazing Grace! how sweet the sound</B></I>
<br><I><B>That saved a wretch like me!</B></I>
<br><I><B>I once was lost, but now am found,</B></I>
<br><I><B>Was blind, but now I see.</B></I>
<br>--John Newton, 1831
</center>
<P>
And its absence for twenty years [<I>1876-1896</I>] became something
of a <I>desideratum</I>--the thing most wanted--in American life.
 Demand for new meaning went unfulfilled until <I><B>A Vision,
A Movement, and Order</B></I> came again to national life.
<P>
And not surprisingly,  it was found in elite form; that is, in
an elite that would lead.
<P>
And leadership meant religion.  Reaffirmation.  Religious revival
among American and British elites was a symbol to everyone else
that they could believe in elites again.  A bond of trust with
regular people was renewed.  But there was more.  Revival connected
personal religious calling to civic calling.  Individuals among
the renewed elite suddenly had authority again:  their voices
for reform rang true.  People got excited again.  People believed
again.  Things got done.
<P>
In Britain, this was called Methodism.  Methodist membership soared
in the decades after Wesley's death in 1791, from about 50,000
to more than 500,000 in 1840.  The important thing to know is
that Methodism became the religion of the new elite.
<P>
Methodism gave a new elite something far better than power:  moral
authority.  And this authority was not just put to the reform
of religion: the revolt of chapel [Methodism] against Church [the
ruling class' state religion].  Righteous Methodists brought their
reform faith to bear on all society.  They would cleanse a society
corrupted by Old Order thinking ... through modern thought.  They
would bring in universities and <I>&quot;institutes&quot;</I>
of expertise based on scientific methods.  Above all, they would
legitimate a <I>new class</I> of professionals, who could face
the problems of the world with an integrity [from the Latin <I>purity</I>.
 Clean!] given by reason and education.
<P>
The most important symbol of the new liberalism was the person
of the monarch herself.  The Georgian kings were the family heads
of their ruling society;  they represented the landed class and
their right to rule--and also, in George IV, their vanity, backwardness,
and profligacy.  Victoria, crowned just five years after the first
Reform Act, deliberately set a new course, where monarchy followed
reform, and by embracing it, decisively legitimated it.  Victoria,
in her person, embodied the new elite ethos.  Her sobriety, modesty,
and rectitude gave liberalism national authority.  Here was a
middle class, modern monarch, championing the new agenda of teetotalers,
social crusaders, and engineers.
<P>
And the idea of a democratic franchise gradually took root.  The
sway of the landed elite was worn away between the two reform
acts of 1832 and 1867, and the Beerage was co-opted into the new
spirit of the age.  The Corn Laws were repealed, and a ten-hour
work week was passed in 1841.
<P>
But getting to the new vision -- giving order to a chaotic transformation
in national life -- was long and hard-fought.
<P>
The vision was not even conceived until well after the initial
pulse of economic revolution, and no part of the new vision came
from the old order.  Nothing.  <I>Nada</I>.  And from the rollicking
new elites? -- A new way of life, a new context, a new physical
texture of existence.  But not meaning, not vision, and certainly
-- save for the same elites in their cozy brownstones -- not <I>order</I>.
<P>
The vision came out of a different elite that itself emerged as
individuals deserting both the old order elite and the new industrial
elite.
<P>
The Progressive movement renewed the American ruling class in
much the same way as Methodism led Britain's social revival, fifty
years later.  But our driving religious impulse was Presbyterianism,
offering a kind of Calvinist <I>noblesse oblige</I>, which gave
the early Progressives their high sense of order, determinism
and drive.
<P>
So much of Britain's reform was mirrored in America's elite revival:
<P>
<U><I>Temperance</I></U><I>:</I>  British <I>Teetotalism</I> transmuted
into our own, <I>Prohibition</I>;
<P>
<U><I>Anti-serfdom</I></U><I>:</I>  Not only a kindred lineage
from Wilberforce [<I>the Brit who stopped the slave trade</I>]
to Abolition, but a stretching of the anti-slavery metaphor to
industrial labor;
<P>
<U><I>The Rule of Reason</I></U><I>:</I>  From Bentham [<I>such
a modern guy he had himself stuffed and put on display in London
U., the place he founded</I>] and Britain's university surge,
to a skyrocketing of American engineering [<I>see below</I>] Ph.D.'s,
just before the Progressive era;  and,
<P>
<U><I>Administration by the Engineer</I></U><I>:</I>  The great
fairs in St. Louis and Chicago presaged the Progressive new wave,
just as the Great Exhibition of 1850 gave physical symbolism to
a new sense of order in British society.  Both built their vision
of progress on the physical mastery of the engineer <I>[hence,
the easy glide to &quot;social engineering&quot;].</I>
<P>
The Progressive movement had achieved its goals by 1920.  The
two <U><I>Time</I></U> cover men of the new generation, smooth
bringers of enlightened government and managed society, were Bernard
Baruch and Herbert Hoover.  Their gaze locked to a cloudless future.
<P>
But the nature of labor could not be jammed into an ordered dream
society.  One problem was the decline in agricultural jobs.  Farm
labor still nearly equaled manufacturing in 1900:  13 million
manual [industrial and related] workers, vice 11 million farm
laborers.  The broad swathe of what was now called &quot;white
collar&quot; was still small, at 5 million. 
<P>
Progressives had carefully crafted a world celebrating the worker,
where every American -- <I>as worker </I>-- could manufacture
their own American Dream.  The new managers expected that farm
labor would plummet as mechanized agriculture advanced.
<P>
What they did not anticipate was a decline in assembly line jobs.
 Not only were fewer and fewer needed in agriculture, but fewer
and fewer were needed to make things.  The obvious response was
to coax demand to keep pace with manufacturing efficiency.  Gone
would be the late-century terror of slumps and industrial surplus.
 Some say that to do this the managers created a cult of consumerism,
of ever-growing demand, to keep the workers' world going.  Sly
Pied Pipers!
<P>
But the Progressives' all-knowing vision seemed to crack and totter
after 1929.  The spiral into all-consuming depression could not
be managed;  the movement had failed.  But Progressive elite society
was unfazed by crisis.  It responded by turning on, and demonizing
the small-<I>c</I> conservatives among its own, those who had
run America since 1920.  And Herbert Hoover, master engineer,
became the gaunt-eyed icon of a vision that had failed because
of its conservatism.  The vision was not wrong; it had simply
not gone far enough.
<P>
Bad old Republican progressives had blown it because they let
the chaos of the market continue, but they <I>sinned</I> in believing
that private institutions could keep order and stability through
mere mediation.  It was not enough, the <I>Renewed Progressive</I>
said, for enlightened government just to regulate and advise;
 the state should intervene in the actual workings of society,
in order to insure progress and stay future catastrophe.
<P>
FDR did not bring revolution;  he found a way to renew peoples'
trust in the old elite -- <I>with a new face</I>.  His <I>Brain
Trust</I> borrowed the nicest-sounding tidbits from European social
democrats, but stayed true to the original Progressives' Presbyterian
patterns, especially the <I>noblesse oblige</I> part.  <I>Renewed
Progressives</I> wanted real government management of society,
but stopped short of advocating government ownership.  Their role
models were not gods nor fathers, but headmasters and ministers.
 The whole nation was their classroom and congregation.  They
would make things better -- manage industry right, give social
welfare to all, and coax an equality of outcome in American life
-- by preaching and instructing.
<P>
This elite makeover made sense to Americans.  Then world war actually
renewed emotional ties between people and their elites.  And World
War Two was a rip-snorting celebration of socialism.  The state
took over all our energies -- <I>they owned them!</I> -- for four
years, and they gave us a great adventure in return.  When Americans
came out into the sun and promises of peace, they gave FDR's brand
of progress their full faith and trust.
<P>
But there was no going back to the fervid installment consumerism
of the 1920s.  <I>Boy, but we could make!</I>  American workers
-- many of them women -- made everything world war demanded with
ease.  <I>And this</I> <I>with 12 million workers in uniform,
off the assembly lines</I>.  Recognition hit, at the moment of
the workers' world's biggest win, that the US was no longer for
workers only.
<P>
But we were still pretty creative:  we countered with a new class
of managers.  And a big new labor sector called &quot;management
services&quot; met two needs.  It allowed the economy to increase
total work, rather than rationing it <I>[meaning fewer jobs and
more social welfare]</I>, or reducing it <I>[meaning fractional
jobs for all].</I>
<P>
And much of this new work came with higher status.  This meant
that most millions of Americans could tie &quot;a better life
for our children&quot; to a promotion in <I>class</I>.  The GI
Bill made college the subsidized brass ring of the common man,
and college for all made us all <I>[eventually]</I> middle class.
 Upward mobility for all of us! What a concept!
<P>
This outward and upward expansion of labor unleashed a people
just past depression and war.  Full of pent-up demand for goods,
and, equally, full of pent-up expectations.  The elite had found
a way to meet them both.  Their seductive shibboleth:
<P>
<I>&quot;The American Dream.&quot;</I>
<P>
<CENTER><B>*.*.*.*.*</B></CENTER>
<P>
<br>
<br>
<center>
<I><B>&quot;Gee, Wally ...&quot;</B></I>
</center>
<P>
The new order worked like a big block <I>Chevy 454</I>.  And many
continued to believe that enlightened Government and the GI Bill,
had helped make it work.  In the 1950s and 60's, at belief's crest,
75% of Americans thought Government should help manage society.
<P>
LBJs <I>Great Society</I> was the floodtide of our faith in government.
<P>
What had been achieved?  The United States was no longer a worker's
world, it was now a middle class world.  In 1948, two-thirds of
Americans identified themselves as &quot;working class.&quot;
 By the 1960s, most said instead, &quot;middle class.&quot;  The
early TV sitcoms etched an indelible portrait of idealized American
life, a mythology now gathered under the collective mantle of
 <I>Leave It to Beaver</I>. [As nostalgic, <I>Nick at Nite</I>
Yuppies rush to embrace old sitcoms, they lay bare the same Old
Order reflex to revolution as Keats and Shelley lamenting a lost
countryside, or readers of <I>Tom Sawyer</I> and <I>Huckleberry
Finn</I> the demise of small town America].
<P>
People now lived in what academics would call <I>&quot;the mature
variation&quot;</I> of the industrial network of cities.  We called
it <I>suburbia</I>.  Auto and interstates made its sprawl possible,
and the sprawl itself made possible the big upstairs move in status
[for most].  The tract house and its passionste sidekick, the
white picket fence, was the campaign ribbon of a better life that
kept close people and their elites.
<P>
This was the third stage of urban America:  its life cramming
first into the strip shopping center, and then hitting its brief,
glittering zenith with <I>Edge City</I>, The Great American Mall.
 It is the place we still inhabit.  It is the mature end state
of classic industrial society.  It is a world that made room for
too-efficient manufacturing by creating a new management class
and service economy that soaked up the spilling excess of labor.
<P>
It all peaked around 1970.  That year, there were 40 million industrial-related
workers, only 2 million on the farm, and 38 million white collars
in America.
<P>
The new elites had brought order out of the chaos of industrialization.
 Their assembly line world worked.  First they rooted meaning
in the worker, then grafted on this social sod a middle class
world of management and services, living off its harvest.
<P>
Education and entertainment showed how well-oiled it all was.
 Education had become a machine designed to socialize and prepare
workers for an assembly line world, and managers for a world of
<I>pyramid-climbing</I>.  And new entertainment technologies were
harnessed to please and pacify.  Movies, radio, and television
-- unlike vaudeville and opera -- were based on a detached, objectified
relationship between artist and audience, and encouraged far more
passivity than traditional theaters.  And passive people make
controlling people very happy.
<P>
But now, no matter how smooth its control, the elite worried about
how to split up the still-shrinking pool of jobs.  And by jobs,
they meant <I>real</I> jobs.  And in industrial iconography, 
<I>real jobs</I> = <U>manufacturing</U>.  Real jobs would go away
because of -- dread word of that day -- <I>automation</I>.
<P>
This fear was an elite commonplace:  you could catch it in Kurt
Vonnegut's <I>Cat's Cradle</I>, or in high-tone, hard-back rags
like <I>Horizon</I>.  Look at Dennis Gabor's &quot;The Perils
of Leisure,&quot; from the Summer, 1964 issue -- the warm apogee
of the Great Society.  Productivity says Gabor, keeps growing
in the industrial world at a steady <I>x</I> percent, so high
that no social welfare spending can outpace it.  Eventually, said
the trendline, only the privileged would work.  The article's
substance, in fact, is in its opening cartoon, by David Levine.
 First, we see the bad old days, with working people in harness,
pulling a cigar-corpulent plutocrat on a wheeled palanquin.  Then,
we see tomorrow:  with happy mill workers playing cards on that
same, cushy float;  pulled now by three dapper, winking, Harvard
engineers.
<P>
The end of work itself was in sight:
<P>
<blockquote>
<I>For the first time in history we are now faced with the possibility
of a world in which only a gifted minority need work, to keep
the great majority in idle luxury.</I>
</blockquote>
<P>
This scene of the story ends here, in the mid-1960s, with elite
certainty that the engineering ethos -- managing the human condition
-- had triumphed.  The only problem they saw:  only the engineers
would have jobs.
<P>
But they were wrong.  Totally wrong.
<P>
How could they have been so far off the mark?
<P>
They took a straight line -- or like Gabor, just fondly cited
it as ever-truth -- and pushed it out.  All else stayed constant.
 What they overlooked, <I>or perhaps could not bring themselves
to believe</I>, was that human imagination itself was about to
change how the world worked.  New wealth and new jobs would be
created out of nothing:  <U><I>by creating new demand</I></U>.
 
<P>
This demand would be like the new demand created more than a century
before, at the beginning of industrial revolution.  The irony
for the now-aging elite was that their very success encouraged
innovation that would shake their world apart.  The Progressive
elites of late-20th century America made for themselves the same
predicament as the landed gentry of late-18th century Britain.
 Their wealth and ethos of improvement unwittingly set in train
the industrial revolution that would unseat them.
<P>
And this, Ladies and Gentlemen, is the roller-coaster of <I>our</I>
revolution heading toward its first plunge:
<P>
<I>The discovery of Byte City.</I>
<P>
<CENTER><B>*.*.*.*.*</B></CENTER>
<P>
<br>
<br>
<center>
<I><B>We've all heard a lot of talk about the Digital Age.</B></I>
<br><I><B>But what have we seen?</B></I>
<br><I><B>Here ends the hype ...</B></I>
<br><I><B>Television will never be the same again.</B></I>
<br><I><B>Enter the DSS system.</B></I>
<br><I><B>The DSS system will be on the cutting edge</B></I>
<br><I><B>  well into the next century.</B></I>
<br><I><B>--RCA ad, 1995</B></I>
</center>
<P>
&quot;Discovery&quot; means a burn-jump:  flash-link idea to technology.
 But we can't do that.  It's still too hard if Flashy ads can
trumpet TV [!!!] <I>as the future</I>.
<P>
<I><B>Humbug!</B></I>  We could demo the virtu-screen <I><B>&amp;</B></I>
Byte City <U>in five years</U>.
<P>
But maybe it doesn't matter whether we see, because we are stumbling
blind toward Byte City anyway through Big Money.  The coalitions
that will build Byte City have just been made.
<P>
And the big combos aren't waiting for the idea.  These are the
big alliances, the merging of corporate muscle in <I>tele-communications</I>
-- Bell South, Bell Atlantic, MCI -- with <I>entertainment </I>--
Disney, Time Warner -- with <I>software</I> -- Apple, Microsoft,
IBM -- and with the big <I>Cable</I> companies.  More than enough
to make <I>Byte City</I> happen ... when they finally figure it
out.
<P>
It doesn't matter that they are still fumbling with stagecoach
metaphors, when the railroad is waiting to be built.  It doesn't
matter that they still speak the language of <I>computer</I> and
<I>TV</I> and <I>telephone</I> and <I>Information Superhighway</I>
... when each one of these tools is poised on the crumbling edge
of historical oblivion.  It doesn't matter, because
<P>
Byte City, the rollercoaster rush to revolution, awaits, simply,
its own 
<P><I>Logos</I>, 
<br><B>The Word.</B>
<P>
The network of Byte Cities will be constructed on top of the on-line
services' road network that exists today.  We still think of <I>The
Net</I> as a communications mesh, but it is really a transportation
network.  It will be like the railroad of the last century because
it will do the same thing the railroads did to our lives.  But
instead of a physical locomotive, taking us to the city, the virtu-screen
will be a <I>virtual</I> engine, bringing the city to us.
<P>
We are only perhaps 20 years away from living, and working, in
the virtual public square of Byte City.  And when it hits us,
its power to entrance will be irresistible, but just as irresistibly,
it will disrupt the inherited rhythm of our lives.
<P>
Keep in mind that this will be nothing like looking at a television,
no matter how big the TV image gets.  Marshall McLuhan told us
that TV was a &quot;cool&quot; medium, because the screen was
always in the way, scratching at our emotional bond with the moving
imagery on it.  The interface was the emotional distance that
diminishes TV &quot;reality.&quot;
<P>
The wall-high virtu-screen parts ways with all of its vacuum-tube
progenitors because
<P>
<I>There is no interface.</I>
<P>
It is not only big like a movie screen, it has the picture fidelity
of life.  High-definition, digital imagery is <I>here</I>, but
the truly life-like is <I>there</I>, only a few years away.  You
will not hit the pavement of Byte City streets, but you will walk
the sidewalks none the less.
<P>
You will appear on those streets, visible to others, in a simulated
form:  a digital composite.  Most, surely, you will also appear
in slightly <I>[or highly!]</I> idealized form.  A whole service
niche will spring up, like the Pinkertons of the last century,
to verify that those we meet in Byte City are who they say they
are ... Countering <I>[of course!]</I> the artistry of an even
bigger new niche, the persona-<I>couturiers</I>;  from <I>haute</I>
to almost off-the-rack.
<P>
In fact, demand for a yet-unimagined range of services will surge
to meet the needs of this fabulous, overwhelming, new urban world.
 There will be so much to do, so much that one wants to do, that
our sense of <I>needs</I> will be wrestling with almost constant
redefinition.  Is it so different now?  <I>I <U>need</U> that
new computer?</I>  Really.  Just take that urge up an order of
magnitude.
<P>
You will work there, you will want to play there, you can do <I>[almost]</I>
everything there.  And each of the Byte Cities -- some big, some
very intimate -- will savagely compete for your time and your
precious subscription.
<P>
But one thing they will not compete for, one thing they will all
strive actively to assuage, will be the eventual <I>anomie</I>
they spread, seeping into our spirits even as we work and cavort
in the cool, passionate swirl of neon and gilded <I>chiaroscuro</I>.
<P>
Because it will change the way we relate to people.  Think about
it:  If you can meet with anyone, anywhere, any time, interact
with them, do anything with them -- immediately, intimately, but
<I>virtually</I> -- the potential for initial social disruption
is as great as that visited on the flood of urban migrants to
the brick cities of smokestacks and furnaces that scarred England
two centuries ago.
<P>
Those cities physically threw people together.  Our revolution
will also throw people together, but the impact of intimacy --
for work or play -- without barriers of time and space, will stretch
and stress our social patterns to the limit.
<P>
How will it do this?  Let's look at three torquings of necessary
intimacy:
<P>
<pre>
<CENTER><I><B>Sports   		Speech    		Sex</B></I></CENTER>
</pre>
<P>
<CENTER><B>*.*.*.*.*</B></CENTER>
<P>
<br>
<br>
<CENTER><I><B>Sports</B></I></CENTER>
<P>
keep us tribally blooded.  Not with the band, out for the hunt,
but in a theater of its training.  Sports is our ritual connection
to the tribe working together for survival, seeking great elk
kills.  Sports takes us back to origins, keeping our oldest identity
alive.
<P>
But sports changes to fit new worlds of work.  And sports is not
like work, sports is not for work.  Sports gives us things that
new worlds of work take away.  So when mill and assembly line
made us stand all day, sports let us sit down.  Baseball is America's
industrial sport, the theater that let a tired worker sit down
in the cool evening, have a beer, and watch them play ball.. 
Watching is as important as playing;  they are both equal parts
of the ritual sharing, because in a mass society, if the hunt
is to be tribally shared, the theater must encompass all.  Hence
the 100,000 Bowl, a stadium for the whole <I>polis</I>;  or <I>Monday
Night Football</I>, for the biggest tribe of all.  <I>Nation</I>
meant tribe for the Romans, and nation came from the verb, <I>to
be born</I>.
<P>
But Byte City forces us to get outside and play.  Now we work
in our own cells, we labor without moving, we sweat virtually.
 That vast virtu-screen becomes our master, we long for escape.
 Our urge to feel the primitive overwhelms us.  Forget baseball,
football, basketball, all the ball-pushing million-dollar heroes
do for us -- we want to get out.  Today, in places like Moab,
Utah, yuppie precursors of the new world of work sit all day in
front of their vacuum tubes, longing for the five-hour, four-wheel
drive that will take them to some wind-scarred escarpment where
they can hang-glide, or kayak-surf, or snowboard to within a fingernail's
proximity of themselves, the once-Magdelian hunter, in that very
place, an elk and a glacier ago.
<P>
<br>
<CENTER><I><B>Speech</B></I></CENTER>
<P>
is more than how we talk.  It's about the identity we get from
how we talk.  Old Order types talk in writing, and they lament
what they call the end of literacy.  Whining:  <I>When people
stop writing, the greatest glory of human expression will die,
and with it, the heart of civilization itself.</I>
<P>
But the death of Old Order writing is the rebirth of our language.
 The death prose we now call <I>the written word</I> was once
alive with current.  When Samuel Johnson bleu stronge with so
grayte a noyse, written English was vital, rich, hot-blooded.
 We didn't even know how to spell until well into the 19th century:
<P>
Until well into the industrial era.  After the revolution.  The
new elites may have brought order, but they also brought formality,
control.  Over the last century, the enlightened elite wrung the
spirit out of language.  Bureaucrats made rigid the written word,
larded it with rules, a bid to control thought itself.  In industrial
end-times, <I>Elitespeak</I> is unreadable.  <I>Elitespeak</I>
is not for giving a message; it is for hiding it.  It is <I>anti-language</I>.
<P>
But now, as we lose our &quot;literacy,&quot; we liberate our
tongues.  New ways of telling fit new values to be told, all spoken
in a new place.  And telling it affirms what we are, as it overturns
what we are not.  So as we speak the truth, song returns to speech.
 And as we make new landscape heroic in virtual expanse, we come
back to Homeric, Hip-Hop cadence.  New language, new connection,
new message.
<P>
<br>
<CENTER><I><B>Sex</B></I></CENTER>
<P>
is to society what C4 is to civil engineering:  it is elemental
both to creation and to destruction.  That is why all cultures
work hard to harness sex, to make it celebrate and reinforce society
... because it also has the power to tear away at it.  Modern
lore remembers two tearing times:  the libertine French Revolution
[as in <I>Marat-Sade</I>:  &quot;What's the use of a revolution
without general copulation?&quot;], and the more widespread wildfire
of &quot;liberated,&quot; pre-AIDS America:  1790s, 1970s.  Neither
lasted long.
<P>
Byte City does not promote uncontrolled sex, it merely removes
the controls.  Remember, you can meet anyone, anywhere, anytime.
 And whatever you do is free of consequences.  Byte City's most
obvious limitation is also its biggest draw:  you can't actually
touch anyone, so no one gets hurt. <I> Physically</I>.  Old style,
uncontrolled sex meant a river of consequences:  unwanted births,
incurable diseases, collateral crimes aplenty, and marital mayhem.
 None of these would attain in <I>Byte City</I>, the ultimate
terminus of protected, vicarious, unbridled sex.
<P>
No culture has ever been offered such a painless feast.  No culture
has ever had its ethos so tested.  Culture controls sex by linking
it indissoluably to love.  Promiscuity requires cruel manipulation
of others while zeroing out love;  even in a society where sex
is available, only a few can sustain the drain on persona that
promiscuity demands.  Byte City's sexual <I>smorgasbord</I> makes
no such demands.
<P>
Everybody can do it:  we feel no pain, no pain is inflicted, identity
is hidden, and fantasex is limited only by mind and by byte.
<P>
But there is a fee.  This is real sex, and there will be consequences.
 How overwhelming?  Look at the constant pushing of the envelope
in on-line sex right now;  but this is nothing to the pulsing
explosion to come.  Baroque paraphernalia will be like quaaludes
in the high-quest:  virtual reality armor and implants, real-time
video changelings for digital personae, and wild, wild metamorphoses.
<P>
Morph sex itself will stretch us, in the end, back to ourselves.
 At that final limit, so far beyond what physical sex restrains,
the very terror we will feel will be in our own reflection;  in
what we have become.
<P>
<CENTER><B>*.*.*.*.*</B></CENTER>
<P>
<br>
<br>
<I><B>And</B></I> the free-wheeling, almost frontier spirit of
Byte City will push the <I>coming apart</I> we all feel is tearing
at American society.  When historians look back on this period,
perhaps they will shake their heads, thinking the clich&eacute;
of all historians:  <I>Couldn't they see it?  It was so obvious:
 the breakdown in family life, the 60% illegitimacy rates of the
early 1990s ... these were just the heralds of things to come?</I>
<P>
But people feel what is coming, even if their elite officially
denies it.  The elite denies by redefining the <I>tsunami</I>
to suit its own needs, even as the wave rises over them:  <I>A
changing labor force?  We can solve that with another federal
jobs retraining program</I>.  People are more honest;  they feel
the revolution's rumble in their guts.
<P>
Because they know the comfort of mature industrial times, the
apparent orderliness of a work force half-maker, half-manager,
has been eroding away for two decades.  But the erosion doesn't
stop;  it accelerates.  The industrial world is going away.
<P>
What does work -- and the identity work brings -- look like in
Byte City?
<P>
Say we end up in this world by 2020.  Byte City -- the new economy
-- will live on ideas.  If ideas are really the currency, if ideas
are really what make things happen, then <I>making it</I> will
be even more meritocratic than it is now.
<P>
It won't be enough to have a college degree from Yale and announce:
 <I>I'm Wolf's Head, <U>cum laude</U>, make me a Foreign Service
Officer</I> -- or some other bureaucratic lifestyle slot.  Or
-- <I>I rate a fat niche on the corporate pyramid at IBM</I>.
 No.  All job worth must be proven in Byte City.  Only a very
few will make it to the ether either ... and Murray's <I>Bell
Curve</I> won't be the best litmus test for their success.  I.Q.
measures what's in the box, but <B>Brain Lords</B> are made by
going out of the box.  That's what Byte City will thrive on, and
that's why they are the great winners, initially, in this world.
<P>
Brain Lords are not like the Robber Barons, nor their enlightened
engineer successors, the <I>Brain Trust</I>.  They are not empire-builders,
like Carnegie, nor do they wish to be managers of millions, like
Ira Magaziner.  Their goal is not control of others.  They seek
realization within their persons, like ancient heroes:  where
their brain power is like the strength and speed of Achilles.
 Tom Wolfe called them, wryly,<I> &quot;Masters of the Universe.&quot;</I>
 Milken, Gates, Spielberg:  they are the Achilles of Smart.
<P>
Yet the brain lords will not represent a heritable class.  They
will make it as individuals, and most of them will make it only
for a brief time.  Burn-out will be their limiting factor.  Like
their prototypes today in entertainment and the media, they will
use up their personal capital quickly.  The top job niche will
emphasize golden parachutes aplenty, with more relaxing work to
follow a forties' retirement.
<P>
Still successful, still needed, will be the <B>Upper Server</B>
society.  Lawyers and doctors will still make big money, but their
top echelon status will be undercut by a wholly new job persona:
 the Agent.
<P>
<B>Agents </B>will be the individual entrepreneur class, those
who offer tailored information services -- including law and medicine
and education! -- in Byte City.  Many in what we still call &quot;the
professions&quot; will squat in this niche.  The rising class
of personal information-providers and navigators will put real
downward social pressure on doctors and lawyers and academics,
because agents will get you -- or take you to -- the knowledge
you need, without a defilingly expensive appointment with the
almighty.
<P>
And maybe 10 percent of the workforce stays in production, whether
it's growing food or whether it's making things.  And they will
form a sort of upper tier themselves.  Because of the highly specialized
skills required to be a new manufacturer, <B>Makers</B> will usually
be part owners of their firms.
<P>
So say about 25 percent are doing well, very well.  And, given
the corrosion and damage to the young in illegitimate and single-parent
households today;  tomorrow's labor force will include a bottom,
an underclass, also about 25%.  This, tragically, will be double
the population share of those discarded in the bad old industrial
era.  These are <B>The Lost</B>;  and in revolutionary times,
societies have shown little inclination to find them.
<P>
And they can be sustained, as they are now, by the great wealth
unlocked by Byte City.  They can be sustained, but they can't
be ignored.  Those who bring order from the chaos of things to
come, those who come after us, will very likely make the rediscovery
of the lost their great task, just as the Victorians and the Progressives
in their day sought out the poor.
<P>
But what will the rest of us, the 50 percent in the middle, the
bedrock of the industrial world's great &quot;Middle Class;&quot;
 the true believers in &quot;The American Dream;&quot;  <I>what
will we do?</I>
<P>
Old Order, New Deal elitists still think that there won't be anything
to do.  Jeremy Rivkin's new book, <I>The End of Work</I>, rehashes
the old lie of the engineer class:  there is only so much that
can be produced, so as the work force gets more productive, there
will be fewer and fewer jobs.  And eventually, there won't be
any work anymore.  Let us, the enlightened engineers of the elite,
apportion work <I>equitably</I> [meaning:  <I>as we see fit</I>].
<P>
We know <I>[Oh! How we know!]</I> that this just isn't true. 
The mountainous evidence is everywhere about us.  Demand creates
wealth;  the industrial revolution created a whole new universe
of demand.  Look at the personal computer.  <I>Demand=Wealth</I>;
 created out of nothing, out of the thin air of an idea!
<P>
There will be plenty of jobs in Byte City.
<P>
There will be plenty of money.  The question is:  What status
will these jobs have?  Of all the old badges, the four-year college
degree will be the most worthless.  People still think:  <I>I
have a college degree, I can be in middle management and rise
to the top if I'm good; I can do it</I>.  That is the motivational
mythology of the industrial age.  It is a blind guide to tomorrow.
<P>
Work in Byte City is all about service.  And the bulk of work
will be in maintenance, sales, support, and delivery.  Like video
game advisors, telling you how to get through <I>Donkey Kong in
Paris</I>, or getting you those perfect tomato cubes from the
Safeway <I>Casbah </I>local warehouse, or showing you wares in
the Woolworth Palace in Mainstreet, USA, or fixing a damaged local
fiber optic line for an Opreyville subscriber, or working up a
new simulated persona for a customer who wants to make a splash
as Conan in <I>Dirty</I> <I>Rita's Party Place</I>.
<P>
A chilling possibility is this comeback of service.  But that
trend today is in full flood.  At least in Byte City, most of
us are serving each other.
<P>
The problem -- <I>always</I> -- is status.  Like those new workers
in the early industrial era, those in the mills and furnaces were
not offered the status of the craftsman they replaced.  They were
pushed to the limit, because there were no limits yet defined.
 They were abused because their undefined status did not culturally
protect them.
<P>
We, the majority, the 50 percent who will make Byte City work,
will go to work in our living rooms <I>[or even, closeted in our
bedrooms]</I> before the big screen, and we will suffer much the
same stripping of self as that majority entering the Midlands
milltowns of 1820 or the East Side sweatshops of 1880.  Already
Americans are working longer and longer hours.  Can you imagine
-- with &quot;<I>global competition&quot;</I> as the excuse --
people in Byte City standing in front of their screens, working
their customers, 12, 15 hours a day?  And with an end to commuting
for many, the Brain Lords will say, S<I>o much the more time to
work</I>.  <I>And you're working at home, right?</I>
<P>
So all this talk about class is upsetting?  Americans don't like
the word:  the elite don't want to be likened to Euristocrats;
 the rest of us don't want to be reminded that The People are
not in charge.  Or maybe just that we didn't <I>make it</I>.
<P>
Class in America is always there, and it rises right to the surface
of our thinking during Big Change.  Why?  Because those driving
change also seize its opportunities.  While old elites topple
and gutter-slide, the new are in chic media worship.  They are
<U>what's happening</U>, we are <U>what is done <I>to</I></U>.
 So while our lives are in free fall, they float, majestically,
in the ether of the new world.
<P>
But what we will see as the new class won't have any of its ancestors'
levers of control.  First it was land, then commodities, then
&quot;the means of production.&quot;  In this this century it
has been knowledge.  The mature industrial world was run by bureaucratic
machine.  And what was that?  It was a pyramid of professionals,
managers, engineers:  these were the noble titles of the twentieth
century's equestrian order of knowledge.  Control of knowledge
was power, and access to knowledge was carefully controlled.
<P>
No one will control knowledge in Byte City.  The new class will
only appear to us as swaggering Brain Lords; we will assume that
they are the new masters of the universe, Robber Barons reborn.
 Their moment will be even more evanescent than in industrial
times.  After the Big Change, when it all shakes down, Byte City
may be a place for Big Men, but not for Lords.  But during the
rollicking, roughshod rollercoaster wavetime, the Brain Lords
will be the riders of the transformation, the ones scoring big,
the arrogant makers and high rollers.  And because they are the
first to benefit big from the revolution, while its impact is
still crashing down on us, we will vent on them.
<P>
Because we will identify the new elites with the whole change,
<I>bad and good</I>.  And because they break the old but then
themselves do not lead, we at last despise them.  We flock to
their network, but then, as we live and work there, Byte City
becomes ours:  a public square, a community of many neighborhoods.
 And we will want a different vision of life in this place.
<P>
So the time will come, soon after the network is built, when we
will, as those before us, demand new meaning.
<P>
And we will find it along two paths unexpectedly familiar:  politics,
and religion.
<P>
The industrial world threw people together.  Their physical closeness,
<I>en masse</I>, allowed people to mobilize politically <I>en
masse</I>.  And they did.  And that was the birth of mass, plebiscitary
democracy.
<P>
But Byte City lets us escape the faceless experience of mass democracy.
 People today are rejecting machine politics because they sense
that the new tools of social connection, the very tools that will
soon fuse into Byte City, will give them the voice to speak decisively
in all decision-making;  and not, this time, in instant mass telephony
-- button-pushing robot Perotistas -- <U>but through thousands
of interest groups and factions.</U>
<P>
Byte City returns us to politics as The Founders meant it to be.
 But politics then -- <I>say, in 1800</I> -- were for a few thousands
of Americans only.  Byte City will let millions of civically motivated
citizens meet, and caucus, and <I>politick</I>:  anywhere, anytime.
<P>
And they will demand directly.  We can only marvel in advance
at the political turbulence that lies in wait.  <I>What will we
do with all those factions?</I>
<P>
Because Americans want unity too.  They want that mythic togetherness,
like a Raoul Walsh war film or a John Ford western 
<P>
<I>Around her neck, she wore a yellow ribbon,</I>
<br>
<I>She wore it in the springtime, and in the month of May,</I>
<br>
<I>And when I asked her, why the hell she wore it,</I>
<br>
<I>She wore it for her sweetheart in the US Cavalry ...</I>
<P>
American togetherness is slipping away.  Where can it be found
again?
<P>
Maybe in our search for meaning in Faith.  Byte City will open
up new communities of faith as we struggle with disorder in our
lives, and especially, a fracturing of how we relate to others.
 Byte City will redefine words like <I>temptation</I>, <I>abandonment</I>,
<I>anomie</I>.  What will be the basis for connection, for commitment?
 To whom will we owe allegiance, in whom can we repose our trust?
<P>
Byte City's very nature brings a breaking-down of secular society.
<P>
And out of the rootlessness and freaky chaos will come religious
revivals.  But they will not emerge from the Old Order <I>Mainline</I>
Churches -- <I>those bastions of the elite</I> -- nor from the
Evangelical patent-leather bureaucracies that have risen to such
estate in recent years.
<P>
Why <I>patent-leather</I>?  Because to fight the elite society
of the modern state, elite evangelicals organized themselves on
the same lines.  They learned the same machine politics, and they
crafted an agenda of state control.  This time, their state. 
They became the very Church their own prophets had once fled from.
 They became the very image of the thing they fought against.
 Now their <I>tele-ministries</I> and <I>coalitions</I> are full
partners in the Old Order landscape of squabbling necropoli.
<P>
<I>Cities of the Dead</I>.  The new cities are coming, and with
them, a maw of <I>anomie</I>.  The new revival will come as a
calling:  of people rising up.  It will be the evangelism that
meets spiritual crisis head-on, that is witnessed in the new wilderness
by those who speak the truth and give good news.  And the message
will meet the times.  It will not look backward, like the anti-progressive
Old Order, to some nostalgic golden age that we can get back to
if only we have the right regulatory structure, or pass the right
laws, or ... 
<P>
The next <I>Great Awakening</I> will happen in Byte City itself.
 Maybe many sects, hot competition, fighting over their skyrocketing
convert-count.  Yet chances are that it will rise from the grassroots
Of Catholic and Protestant evangalism, like Methodism did two
centuries ago.  And maybe like Methodism, a single vision will
sweep over us.  But the revival itself will meet a great wave
of national emotion.  And [<I>when it comes</I>] its talk will
be the center of our search for new American life.
<P>
[<I>Important!  It won't look like any ad on today's Religion
page!</I>]
<P>
That is why <I>how</I> Methodism came to Britain is what we need
to know, not that it was <I>Methodist</I>.  It came.  We need
to know why it came, because we are in for the same ride.  The
cultural paradox for us at the end of <I>The Modern</I> is that
religion didn't go away.  It's going to be more important.  Just
different.  And whatever it looks like, how we find faith will
be a big part of the way we join hands civically as Americans.
<P>
And what we demand, and how we demand it, will determine who rises
to give demand leadership and vision.  We can say with certainty
that it cannot come from the dying old order:  both deathbed <I>New
Dealers</I> and but slightly less moribund <I>New Democrats</I>.
 And we suspect that it will<U><I> not</I></U> come from the cocky
Brain Lords who build Byte City <I>[but we need them to build
it!].</I>
<P>
But we should know that the Brain Lords <I>will </I>build it,
and that it <I>will</I> change our lives forever.  We know further,
in spite of Social Democracy's sentimental gurglings, that the
future cannot be managed, nor its reality held back.
<P>
But we should comfort ourselves in the knowledge also that these
things have happened before.  Others survived their time of stress,
dislocation, and <I>anomie</I>.  Britain made it through its crisis
to a world that would later be enshrined by us [in <I>Sherlock
Holmes</I>, <I>Upstairs, Downstairs</I>] as among the best of
good times.  And the United States made it through its crisis
to a similar happy place in the American mind [in <I>Meet Me in
St. Louis, Easter Parade</I>].  Crisis was succeeded by a spirit
of confidence and of hope, and a reassertion of the inevitability,
and ultimate good, of Progress.
<P>
<I>How will it happen?  How will we get to these good times?</I>
<P>
That's another story.
<br>
<br>
<P>
<i>Michael Vlahos is a Senior Fellow at the Progress and Freedom
Foundation, and a Fellow of The Foreign Policy Institute of the
Nitze School of Advanced International Studies.  [&copy; Michael
Vlahos, 1995; Byte City]</i>

<P><br>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
