<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Front Matter & Acknowledgements -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<FONT SIZE=6 >ADVANCING MEDICAL INNOVATION</FONT>
<H3>HEALTH, SAFETY AND THE ROLE OF GOVERNMENT
<br>IN THE 21<SUP>ST</SUP> CENTURY
</h3>
 February 7, 1996<BR>
</FONT>
<br>
 Ralph A. Epstein, M.D.</FONT>
<br>
 Thomas M. Lenard, Ph.D</FONT>
<br>
 Henry I. Miller, M.D.</FONT>
<br>
 Robert D. Tollison, Ph.D.</FONT>
<br>
 W. Kip Viscusi, Ph.D.</FONT>
<br>
 William M. Wardell, M.D.,
Ph.D.<BR></FONT>
<P>
In its current form, the Food and Drug Administration is a prototypical
centralized, bureaucratic regulatory agency, similar to so many
other agencies designed during the heyday of the Progressive era.
 By modern standards, it is cumbersome, slow, expensive and inefficient.
 But its most significant costs are not financial - they are human.
 America's outmoded FDA directly results in jobs being exported
overseas.  And, most importantly, it denies new health technologies
to patients who need them to live healthy lives, or even to survive.
<BR>

<P>
The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation has undertaken a multi-year
effort to design and to create a new, modern institution that
will continue to ensure the safety and effectiveness of medical
products while providing patients with faster access to new treatments.
 Two earlier versions of a replacement model for the FDA were
circulated to the public with request for comment.  In addition,
the Advisory Committee, under the chairmanship of Dr. Louis Sullivan,
provided valuable guidance.  The views expressed here-in are solely
those of the authors and do not necessarily reflect those of The
Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation.<BR>
<BR>

<B><FONT >THE ADVISORY COMMITTEE</FONT></B>
<br>
Hon. Louis Sullivan, M.D.  Barbara Lawton, Ph.D.
<br>
John E. Calfee, Ph.D.   Fred McChesney, Ph.D., J.D.
<br>
James Driscoll, Ph.D   Keith Mowry
<br>
Henry G. Grabowski, Ph.D.  Paul Rubin, Ph.D.
<br>
Robert Helms, Ph.D.    Eugene Schonfeld, Ph.D
<br>
Peter Barton Hutt, Esq.   W. Leigh Thompson, Jr., M.D., Ph.D
<br>
Sam Kazman, Esq.   Frankie Trull
<br>
James Kitterman    Gail R. Wilensky, Ph.D.
  <BR>

<P>
<B><FONT >THE PROGRESS &AMP; FREEDOM FOUNDATION</FONT></B>
<P>
A private, non-profit, non-partisan idea center established in
1993, The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation aims to create a positive
vision of the future founded in the historical principles of the
American Idea. It brings together a diverse group of thinkers
and policy experts and shares their work with the American people
through seminars, conferences, publications and electronic media
of all forms. Tax-exempt under Section 501(c)(3) of the Internal
Revenue Code, The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation does not engage
in lobbying activities or take positions on legislation.  The
views expressed here are solely those of the authors and do not
necessarily represent the views of the Board, Officers or Staff
of The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation.<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT >BOARD OF DIRECTORS</FONT></B><FONT >
 </FONT>
<P>
George A. Keyworth II Jeffrey A. Eisenach     Frank J. Hanna III
 James C. Miller III
<P>
<I>        Chairman  </I>      <I>President      </I>Arianna Huffington
 William Roesing
<P>
                      R. Mark Lubbers
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >ABOUT THE AUTHORS<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B><FONT >Ralph A. Epstein, M.D. --</FONT></B><FONT >
An adjunct fellow at the Foundation, Epstein is professor of anesthesiology
at the University of Connecticut. He is known for his expertise
in the technology of medical devices and in the functioning of
the medical device industry. He is the author of more than 50
articles covering a wide range of interests varying from scientific
experimentation to commentary on medical and legal issues.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >Thomas M. Lenard, Ph.D -- </FONT></B><FONT >Lenard
is a senior fellow and director of regulatory studies at The Progress
&amp; Freedom Foundation. Previously, Lenard was vice president
of Heiden Associates, a Washington, D.C., economics consulting
firm, where he specialized in economic analysis of regulatory
and competition/antitrust issues.  Lenard has also served as Senior
Advisor for Economic Policy at the Office of Management and Budget.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >Henry I. Miller, M.D.</FONT></B><FONT >
<B>-- </B>is a Robert Wesson Fellow of Scientific Philosophy and
Public Policy at the Hoover Institution and a consulting professor
at the Institute for International Studies, Stanford University.
He served at the Food and Drug Administration from 1979 to 1993,
lastly as founding director of the FDA's Office of Biotechnology.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >Robert D. Tollison, Ph.D. -- </FONT></B><FONT >An
adjunct fellow at the Foundation, Tollison is Duncan Black Professor
of Economics and director of the Center for Study of Public Choice
at George Mason University in Fairfax, Virginia. Tollison has
also served in government twice, once as a Senior Staff Economist
on the President's Council of Economic Advisers and again as Director
of the Bureau of Economics at the Federal Trade Commission.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >W. Kip Viscusi, Ph.D. --</FONT></B><FONT >
 An adjunct fellow at the Foundation, Viscusi is the George G.
Allen Professor of Economics at Duke University. Viscusi's research
focuses primarily on individual and societal responses to risk
and uncertainty.  He has published 15 books and 166 articles,
most of which deal with different aspects of risk and product
liability.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >William M. Wardell, M.D., Ph. D. --  </FONT></B><FONT >An
adjunct fellow at the Foundation, Wardell is president of Wardell
Associates International of Belmont, MA., a consulting firm for
the development and approval of pharmaceuticals, biotechnology
products and medical devices.  He is also Adjunct Professor of
Pharmacology and Experimental Therapeutics at Tufts University
Medical School.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT >ACKNOWLEDGMENTS<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT >The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation began
its work developing a replacement model for medical technology
regulation in 1993, believing that the coming advances in medical
technology have the potential to dramatically increase both life
spans and the quality of life while greatly reducing the cost
of health care.  We also realized that this would only occur if
a regulatory process was in place that encouraged rather than
stifled innovation.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >We wish to thank our adjunct fellows - Ralph
Epstein, Henry Miller, Bob Tollison, Kip Viscusi and Bill Wardell
- who did a yeoman's job in designing a regulatory process for
the 21<SUP>st</SUP> Century. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >We are particularly honored that Lou Sullivan
willingly and faithfully served as Chairman of our Advisory Committee.
 In addition 15 other individuals on the Advisory Committee gave
freely their time, expertise and advice throughout the process:
 Jack Calfee, Jim Driscoll, Henry Grabowski, Robert Helms, Peter
Barton Hutt, Sam Kazman, Jim Kitterman, Barb Lawton, Fred McChesney,
Keith Mowry, Paul Rubin, Gene Schonfeld, Leigh Thompson, Frankie
Trull and Gail Wilensky.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >We are immensely grateful to several individuals
in Europe, both in government and industry, who took time out
of their busy schedules to meet with us and explain the European
approach for bringing pharmaceuticals and medical devices to the
marketplace.  Without their willingness to help us, our work would
have been far more difficult and frankly, incomplete.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Of course, not of this could have been possible
without generous financial support from individuals and organizations.
 Although funds are not targeted toward a specific project, many
medical device and pharmaceutical companies have supported our
foundation since 1993.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Finally, we wish to thank over 1500 individuals
including organizations representing patients, physicians, consumers
and industry plus government officials and companies that were
asked to comment on our reports.  Many expressed concern for the
inability of a large bureaucracy to keep up with current science
and that FDA generally lags behind its European counterparts.
In spite of these concerns, most wanted to make sure that the
standards for safety and effectiveness would not be compromised.
 We thank all of those who took the time to provide advice, suggestions
and even criticism to the work we undertook.<BR>
</FONT>
<br>
<FONT >      Jeff Eisenach</FONT>
<br>
<FONT >      Bill Myers</FONT>
<br>
<FONT >      Tom Lenard</FONT>
<br>
<FONT >      Libby Wright</FONT>

