</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Regulatory Reform -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<P>
<P>
<h3><FONT >REGULATORY REFORM:  IMPORTANCE,
HISTORY, AND GOALS</h3>
</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<B><FONT >The Need For New Therapies</B>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >American patients and physicians need and deserve
more rapid access to greater numbers of safe and effective drugs.
 It is clearly in the public interest to encourage pharmaceutical
innovation -- the discovery, development, and marketing of new
therapies.  Over the past 35&nbsp;years however, regulations originally
designed to protect public health by preventing the sale or use
of unsafe or ineffective products have themselves become impediments
to progress in the field.  The evolution of pharmaceutical regulation
has moved inexorably in one direction: toward more stringent,
burdensome, and intrusive oversight as FDA has assumed more and
more responsibilities and power.  As the Presidents Biomedical
Panel concluded in 1976, the delays and costs that the FDA's protective
systems impose on drug development constitute a &quot;hazard to
public health&quot;<sup><a href="foot.html">1</a></sup>.  In 1973 the president's Science Advisory
Committee concluded that it may &quot;be worth adapting US regulations
so that not even a single important new entity introduced into
selected foreign countries during the previous year fails to become
available in the US.&quot;<sup><a href="foot.html">2</a></sup><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >This proposal seeks to restore a more appropriate
balance between regulation and innovation - but without jeopardizing
product safety - by facilitating the development and regulatory
review of pharmaceuticals.  Public health will be maintained and
even enhanced.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >Why is Innovation so Difficult and Costly?</b></FONT>
<P>
<FONT >It is a fact that the development and approval
of new drugs in the United States takes too long.  The total time
for drug development, from discovery or synthesis of the molecule
to NDA approval, has more than doubled since 1964, from an average
of 6.3 years, in the period 1963-1965 to 15.0 years, in the period
1990-1992.  The time from IND filing to NDA approval (the most
highly regulated portion) now averages 8 years in the United States
-- two years longer than in Europe.  There have been dazzling
advances in discovery, such as the cloning of receptors and the
use of transgenic animals for both toxicology testing and human
disease models. But regulatory burdens have hampered innovation,
compromised the availability of new therapeutics, and wasted the
resources of both FDA and the pharmaceutical industry.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >As the time required for drug development has
lengthened, the average &quot;effective patent life&quot; - that
is, the time remaining from NDA approval to expiration of the
main patent -- has declined correspondingly, a double disincentive
for sponsors considering drug development. Effective patent life,
nearly 14 years in 1966, declined to less than seven years in
the early 1980s.  The Waxman-Hatch Patent Restoration Act of 1984
restored, at most, half of this loss, and required other substantial,
costly concessions from the research-based drug industry, notably
earlier approval of generic drugs.  It is the effects of these
and other disincentives to research that are being seen in the
consolidation of the research-based industry today.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Analyses of innovation in the U.S. pharmaceutical
industry show that its research output, as measured by the introduction
of INDs for new chemical entities (NCEs), declined rapidly and
significantly after the 1962 law was enacted.  The decline occurred
in several phases.  There was an immediate decline (by more than
50 percent) in the early 1960s.  Then for a decade the output
was fairly constant, but in the mid-1970s it fell again by another
50 percent.  It recovered somewhat in the early 1980s.  However,
in the last decade it has declined again, although in the 1990s
the shortfall in NCEs has been compensated by &quot;new biotechnological
entities&quot; (NBEs), the corresponding biotechnology product
candidates.  (DiMasi et al, CPT 1994)<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >It would be overstating the case to argue that
all impediments to innovation derive from regulation.  The process
of innovation -- a lengthy and complex one involving discovery
and development, including clinical testing -- is formidably difficult
and expensive.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >In addition to the scientific and technological
hurdles, there are new obstacles in marketing. Over the past decade
there have been fundamental changes in the nature of the market
for pharmaceuticals and in the product criteria needed to succeed
there. The days of the manufacturer selling a new drug directly
to individual physicians are rapidly vanishing.  Typically, today's
manufacturer of a new drug must convince a panel of experts who
comprise a managed-care organization's formulary committee --
a discerning and informed consumer -- of the importance of the
product.  Their evidentiary criteria can exceed those of FDA and
they may call for evidence (such as pharmacoeconomics and comparative
efficacy) that is outside the sphere of the drug-approval process.
 The utilization of new (and other) drugs is becoming more tightly
controlled, and the outcomes are being recorded and analyzed in
ways that were previously inconceivable. There is, for example,
a growing use of computerized control of patient selection, indication,
dose, and duration of therapy.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Thus, manufacturers' products and claims, and
the evidence supporting them, must meet very high standards to
be accepted in today's marketplace.  In this exacting environment,
government regulation of the product-development process should
not add burdens that are no longer necessary.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >One fundamental cause of the ever-increasing
regulatory burden in the United States is  that regulators strive
to avoid, at any cost, approving a product that might turn out
to be harmful, even if this policy causes them inevitably and
systematically to delay or neglect to approve products that promote
patients' well-being.  Consequently, FDA has continually imposed
new requirements and assumed new regulatory responsibilities that
have inexorably increased the length of the approval process and
the costs involved.  Because this phenomenon goes to the fundamental
malaise of FDA's monopoly over drug evaluation and review, it
is worth exploring further. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >There exists a marked asymmetry, or imbalance,
between the two kinds of wrong decisions that a regulator can
make: (1) a decision to approve for marketing a drug or other
product that turns out to be harmful (an &quot;error of commission&quot;),
or (2) a decision to deny, delay or inhibit approval of a drug
or other product that would be beneficial (an &quot;error of omission&quot;).
 Putting this another way, it is the difference is between permitting
something bad to happen and not permitting something beneficial
to happen.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Several kinds of asymmetry exist in the two
situations.  Two classic examples of errors of commission are
the approval of the tranquilizer thalidomide by some European
regulatory agencies in the 1960's and the approval of the &quot;swine
flu&quot; vaccine by FDA.  Mistakes like these are highly visible.
 They bring down the wrath of the media, the public, and legislative
oversight bodies.  Often both the developers of the drug and the
regulators who allowed it to be marketed are criticized and punished
-- witness the modern-day pillories in Congressional oversight
hearings and the press.  A regulator's career might be damaged
irreparably by the good-faith but mistaken approval of a product.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Errors of omission, in the form of unreasonable
demands or requirements, can delay or prevent entirely the marketing
of an important new product.  But such errors of omission caused
by regulators' bad judgments, timidity or anxiety is often known
only to a few knowledgeable company and FDA insiders.  And if
the mistake precipitates a company's decision to abandon the drug,
both the regulatory misstep and the sequelae may be largely invisible.
 Moreover, there may be no direct evidence that the continuing
suffering of patients is avoidable -- or that the regulators are
culpable.  Too often FDA is allowed to &quot;err on the side of
safety,&quot; when that is merely a euphemism for committing an
error of  &quot;ommission.&quot; <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The changes in regulations proposed here are
intended, in part, to improve the balance between benefit and
risk, and between safety considered narrowly and patients' overall
welfare.  The plan will shift the balance toward encouraging product
development and permitting patients greater and timelier access
to the benefits of innovation.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >Positive Features of the U.S. System of
 Drug Development and Regulation</FONT></B>

<P>
<FONT >In proposing reform, it is important to understand
and preserve the virtues of the present system.  Industry, government,
academia, and medical practice all play a role in the scheme of
drug development, regulation, and use in this country.  This system
has substantially achieved two major goals: <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >1) protection of human subjects of clinical
research (through the IND process); and,</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >2) assurance that no product reaches the market
until proved reasonably safe and effective for its labeled use
(through the NDA process).<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The major regulatory requirements governing
this process were instituted in 1962.  Over the past 35 years,
students of U.S. regulation have learned a great deal about the
nuances of the regulatory system and of FDA itself, including
which aspects work well and which need to be improved.   It should
be noted, however, that drug regulation, while important, is only
one of many important contributing factors in bringing new therapies
to patients.  Profound changes have occurred over the past three
decades in widely disparate parts of the system and in society.
Clinical research has advanced. The media has become more aggressive
and covered these subjects more fully.  Public sophistication
and awareness has grown.  Pharmaceutical marketing, tort case
law, and -- perhaps most important and powerful now and for the
foreseeable future -- the system of paying for medical treatments
have all changed dramatically.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Clinical research, for example, has many more
professional, full-time, career clinical researchers (including
MD/PhDs) than it did in 1962.  Since 1962, we have also seen the
advent of institutional safeguards, such as Institutional Review
Boards (IRBs).  Corporate operating procedures have been systematized,
as have corporate and government clinical-safety reporting and
analysis procedures. There is the new science of pharmacoepidemiology,
and innovations in patient care, such as skilled clinical research
nursing at research institutions, have provided yet another level
of expertise applied to clinical research. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >In addition, various entities have become <I>de
facto</I> standard-setting organizations.  The newest ones, which
are rapidly becoming the most powerful, are managed-care organizations.
 As described above, these organizations exercise influence through
large-scale purchasing, control over their formularies, and drug
utilization review.  Formularies and drug utilization-review are
particularly powerful; physicians practicing within organizations
like HMOs are seeing their ability to prescribe increasingly constrained
or &quot;corrected&quot; by computerized &quot;governors,&quot;
in systems that perform overall integration of the medical record
for case management.  A physician might be prevented from prescribing
a drug if according to software filters it does not fit a patient's
listed diagnosis, or is excessive in dose or time of administration.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >While drug regulation has played a major role
in the elevation of standards to their present levels, these other
factors are essential and autonomous components that exist outside
FDA's  realm.  They are virtually independent, non-governmental
instruments that help to maintain research integrity, drug safety
and efficacy, and post-marketing surveillance.  Furthermore, FDA
is by no means the only world body that regulates drug approval
for safety and efficacy: a score of other countries (and now the
EU) have systems that perform reviews and achieve results that
are essentially similar to those of the United States -- and incidentally,
operate with staffs and budgets disproportionately smaller than
the FDA.  Indeed, as drugs become increasingly subject to these
various new controls before and after marketing approval, the
relative importance of FDA as a protector inevitably diminishes.
 This evolution must shape the reform of pharmaceutical regulation.
A regulatory system for the 21st century has to be different from
one crafted in 1962 when the problems were very different, and
the other elements of <I>de facto</I> regulation were almost non-existent.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT >The History of Regulatory Reform<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT >FDA is responsible for regulating the testing
and marketing of all new human and veterinary drugs.  FDA's basic
authority is embodied in the 1902 Public Health Service Act; the
1938 Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act; and 1962 amendments
to the Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act. The Public Health Service
Act mandates the <I>safety </I>regulation of biological drugs.
 The 1938 Act charged FDA with ensuring the <I>safety</I> of all
new drugs before they are released to the market (the NDA approval
process).  In 1962, partly in response to the thalidomide tragedy
in Europe, Congress imposed the additional requirement that a
new drug be shown to be <I>effective</I> as well as safe.  The
amendments also expanded the government's authority to regulate
clinical investigations of drugs (the IND process). Today all
preclinical and clinical research is conducted under FDA regulations
and policies.
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >It is striking that for decades, debates about
regulatory reform have identified the same problems and the same
solutions have been recommended by panel after distinguished panel.
These eminent and expert panels, including the McMahon Committee,
the Lasagna Committee, the Edwards Committee, and the Council
on Competitiveness have recommended both broad changes and specific
improvements that would reduce the time, cost, complexity, and
unpredictability of the process, and thereby prevent the loss
of potential therapies.  Because the agency has been too slow
and obdurate in implementing most of these repeated recommendations,
reform must come from outside the agency, via legislative changes.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > </FONT>
<P>
<FONT >A particular advantage of our proposal (to
be described in Section II) is that delegating a portion of the
oversight responsibility to non-governmental entities introduces
two basic improvements simultaneously: (i) an element of competition
among DCBs for drug companies' business, which creates pressure
for greater creativity and efficiency; and (ii) a more appropriate
balance between risks and rewards, incentives and disincentives
than presently exists.  These basic elements derive from first
principles of management and regulation.  The proposed mechanism
also contains safeguards to assure the integrity of the process,
including high-quality reviews.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT10-B18-102</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA015-000155-B041-270</DOCOLDNO>
