</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Achieving Reform Goals -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>

<h3>ACHIEVING THE GOALS OF REFORM</h3>
<P>
This
proposal outlines necessary reforms in the system of new drug
approval. It takes into account the need for high standards of
public safety and also the often-ignored need of patients to have
access to beneficial, sometimes potentially life-saving, new therapies.
It preserves some of the salient features of the present system,
and changes those that have become inefficient and unnecessarily
burdensome. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The existing system 1962 and, resistant to
reform, has become more complex and troubled over time.  Fundamental
changes have taken place in government, industry, and society
that call for a new, less antagonistic and monopolistic system
that fosters innovation, without sacrificing safety.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >At present, approximately 85 percent of New
Drug Applications are ultimately approved. However, given the
staggering costs and the length of time invested in drug development,
that 15 percent failure rate is extremely costly.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >This proposal offers a constructive approach
to responsible and responsive regulation.  While retaining responsibility
for the oversight of safety, the FDA sheds its day-to-day involvement
with the development of specific new drugs, leaving that to government-certified
organizations, the DCBs.  The new role for FDA emphasizes clarifying
and developing criteria for various categories of new drugs; monitoring
the DCBs; and working with the DCBs to eliminate wasted effort
and assure that when the recommendation for approval of a drug
is made to FDA, the agency will be able to approve it.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Under the proposed system, the spur to greater
efficiency and cost-effectiveness will be competition among the
DCBs, which will affect both the tactics and the strategy of drug
development and approval.  DCBs competition for sponsor-clients
will favor those that perform effective problem-solving for the
client, manage the oversight and review efficiently, and perform
reviews in a timely way.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Economic pressures will encourage the DCBs
to be competent and timely, and to cultivate a reputation for
integrity, because these traits will be most highly prized by
clients.  The enormous complexity and myriad alternatives at various
steps in the drug development process provide the DCB opportunities
to add value to the client's product.  Putting this another way,
just in the realm of clinical trials the choice of endpoints,
indications, and trial design strongly influences the size, time
and cost of development programs; therefore, there is vast potential
here for savings of time and money.  Subject to the legal standard
of safety and effectiveness, DCBs will be free to devise innovative
and more efficient ways of developing drugs and getting them approved.
  This strategic competition among DCBs and cooperation between
DCBs and sponsors will transform the drug development and approval
process and reverse the current trend of increasing time and costs.
</FONT>


<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
