<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: The Current System -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>

<h3>AN OVERVIEW OF THE MEDICAL DEVICE
INDUSTRY</h3>
<P>
<FONT >The medical device industry has been dominated
by the United States for many decades. American medical devices
are recognized world wide for quality and innovation. Of the approximately
50 billion dollars in United States production, 20 percent is
for the export market, producing a positive balance of payments.
Nevertheless, the industry's competitive position is very fragile
and our world leadership is now seriously threatened -- not from
external competition but from internal policy. Not only can this
have serious economic consequences, but the quality of our medical
care itself is now in jeopardy. A review of the unique circumstances
of the medical device industry, with an emphasis on the factors
which have fostered innovation, is useful in order to appreciate
how we have come to this state.<sup><a href="foot.html">1</a></sup><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >In sharp contrast with the pharmaceutical industry,
the medical device industry is composed of a very large number
of quite small companies. In 1993, 88 percent of medical device
companies had less than 100 employees.<sup><a href="foot.html">2</a></sup> Although there are a few
companies with sales exceeding a billion dollars, the typical
medical device company has sales in the 50 to 100 million dollar
range. Of the over 7,000 domestic medical device manufacturers,
approximately 1,000 are development companies with no sales at
all!<sup><a href="foot.html">3</a></sup> There are only about 150 firms with sales exceeding $100
million. The very largest medical device companies have total
sales equal to that of rather small pharmaceutical companies.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >One reason device companies are small is that
the market itself is extremely fragmented. For example, the total
U.S. market for anesthesia machines of all types is only about
3,000 units a year with a total value of barely $150 million.
 In contrast, the United States market for systemic antibiotics
or antihypertensives is five <I>billion</I> dollars per year.<sup><a href="foot.html">4</a></sup>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Medical device companies aggressively pursue
research and development. In 1993, while the median R&amp;D expenditure
as a percent of sales for all manufacturing companies was 4 percent,
it was over twice as much, 9 percent, in the medical device industry.
For companies with sales in the 5 to 20 million dollar range,
it was over 20 percent.<sup><a href="foot.html">5</a></sup> Not surprisingly, a very large proportion
of significant innovation occurs in the smallest companies with
the least sales. Venture capital is generally attracted to these
companies in the expectation that the product or the company itself
will be sold to a larger company in 5 to 7 years. While radically
new technologies attract public attention, much of the long term
improvement in medical devices comes from a myriad of small incremental
innovations which cumulatively, over time, have great clinical
relevance. The FDA is required by current law to review over 6,000
applications for such &quot;new&quot; devices a year, representing
the entire range of modern technology.<sup><a href="foot.html">6</a></sup> Much of the impetus for
such product improvements comes from physicians in the field.
Unimpeded communication between physicians (and other health care
personnel) and manufacturers is a requirement for much of this
activity. Likewise the ready availability of sites for device
testing in a clinical environment, generally in our academic health
centers,  is essential for innovation.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Finally, the relatively small size of the market
for any given medical device and the need for specialized material
for many of these devices results in device companies being critically
dependent on suppliers outside the medical device industry. Thus,
the device may be dependent on a small amount of a specialized
plastic, an esoteric metal or an electronic component. The device
company seldom has the resources to develop such materials, and,
because of the small amount needed, there is little financial
incentive for the supplier to provide them. Their availability
is a byproduct of a larger, non-medical, market.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The medical device industry is thus dependent
on multiple factors beyond its direct control, and any breakdown
of these complex relationships will threaten innovation by the
industry. Time is the biggest threat. Small companies have little
reserves and are dependent on fresh infusions of capital or on
current sales (if they exist) to finance innovation. Delays, or
the fear of delays, or even the unpredictability of delays, can
lead to financial disaster and frighten off venture capital. Such
delays can be related to the time required by the FDA to approve
clinical trials or to approve the device itself, among many other
causes. The delays interact. Thus increased FDA requirements for
human investigations, as the FDA attempts ever more to force the
device industry into a pharmaceutical regulatory model,<sup><a href="foot.html">7</a></sup> make the
system more sensitive to delays in approvals of such investigations.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >There are other delays in a new product's revenue
stream, not directly related to the FDA, that are very hazardous,
particularly to small companies. Since many innovations are incremental,
it is often good medical practice to use the device for routine
patient care while it is still the subject of human investigation.
If the investigational nature of a device prevents payment for
the device by government or private payers, the financial integrity
of the company may be threatened. Furthermore, if such use threatens
payment for any associated hospital or physician care, the health
care facility and physician may find it impractical to continue
interacting with the manufacturer, destroying a relationship needed
for continued product improvement. Finally, as U.S. academic health
centers come under more financial pressure, the opportunities
for clinical investigations decrease. The result of these forces,
coupled with FDA delays in approval of clinical investigation
protocols, has become  a potent incentive for American companiesto transfer some or all of their advanced research and development
offshore.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The product liability environment further discourages
innovation. First, many companies simply will not support the
development of new products in those areas of medicine most subject
to product liability suits, such as contraception and implantables,
as well as in entire medical specialties, such as anesthesia.
Where there were once many companies competing in the anesthesia
machine field, there are now only two significant U.S. based companies,
both of which are highly dependent on the export market. If, as
is the case, companies are liable under the doctrine of strict
liability (i.e., for any harmful event) rather than for actual
negligence, many companies will avoid intrinsically high risk
areas of medicine. The problem is compounded by the prevailing
doctrine of joint and several liability. Even if a company's actions
are only slightly related to an injury, it can be held liable
for the entire cost, if others sharing the liability have inadequate
assets. For this reason, a company producing a high-tech material,
(e.g., a plastic), which is used mostly for non-medical products,
has a huge incentive to prevent medical device companies from
having access to the material. The potential profit from the sale
of a small quantity for medical use is far less than the potential
liability or even the costs of litigation.<sup><a href="foot.html">8</a></sup><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Finally, third party payers are limiting the
technology for which they will pay. To survive in a managed care
environment, the industry must have the flexibility to turn its
innovative energies to developing products which, if they do not
dramatically improve health care, lower its costs.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT > </FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Currently, innovation is threatened by all
these factors simultaneously. The industry is over-regulated and
preyed upon by the plaintiffs' bar. Hobbled by these forces, it
is threatened by a new payor environment which has redefined what
sort of innovation is valued. The result in the last several years,
has been a decrease in the availability of venture capital; a
decrease in new product introduction in the United States; a trend
toward moving research and development as well as some manufacturing
to Europe; a decrease in the traditional growth of employment
opportunities in the United States; and, ultimately a delay in
the availability of medical technology needed by American patients.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Current market forces seeking to rationalize
health care costs should, if anything, provide new opportunities
for innovation in all areas of medicine, including medical devices.
Innovation would simply become more related to optimizing the
relationship of benefit to cost. Innovations in medical technology
can just as easily decrease as increase costs. The current revolution
in minimally invasive surgery and the consequent decrease in hospitalization
and time for recuperation is just one example of the potential
for technology to significantly decrease costs. Such market forces
are simply part of the environment that normally modulates the
growth and direction of an industry. Government regulation has
the perverse effect of constraining industry from rapidly adapting
to this changing environment.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
