</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: The EU System -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<br>
<h3>THE EU SYSTEM APPROVAL OF NEW MEDICAL
DEVICES</h3>
Much can be learned from the ongoing European
Union medical device regulatory reforms. Approval of new medical
devices in the EU is characterized by:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
1:<I> Objectivity    </I></FONT>
<P>
2: <I>Flexibility  </I></FONT>
<P>
3: <I>Timeliness</I>    </FONT>
<P>
4: <I>Competitiveness<BR>
</I></FONT>
<P>
The European Union medical device regulation
law is based on a list of &quot;Essential Requirements<sup><a href="foot.html">20</a></sup>.&quot;
These are universal requirements that apply to all devices. They
cover areas such as safe design and construction, clinical efficacy,
disclosure of residual risks, protective packaging, infection
control, compatibility with other devices, calibration and stability,
radiation protection, electrical safety, labeling, and instruction
manuals. In principle it is sufficient for the manufacturer to
rely solely on these requirements to justify putting a device
on the market. However, manufactures usually rely on published,
internationally agreed upon, standards which are specific to individual
devices or processes. For many decades, professional organizations
such as AAMI and IEEE in the United States and international standards
organizations such as ISO have brought together groups of experts
from the manufacturer, user and government sectors to develop
written standards covering a wide variety of topics. These include
very technical narrowly defined standards to ensure mechanical
compatibility, such as standards for machine screw threads; performance
standards for various materials, such as those for biocompatibility;
safety standards for the internal monitoring of life support equipment;
limits on electromagnetic radiation; as well as very broad standards
defining quality assurance for production, testing and even the
design process<sup><a href="foot.html">21</a></sup>. In the European system, such standards, originating
in various sources, are ultimately accepted by the EU's central
standards organization. While a manufacturer may choose to devise
alternate methods, adherence to such standards by the manufacturer
is presumptive evidence that the manufacturer has met the Essential
Requirements. Clearly defined standards provide objective criteria
and remove much of the uncertainty and risk in seeking approval.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Using published objective criteria related
to complexity and risk, all devices are placed in one of four
classes (I, IIa, IIb, III) by the manufacturer<sup><a href="foot.html">22</a></sup>. </FONT>
<P>
Examples are shown in Table 1.</FONT>
<P>
 <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
                                          
                TABLE 1</FONT>
<P>
                      Examples from the European
Device Classification System</FONT>
<P>
    </FONT>
<TABLE BORDERCOLOR=#000000 BORDER=1>

<TR><TD WIDTH=165><BR>
CLASS I</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=158><BR>
CLASS IIa</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=180><BR>
CLASS IIb</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=195><BR>
CLASS III</FONT></TD>
</TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=165><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2 >simple bandage</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >syringe   </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >surgical scalpel</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >wheel chair</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >glasses</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=158><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2 >hearing aid</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >diagnostic X-ray</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >blood filter</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >steam sterilizer</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >phototherapy unit</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=180><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2 >external pacemaker</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >hip implant</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >cardiac monitor</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >respiration monitor</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >barrier contraceptive</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=195><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2 >coronary stent</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >implantable pump*</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >heart valve</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >ventricular shunt</FONT> </FONT><FONT SIZE=2 >(brain)</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >implanted contraceptive</FONT>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >*active implantable devices are technically
regulated under a separate EU </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >regulation but from a practical standpoint
are handled like Class III devices<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
For the large number of devices in Class I,
the manufacturer self-certifies compliance with the Essential
Requirements by preparing a prescribed Declaration of Conformity,
a technical document containing the supporting data which is available
to the authorities. Certain special processes, such as sterilization
needed for a Class I device, may require additional certification
by a notified body,<I> vide infra</I>.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<U>Notified Bodies</FONT></U>
<P>
For all other devices, the manufacturer must
engage the services of an independent &quot;test house&quot; to
audit their systems or product and certify compliance with the
Essential Requirements. These test houses, termed &quot;notified
bodies&quot; in the European system and &quot;device certification
bodies,&quot; or DCB's in our proposed reform are themselves certified
(licensed), in accordance with published standards, by governmental
authorities. In Europe, the manufacturer may engage any notified
body from any country in the European Union. In practice, many
of the notified bodies come from the long tradition of test houses
which physically test production samples. They can be thought
of as being similar to analogous firms in the United States such
as Underwriter's Laboratories. Others come from the more recent
tradition of firms that certify quality assurance systems. There
are a large number of American firms that do similar work and
certify that manufacturers of all types conform to ISO 9000 quality
assurance standards. Many of the notified bodies are licensed
in specialized areas. <I>Objectivity</I> is ensured by the heavy
reliance on published, well constructed standards for both device
classification and regulatory compliance.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
In addition to being able to choose between
compliance with published standards and devising <I>ad hoc</I>
methods of compliance with the essential requirements, manufacturers
generally have the <I>flexibility</I> to choose between two fundamentally
different methods of demonstrating compliance with the Essential
Requirements. One method involves having the notified body actually
examine or test the entire production run (or statistically valid
samples of the production run) to confirm that applicable standards
have been met. The second method involves having the notified
body certify the manufacturer's quality assurance systems. These
include systems for testing the final product, producing the product
and/or designing the product. The notified body, in many instances,
can certify that the manufacturer has sufficient quality assurance
systems in place to self-certify individual products<sup><a href="foot.html">23</a></sup>. The specific
options available to the manufacturer depend on the class of the
device. In general, the higher class devices must adhere to more
stringent regulations. Examples of allowable compliance methods
are presented in Table II.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
                                          
               TABLE II</FONT>
<P>
Typical Examples of European Compliance Methods
for Different Device Classes</FONT>
<P>
 </FONT>
<TABLE BORDERCOLOR=#000000 BORDER=1>

<TR><TD WIDTH=353><BR>
CLASS I</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=353><BR>
CLASS IIa</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=353><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2 >Manufacturer prepares self-certification document (Notified body certifies sterilization processes, if applicable)</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=353><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2 >Notified body certifies full QA system</FONT>
<P>
<U><I><FONT SIZE=2 >or</FONT></I></U><FONT SIZE=2 >  inspects the final production</FONT>
<P>
<U><I><FONT SIZE=2 >or</FONT></I></U><FONT SIZE=2 > validates production quality assurance</FONT>
<P>
<U><I><FONT SIZE=2 >or</FONT></I></U><FONT SIZE=2 > validates product (final testing) quality assurance</FONT>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<TABLE BORDERCOLOR=#000000 BORDER=1>

<TR><TD WIDTH=353><BR>
CLASS IIb</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=353><BR>
CLASS III</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=353><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2 >Notified body certifies full QA system</FONT>
<P>
<U><I><FONT SIZE=2 >OR</FONT></I></U>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >Notified body certifies both the design</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >   <U><I>and</I></U> </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >compliance of a representative production sample</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 >      <U><I>and</I></U></FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >      inspects the final production</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 >      <U><I>or</I></U></FONT></I><FONT SIZE=2 > validates production quality assurance</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >      <U><I>or</I></U> validates product (final testing) quality</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >      assurance</FONT>
</TD><TD WIDTH=353><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2 >Notified body certifies full QA system</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >   <U><I>and</I></U></FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 > reviews device design</FONT>
<P>
<U><I><FONT SIZE=2 >OR</FONT></I></U>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >Notified body certifies both the design</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 >   <U><I>and</I></U></FONT></I><FONT SIZE=2 > </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >compliance of a representative production sample</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 >      <U><I>and</I></U></FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >      inspects the final production</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 >      <U><I>or</I></U></FONT></I><FONT SIZE=2 > validates production quality assurance</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2 >      <U><I>or</I></U></FONT></I><FONT SIZE=2 > validates product (final testing) quality </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 >      assurance</FONT>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
 <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Thus, manufacturers have the <I>flexibility</I>
to choose from a wide array of methods to comply with the device
regulations so that the process of bringing devices to the market
is facilitated. Methods may be chosen that are appropriate to
the company size, strengths and market. The result is that unnecessary
delays are avoided.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I>Timeliness</FONT></I>
of approvals is critical. One of the largest sources of complaints
concerning our current system is the time required to get through
the regulatory approval process. Although the FDA has recently
attempted to expedite the process, 510(k)s and PMA's have taken
far longer that the statutory 90 and 180 days to complete the
process. The profitability associated with bringing a new device
to the market, and thus the practicality of devoting resources
to innovation, is critically dependent on the amount of time it
takes. A delay has at least three deleterious effects. First,
more venture (or internal) capital is needed to support the product
during a prolonged development phase. Second, an income stream
needed to provide an adequate return on capital is delayed. Finally,
during the delay, competitors may become established in the market
place. The European system attacks the problem of timeliness directly
by not allowing anyone to have a monopoly on approval authority.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
A basic problem in the U.S. medical device
regulatory system is that the FDA has had a legal monopoly on
approvals and, if it takes longer than what is reasonable, the
manufacturer has no alternative options. By opening up the process
to competition and allowing the manufacturer the option of choosing
which notified body to engage, the Europeans have essentially
obviated the entire problem. In addition, for many devices, especially
when certified high level quality assurance mechanisms are in
place, the manufacturer may gain additional flexibility and save
time by being allowed to self-certify that the essential requirements
have been met. This problem with timeliness of approvals probably
has been the primary reason some of our best device companies
have shifted new product development to Europe<sup><a href="foot.html">24</a></sup>. Their goal is
to obtain expeditious approval so that they can establish an early
revenue stream so as to produce a return on their large capital
investment<sup><a href="foot.html">25</a></sup>. The Wilkerson Group<sup><a href="foot.html">26</a></sup> has complied a list of 100 devices
which are currently available in other developed nations but which
are unavailable to the American patient.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
The European system objective takes advantage
of <I>competitiveness</I> is two separate areas. First, the notified
bodies compete with each other on the basis of price, timeliness
and availability. Our DCB's will function in the same manner.
In addition, since a European manufacturer can engage a notified
body from another country (which was certified by that country's
authorities), there is also jurisdictional competition which acts
as a check on the government itself. If the United States and
the European Union were able to sufficiently harmonize their systems
so as to allow mutual recognition of device approvals, we would
be able to emulate that aspect of the European system.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
