</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: A New Proposal -- PFF</TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<br>
<h3>A NEW REGULATORY REFORM PROPOSAL</h3>

<FONT >The FDA itself has publicized its efforts to
speed approvals and is investigating contracting out some of its
functions to non-governmental bodies. Devising a more reasonable
regulatory structure is made easier by the fact the European Union
has accomplished just that. Not only is their experience useful,
but bilateral trade would be facilitated if the system we adopt
is similar enough to theirs that device approval on both sides
of the Atlantic could be accomplished with minimal duplicative
effort and cost.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Alternative paths to reform which would simply
seek to curb the worst governmental abuses without fundamentally
changing the structure are inadequate. The basic 1976 law was
predicated on a device classification system based on performance
standards that were never developed. Approval of most new devices
was based on &quot;substantial equivalence&quot; to previously
approved devices. Not only was the meaning of &quot;substantial
equivalence&quot; never adequately defined, but the entire concept
of similarity with predicate devices must, by necessity, break
down over time as technology advances and the thread of similarity
with older devices becomes weaker. It is as if the space shuttle
was to be approved based on its substantial equivalence with an
ox cart. Finally, faced with the lack of objective criteria for
action, the FDA has become, at best, a cautious and ponderous
bureaucracy. This was predictable and no amount of cosmetic reform
will change the forces which have caused this bureaucratic evolution.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The new European Union medical device regulatory
system offers a more rational structure. The EU system has been
in full effect since 1992 for the most complex and risky medical
devices, active implantables; since the beginning of 1995 for
other medical devices; and is soon to be phased in for <I>in vitro</I>
diagnostic devices. U.S. manufactures have gained experience with
the EU system through two mechanisms. First, many U.S. companies
export to Europe and are thus fully subject to the EU system.
In response, the European notified bodies are well represented
in the United States. More fundamentally, over the years, American
professional organizations have been very active in publishing
standards which ultimately have become the international standards
that form the basis of the EU system. This includes both the thousands
of narrowly defined standards that guide details of design and
also more fundamental standards, such as the ISO 9000 series,
which form the basis of modern quality control systems. In fact
most major American medical device manufacturers either have obtained
or are in the process of obtaining ISO 9000 (series) certification.
Full ISO 9000 certification is significantly more comprehensive
than the GMP regulations currently administered by the FDA as
it includes a quality control system for the design process itself.
Full conformity with these standards, frequently reconfirmed,
allows medical device companies subject to the EU system the authority
to self-certify new products of moderate complexity. This then
allows a very rapid design-marketing cycle, so important to facilitate
the incremental nature of medical device innovation. Because of
the familiarity of American manufacturers with both the EU system
and the standards upon which it is based, it should be possible
for the United States to make a rapid transition to this more
rational and modern system of medical device approval. No doubt
there would have to be a transition period with both the old and
the new approval systems available, especially for devices already
in the approval process. In addition it would seem prudent, at
least until the new system is well established in this country
for the FDA to be notified of each DCB Class III device approval
sufficiently in advance of marketing (90 days) to allow confirmation
that the appropriate standards had been used.  Since the FDA is
a member of international standards organizations, this would
have the further advantage of providing information useful in
drafting new standards. Figures 1 and 2 compare our current approval
process and the proposed replacement approval process.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<IMG SRC="IMG00017.GIF"><IMG SRC="IMG00018.GIF"><FONT >Adapting
the EU system of device approvals essentially privatizes two important
functions of the FDA: device approvals and GMP (quality assurance)
inspections. There are other FDA functions that need to be considered.
In the EU system, the health authorities of each individual county
have five major functions. They have the responsibility and authority
to license the notified bodies. This is done in reference to internationally
agreed upon standards. Two, administer a post-marketing &quot;vigilance&quot;
system that monitors unexpected failures and adverse effects of
the products. Three, have the authority to remove products from
the market which prove to be out of conformity with the essential
requirements. Four, are responsible for controlling the safety
of human subjects in clinical investigations. Finally, they have
investigative authority and serve to keep the system honest. One
defining characteristic of the EU system is that the manufacturer,
not the government, is primarily responsible for the safety and
effectiveness of their product. The private notified body is a
check on the manufacturer and is in the tradition of a testing
laboratory. The government health authority polices the system.
Most importantly, although the manufacturer must demonstrate (to
the satisfaction of the notified body) that the device is as safe
as is practical according to the state of the art and that it
functions effectively as claimed on its labeling and in its instruction
manual, the final judgement as to relative clinical benefit and
risk is left to the practice of medicine and to those forces which
regulate it.<sup><a href="foot.html">27</a></sup><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >With a few limitations, a reformed U.S. system
should follow this outline. The FDA's current vigilance system
for medical devices is so overwhelmed with data that it has been
of little use. Since manufacturers already are required to collect
and analyze data concerning device malfunctions and adverse effects,
it would seem reasonable for the manufacturer to have the opportunity
to do the preliminary analysis and pass onto the FDA only those
reports where there is a reasonable possibility that there was
a device problem<sup><a href="foot.html">28</a></sup>. The manufacturer would, of course, have to maintain
records of all reports and their analysis for inspection by their
DCB (and in the case of concern, by the FDA). The FDA, as the
recipient of data from all manufacturers could then perform the
important function of correlating adverse reports concerning the
same type of product produced by several different manufacturers.
It also would be able to monitor individual manufacturer's response
to reports concerning their own devices. In addition the FDA would
be in a position to exchange information with the European Union
authorities. This might facilitate the handling of adverse events
that are so rare that data from multiple countries are needed.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >In the United States, Institutional Review
Boards, especially those in the academic health centers, have
generally functioned well to both protect the interests of patients
and subjects and to facilitate research. However, it would be
reasonable for the FDA to function as a repository of data concerning
all adverse events during clinical investigations, as such a national
clearing house with access to data from many sites might facilitate
the early detection of rare events.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >With these few modifications, a reformed American
medical device regulatory system would closely follow the EU model.
The FDA would become a smaller, better focused organization with
many of their functions assumed by organizations in the private
sector.<BR>
<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
