</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Role of Tort Law -- PFF </TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<br>
<h3>The Role of Tort Law</h3>
<P>
<FONT >By imposing costs on the tortfeasor, the liability
system generates both incentives for efficient risk avoidance
as well as compensation for accident victims.  In the case of
monetary losses, both strict liability and negligence standards
will lead to an efficient level of precautions and will lead to
an optimal level of compensation for the accident victim.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Matters become somewhat different in the case
of health effects.  It is very difficult to compensate an individual
for an extreme loss of health status, such as one's life, since
finite amounts of compensation may not make one whole.  The amount
of compensation that would be needed to generate efficient incentives
would be quite large.  An efficient level of damages from a deterrence
standpoint would provide adequate financial incentive to lead
the manufacture to sell products that had an optimal level of
safety when valued using the preferences for safety of the consumer.
 How, for example, do the values of greater safety compare with
the higher cost levels of safer products?  For example, evidence
on the implicit value of life that is appropriate from the standpoint
of deterring risks is $5 million per life.  However, this amount
is not an appropriate guide for insurance and compensation.  Few
individuals would choose to purchase an insurance policy that
would make a payoff of this size in the event of their death.
 As a result, compensation amounts of this magnitude would provide
efficient incentives for deterrence but would provide excessive
insurance.  Consequently, one could view the current tort system
as somewhat split in that the amount of compensation is more closely
linked to the optimal insurance amount, such as the present value
of lost earnings, medical costs, and some compensation for pain
and suffering.  In contrast, the criteria for liability are linked
to generating efficient standards for safety.  Thus, the firm's
obligation is to provide an adequate level of safety for the good,
where this level of adequacy is what would prevail if a good were
traded in a fully functioning and efficient market.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The responsibilities of tort liability to provide
incentives for safety and compensation to accident victims depend
of course on the other societal institutions in place.  If, for
example, an individual at risk were compensated through the workers'
compensation system, there would be less need for compensation
through the tort liability system.  Similarly, if the risk level
and the adequacy of warnings is handled through a regulatory structure
that ensures an efficient level of precautions, then there is
no rationale from the standpoint of adequate deterrence for having
tort liability.  Thus, to the extent that the FDA regulations
achieve the social objective of efficient levels of control of
risk, then there is no need to duplicate this function through
additional tort liability.  The obvious exception is that in which
the company withholds critical information from the regulatory
agency so that the regulation cannot be set in an ideal manner.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Government regulations can of course be set
either too leniently or too stringently.  The fact that there
is a government regulation does not necessarily imply that there
is no role for any supplementary social institution, such as tort
liability.  However, in the case of the FDA, the general consensus
is that these regulations are certainly adequate in ensuring safety
and, to the extent that there is any divergence from optimality,
it is that the regulations are excessively stringent with respect
to the promotion of product safety.  If there is already over-deterrence,
there is consequently no rationale for bolstering of the level
of deterrence additionally through incentives provided through
tort liability.  This consideration pertains to the deterrence
or incentive role of tort liability, not necessarily to the compensation
function since regulations do not provide for the compensation
of accident victims.  However, at least from the standpoint of
safety incentives, the optimal use of regulations is to target
them in areas where there are clearly inadequate safety incentives
provided.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >There is a widespread consensus in the literature
that the current FDA drug approval process establishes safety
incentives that are excessive.<sup><a href="foot.html">17</a></sup>  The stringency of the process
and the meticulous review of new pharmaceutical drugs is reflected
in the substantial delays that U.S. consumers have experienced
with respect to the introduction of new pharmaceutical products.
 These delays are much greater than in other countries, such as
those in Europe, which also have regulatory procedures to ensure
drug safety.  Studies have also shown that because of these delays
Americans have been prevented from having access to new drugs
with beneficial effects, as the agency places a greater weight
on errors of commission rather than errors of omission.  This
imbalance in the emphasis for these two types of errors has led
to excessive deterrence of new risks that may be created by pharmaceutical
products and inadequate weight on reducing existing risks that
patients now experience.  Because these incentives already ensure
a degree of caution and safety with respect to introducing new
pharmaceutical products that is already excessive, one would not
want to further deter companies from introducing beneficial new
products through additional tort liability sanctions.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >One possible counterargument is that after
the drug is approved it may turn out to have adverse effects that
were not anticipated.  However, the task regarding the safety
and efficacy of the product is to make the best judgement that
is possible at the time the product is marketed.  If new information
becomes available to indicate that the product is riskier than
was initially believed, then the company should be held responsible
for acting upon this new information in a reasonable manner and
developing new labeling if necessary.  This way of dealing with
new information is the approach taken in Europe with respect to
medical devices in which companies have a &quot;development-risk&quot;
defense.  Companies are free of liability in the tort liability
regime in all EU countries other than Luxembourg if they can show
that the &quot;state of scientific and technical knowledge at
the time when he put the product into circulation was not such
as to enable the existence of the defect to be discovered.&quot;
 This state of the information defense coupled with a requirement
that companies meet the regulatory standards would ensure than
an efficient degree of product safety be provided both at the
time of the product's introduction as well as throughout the product's
life.  Once this has been assured, there is no additional rationale
for augmenting these safety incentives, at least from the standpoint
of risk prevention.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Off-label uses and their relation to a regulatory
compliance defense is an important issue.  The restrictions that
are pertinent for advertising drugs for off-label usage are now
quite stringent<sup><a href="foot.html">18</a></sup>.  For example, in the case of investigational
new drugs that are currently undergoing clinical study, it is
not possible to promote the drug for the usage that is currently
under scrutiny.  Notwithstanding these restrictions on the promotion
of pharmaceutical products, it is generally believed that off-label
usage are quite prevalent, particularly in the cases of AIDS and
cancer treatments.  Much of pediatric age group drug use is also
off-label.  One survey suggested that nearly one-third of the
prescriptions of oncologists for cancer patients were for off-label
usage.  In addition, an estimated 56 percent of cancer patients
have received at least one drug under an off-label purpose.  
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The degree to which there is insurance reimbursement
for off-label usages depends in large part on the nature of the
experimental treatment and the existence of medical evidence supporting
its reliability.  Many off-label treatments for cancer, for example,
are not reimbursed.  Approximately one-half of 681 oncologists
surveyed by the U.S. General Accounting Office reported that at
some point they had been denied reimbursement for the costs of
an off-label prescription<sup><a href="foot.html">19</a></sup>.  That same U.S. General Accounting
Office survey also found that one-third of all the prescriptions
involving cancer chemotherapy involved off-label uses.  Among
the most controversial reimbursements for off-label usage has
been the insurance coverage for the high dose chemotherapy-autologous
bone marrow transplants, which is an expensive and risky treatment.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Strict adherents to regulatory criteria might
speculate that all off-label uses are inappropriate and should
not be undertaken since they have not been accorded FDA approval.
 However, in many instances the opposite conclusion has been reached.<sup><a href="foot.html">20</a></sup>
 The courts have ruled, for example, that Medicaid coverage could
not exclude AZT therapy for an off-label purpose for some classes
of AIDS patients.  Similarly, the courts have ruled that Blue
Cross-Blue Shield must reimburse high dose chemotherapy-autologous
bone marrow transplants.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >As Christopher (1993) notes, the nature of
the New York legal provisions with respect to off-label usage
is quite complex: &quot;New York forbids insurers from excluding
coverage of off-label uses of cancer drugs if: (1) prescription
drugs are otherwise covered in the policy; (2) the drug is FDA-approved
for some form of cancer; and (3) the off-label use in question
is recognized by one of the three compendia or recommended by
review article or editorial comment in a major peer-reviewed journal.&quot;
 However, he goes on to note that: &quot;The New York law, however,
allows insurers to exclude from coverage off-label uses expressly
contraindicated by FDA-approved labelling and experimental or</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >investigational drugs.&quot;<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The nature of the regulatory compliance defense
is somewhat complicated by the use of drugs for off-label purposes.
 The regulatory criteria and the assurance that the drug has met
efficient standards for safety only pertains to uses for which
the drug has been specifically approved, or those uses specified
on the label.  In the case of off-label uses, there has not been
the same kind of review and approval that would provide an ex
ante guarantee that the firm has met its obligations with respect
to safety and efficacy for these uses.  As a result, in the case
of the off-label uses the regulatory compliance defense that is
advocated here would not be pertinent.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The practical consequences of this distinction
for off-label uses may be substantial.  It has been estimated
that about half of all drugs prescribed by doctors are given for
off-label uses because the drug is believed to be effective for
these off-label purposes.  At a fairly pedestrian level, one has
doctors prescribing Retin-A for middle aged patients who wish
to eliminate wrinkles even though this is not an on-label purpose
of this anti-acne drug.  Perhaps more importantly in terms of
individual welfare is that many cancer treatments involve off-label
uses of drugs.  At present there are no requirements that physicians
disclose to patients that the particular therapy being prescribed
is an off-label usage.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Whereas there is currently no regulatory compliance
defense in the case of pharmaceuticals, in the case of medical
devices, the 1976 Medical Devices Amendments pre-empted liability
claims against medical devices.  Pre-emption is stronger than
a regulatory compliance defense in that it forecloses all product
liability suits.  The 1995 case of <U>Michael v. Shiley, Inc.</U>
found that these Amendments pre-empted all liability actions involving
negligence, strict liability, and breech of warranty for medical
devices.<sup><a href="foot.html">21</a></sup>  This pre-emption includes all medical devices, not simply
the class III medical devices that are subject to the formal FDA
pre-market approval process.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The main exception to such broad interpretations
of the regulatory compliance defense was the recent decision by
the Ninth Circuit in <U>Kennedy v. Collagen Corp</U><sup><a href="foot.html">22</a></sup>.  In this
case, the court upheld pre-emption only when the FDA had enacted
&quot;specific counterpart requirements&quot; applicable to the
device.  Since the court viewed the pre-market approval process
for Class III devices as not constituting a Federal &quot;requirement,&quot;
the scope of the pre-emption would be severely restricted<sup><a href="foot.html">23</a></sup>.  To
date, this decision remains the exception, as other courts have
interpreted the exemption provisions quite broadly.<BR>
</FONT>
<P><b>Punitive Damages<BR>
</b>

<P>
<FONT >The role of the regulatory compliance defense
has been most prominent with respect to punitive damages rather
than with respect to the overall liability of pharmaceutical and
medical device firms.  Although it will be suggested below that
regulatory compliance should be a defense with respect to all
tort liability, it is even more compelling that punitive damages
are not warranted if a firm has fulfilled all of its regulatory
obligations and has not withheld information from the regulatory
agency.  Groups such as the American Law Institute (1991) have
indicated that abolition of punitive damages in such instances
of regulatory compliance is a particularly desirable reform.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >To see why punitive damages reforms head the
list of necessary changes in tort law, let us examine the circumstances
under which punitive damages above and beyond compensatory damages
are awarded and why these damages are not pertinent when pharmaceutical
and medical device companies have complied with government regulations.
 One rationale for punitive damages may be that compensatory damages
alone do not provide adequate deterrence when life and health
are at risk.  This argument is certainly correct from an economic
standpoint, but the role of optimal deterrence will have already
been addressed through regulatory compliance.  If a firm has already
met regulatory standards that ensure a level of safety that is
either efficient or is a more stringent safety level than dictated
by economic efficiency concerns, then there is no additional economic
rationale for punitive damages to augment the safety requirements.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >A second rationale for punitive damages is
that they would be warranted if the company's safety efforts fell
well below what was required to provide an efficient level of
safety with respect to the product.  If a firm has not met the
requirements stipulated by the regulation, then certainly punitive
damages may be warranted.  However, if all the regulatory stipulations
with respect to testing and information provision have been met,
then it is not possible that a company's safety efforts could
have fallen greatly below what should be expected since these
expectations are already set out through the regulatory guidelines.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >This kind of regulatory compliance defense
may not be warranted with respect to every form of government
regulation.  However, the FDA regulations for pharmaceuticals
differ both in their nature and their stringency.  The distinctive
character of pharmaceutical regulations is that they are extremely
meticulous regulations that entail the premarket review of the
product, extensive testing of the product, a determination of
the safety and efficacy of the product, a provision of risk information
through a procedure that conforms with a highly structured warnings
vocabulary, and post-market surveillance.  These stipulations
certainly go well beyond what might be envisioned by a jury in
any particular case. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Another possible objective of punitive damages
is compensation.  However, this objective should already have
been adequately handled by the compensatory aspect of damages.
 The standard components of tort liability are designed to address
the efficient levels of compensation needed by accident victims.
 If, for example, the courts were to routinely award punitive
damages, this practice would not even be in the interest of consumers
of these products.  Higher liability costs will raise the cost
of producing the product, which in turn will raise the product
price.  In effect, purchasers of a product will be paying for
the higher punitive damage awards through more expensive products.<sup><a href="foot.html">24</a></sup>
 Payments of this type are desirable in the case of compensatory
damages that replicate the kinds of insurance that individuals
would have purchased freely.  However, if individuals would not
have purchased insurance to provide for the kinds of compensation
associated with punitive damages, then in effect, a liability
regime that imposes excessive punitive damages will have forced
customers to buy more insurance for their accident losses than
they would have chosen to provide for themselves if they could
have designed such an insurance mechanism.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >A final objective of punitive damages might
be that of retribution.  Although additional penalties on a firm
do serve as a form of retributive punishment, one must also inquire
whose interest such punishment promotes.  If adequate deterrence
and safety incentives are already ensured, retributive punishment
is not needed.  From the standpoint of the consumers of the product,
retributive punishment will not be in their interests if the higher
product price that they must pay for the litigated products reflects
the added costs imposed by such retribution.  Although there may
be instances in which customers will be willing to pay higher
prices for products to know that damages will be assessed to punish
companies, one would expect that such willingness would be associated
with flagrant disregards of safety.  If the company in fact met
regulatory guidelines for efficient provision of safe products,
then there should be little support for retributive punishment
such as this.  If there were such support, then that presumably
would be an indication of a societal preference for even more
stringent pharmaceutical and medical device safety standards than
are now in place.  Thus, a shift in the regulatory guidelines
to promote greater safety levels in response to the preferences
of consumers could ensure that these retributive preferences were
represented without having to rely on punitive damages.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Once the efficient level of safety has been
provided, punitive damages are not innocuous.  Imposing punitive
damages will deter companies from innovating products that might
potentially be subject to punitive damages, such as contraceptives.
 Similarly, companies will have an incentive to exit the market
altogether in an effort to avoid punitive damages, as has been
the case with respect to the production of vaccines.  Deterring
innovations and promoting market exit is not desirable if these
actions are the result of sanctions that are not linked to a provision
of an efficient degree of safety but in fact are imposed on the
firm even if appropriate safety standards have been met.<BR>
</FONT>
<P><b>The Current Common Law Approach<BR>
</b>

<P>
<FONT >Although there have been many discussions of
the regulatory compliance defense for FDA-approved products with
respect to punitive damages, the position taken here will be that
there also should be a regulatory compliance with respect to liability
more generally.  To examine the rationale for this defense, we
must first examine the current status of tort liability as well
as its linkage to the pharmaceutical industry.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Most observers attribute the tort liability
revolution to the emergence of strict liability as well as subsequent
developments in tort law.  The American Law Institute's Restatement
(Second) of Torts was a pivotal document that codified the strict
liability doctrine and indicated that this doctrine would replace
negligence as the preferred theory of liability.<sup><a href="foot.html">25</a></sup>  Section 402a
imposes liability on a firm if the product is &quot;in a defective
condition, unreasonably dangerous&quot; even though &quot;all
possible care&quot; was exercised &quot;in the preparation and
sale of the product.&quot;  This standard consequently is more
stringent than the negligence standard which only required that
an efficient level of safety be provided for the firm to be free
of liability.  For example, additional company expenditures on
safety are desirable so long as the marginal safety benefits exceed
the marginal safety costs.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >It is noteworthy that the original drafters
of Restatement (Second) of Torts apparently did not envision that
these criteria were to be applied to &quot;unavoidably unsafe
products,&quot; such as drugs and vaccines:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT >Unavoidably unsafe products.</FONT></I><FONT >
 There are some products which, in the present state of human
knowledge, are quite incapable of being made safe for their intended
and ordinary use.  These are especially common in the field of
drugs.  An outstanding example is the vaccine for the Pasteur
treatment of rabies, which not uncommonly leads to very serious
and damaging consequences when it is injected.  Since the disease
itself invariable leads to a dreadful death, both the marketing
and the use of the vaccine are fully justified, notwithstanding
the unavoidably high degree of risk which they involve.  Such
a product, properly prepared, and accompanied by proper directions
and warnings, is not defective, nor is it unreasonably dangerous.
 The same is true of many other drugs, vaccines, and the like,
many of which for this reason cannot legally be sold except to
physicians or under the prescription of a physician.  It is also
true in many new or experimental drugs as to which, because of
the lack of time and opportunity for sufficient medical experience,
there can be no assurance of safety ... but such experience as
there is justifies the marketing and use of the drug notwithstanding
a medically recognizable risk.  The seller of such products, again
with the qualification that they are properly prepared and marketed,
and proper warning is given, where the situation calls for it,
is not to be held to strict liability for unfortunate consequences
attending their use, merely because he has undertaken to supply
the public with an apparently useful and desirable product, attended
with a known but apparently reasonable risk.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Thus, pharmaceutical products were to be exempted
from these criteria. Not-withstanding this distinction, the judicial
interpretations eventually broadened the &quot;unreasonably dangerous&quot;
test and began to focus on what constituted &quot;defectiveness.&quot;
 In <U>Barker v. Lull Engineering Company</U><sup><a href="foot.html">26</a></sup>, the court ruled
[a] product is defective in design either (1) if the product has
failed to preform as safely as an ordinary consumer would expect
when used in an intended or reasonably foreseeable manner or (2)
if, in the light of development factors discussed below, the benefits
of the challenged design do not outweigh the risk of danger inherent
in such design.  In subsequent years, both risk-utility tests
and consumer expectation tests proliferated, and it is the general
consensus that the risk-utility test is more appropriate. <sup><a href="foot.html">27</a></sup> The
manufacturer should not be liable for what the consumer might
expect since these expectations need in no way be reasonable,
but a risk-utility test that has a parallel with an economic benefit-cost
test certainly is pertinent.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The most prevalently used risk-utility test
is that developed by Dean Wade.<sup><a href="foot.html">28</a></sup>  That test consists of a variety
of factors that would affect the desirability of the product,
where all but one of these factors is subsumed into a conventional
benefit-cost test.  The one distinctive factor is that the producer
serves in an insurance role for accident victims through the tort
liability awards for product injuries.  It is this insurance role
that underlies the development of strict liability more generally.
 The general notion is that firms provide insurance for consumers
of products through tort liability, where these insurance costs
are transmitted to consumers through higher product prices.  This
theory is sound in the case of rare event product accidents such
as that associated with isolated manufacturing defects, but this
analogy breaks down in the case of mass toxic torts.  The costs
imposed by large scale litigation such as the Dalkon Shield case
cannot be shifted to consumers.  Moreover, it is not feasible
for the company to bear such large scale costs.  The result has
been that many firms have exited the market with respect to development
of new contraceptives and production of vaccines because of the
large scale of these costs.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Pharmaceutical companies have not escaped the
impact of strict liability.  Several jurisdictions have found
that as a matter of law pharmaceutical products are not unavoidably
unsafe.<sup><a href="foot.html">29</a></sup>  More importantly, the courts have not ruled that compliance
with the FDCA provides a defense in the case of product liability
actions.  Pharmaceutical companies have also been found liable
with respect to the development of new liability doctrines with
respect to hazard warnings even though these warnings are specifically
approved by the FDA and developed in accordance with a highly
structured warnings vocabulary specified by the FDA.  At the present
time, the majority of all courts do not recognize the FDA regulatory
compliance defense with respect to overall liability of the firm.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The effects in the absence of regulatory compliance
defense have been quite striking.  Producers of the DPT vaccine,
for example, were exposed to substantial liability that led to
considerable caution throughout the vaccine market.  Since 1968,
the number of vaccine manufacturers in the United States has dropped
by more than 50 percent.  The American vaccine market is now controlled
by single producer monopolies in the case of vaccines for polio,
rubella, measles, mumps, and rabies.  There are similar kinds
of monopolies for many pediatric vaccines as well.  The substantial
costs of tort liability consequently have led to the exit of the
market of substantial markets concentration for vaccines.  The
result has been a considerable rise in the price of vaccines,
well in excess of the inflation rate.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >There have been, of course, changes in the
vaccine areas that have been prompted by the effects of the liability
burden.  In particular, Congress passed the Childhood Vaccine
Injury Act of 1986 in order to replace the burdensome tort litigation
process with an administrative compensation system.  Even in the
case of vaccines, this legislation has not completely eliminated
the tort liability problems.  Many vaccines, such as the chicken
pox vaccine, are not covered by the provisions of the act.  In
addition, this administrative compensation system, which is financed
by a tax on the pharmaceutical companies, requires that claimants
file claims through this program, but the claimant is free to
reject this award and can pursue a tort action under state law
if the claimant views the award as unsatisfactory.  An additional
deterrent to competition in the vaccine industry is that once
firms exited the market for vaccines, it was difficult to reenter.
 Thus, this major liability reform in the vaccine area should
be viewed as an incomplete remedy for the liability problems that
existed.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >To the extent that there has been any exemption
it has been with respect to punitive damages.  Thus far, there
are five states - Arizona, New Jersey, Ohio, Oregon, and Utah
- that have provided for an FDA regulatory compliance defense
against punitive damages.  There has been no punitive damage defense
adopted through Federal legislation, although such a defense is
frequently included in draft bills.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Medical devices are regulated under the 1976
Amendments to the Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act.  Companies
are permitted to market class I medical devices, such as tongue
depressors without government approval.  Class II medical devices,
such as hearing aids, were formerly required to meet government
approved performance standards, and class III medical devices,
such as heart valves, still must undergo a process similar to
that for pharmaceuticals.  In particular, there is a pre-market
approval process for such devices.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The liability regime for pharmaceuticals is
in striking context to medical devices.  The Medical Devices Amendments
of 1976, which were amendments to FDCA, grant a pre-emption defense
for medical devices that is similar in spirit but stronger than
a regulatory compliance defense.  Indeed, in the recent 1995 case
of Michael D. Shiley, Inc., the court ruled that the medical devices
amendments of 1976 pre-empt actions involving negligence, strict
liability, and breach of implied warranty for medical devices.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >In the case of medical devices, there is not
only pre-emption of cases under Federal law but also claims under
state law as well.  In particular, in 1995 the U.S. Court of Appeals
for the First Circuit ruled that the Medical Device Amendments
to the Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act pre-empted all state tort
claims.  Moreover, this pre-emption was held to be true even if
the manufacturer defrauded the Food and Drug Administration and
did not in fact achieve regulatory compliance.<sup><a href="foot.html">30</a></sup>  The defrauding
company was, however, subject to criminal fines for conspiracy
to defraud the FDA and was required to pay total fines of $61
million.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >What is striking about this regulatory compliance
defense, in contrast with the treatment of pharmaceuticals, is
that only class three medical devices (devices that are implanted
under the skin) are subject to premanufacturing review.  The more
minor class I and II devices are not subject to premanufacturing
review, although they are subject to postmarketing surveillance
by the FDA.  The irony of this distinction is that in contrast
with exhaustive pre-marketing review of pharmaceuticals, which
often takes up to a decade, the device approval process has been
estimated to take an average of one year.<sup><a href="foot.html">31</a></sup><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >This discrepancy has even led to an important
anomaly in terms of product treatment.  The Copper-7 intrauterine
device was in fact a medical device, not a pharmaceutical.  However,
before the passage of the medical device amendments of 1968, there
needed to be some means of classifying this product, and FDA chose
to classify it as a pharmaceutical.  If this product had in fact
been regulated under the subsequently promulgated Medical Device
Amendments of 1976, the firm would have been free of its ultimately
substantial liability.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The overall policy proposal of this report
is to make the regulatory compliance defense more symmetric for
both pharmaceutical products and medical devices.  Although a
regulatory compliance defense for pharmaceutical products will
not be as strong as the pre-emption given to medical devices,
it will create more similar legal framework.  The premanufacturing
review process for pharmaceuticals is much more stringent than
for medical devices.  The criteria involved ensure the safety
and efficacy of the product based on the best available state
of the information at the time.  There is no rationale for continuing
the distinction that puts pharmaceutical products at such a substantial
relative disadvantage.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
