<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Legal Implications of Revision -- PFF </TITLE></HEAD><BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small>
<br>
<h3>Legal Implication of a Revised Approval Process</h3><BR>

<P>
<FONT >We have outlined sweeping proposals for the
revision of the pharmaceutical and medical device approvals.<sup><a href="foot.html">32</a></sup> 
The essential elements of this proposal would be to privatize
the review process for new drugs and pharmaceuticals and to foster
competition in this review process.  In the case of pharmaceuticals,
the Drug Certifying Bodies would approve the IND for the drug,
oversee the clinical development, review the NDA, and certify
that the product is safe and effective.  After this review process
was completed, the FDA would have responsibility for the final
sign off in a highly structured review process.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Delegating these responsibilities to private
entities does not necessarily create any legal problems.  Government
agencies, including the FDA, frequently draw on the expertise
and input of private parties in a variety of regulatory areas.
 What is essential, however, is that this delegation of responsibility
be handled in a sound manner to avoid any constitutional problem
that might arise in the delegation of legislative power.<sup><a href="foot.html">33</a></sup><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >In the case of medical devices, the manufacturing
and/or Device Certifying Body would be responsible for compliance
with established standards-based criteria.  In the case of the
highest risk devices, the FDA would do a review and confirm that
proper standards had been used.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >In each case, there would be no compromise
in the safety and efficacy levels of products as compared to the
current regime.  The ultimate sign-off for these products would
also be the responsibility of the Food and Drug Administration
as would the overall character of the safety criteria.  The same
kinds of regulatory compliance defenses that would be sound proposals
under the current product liability and regulatory regime would
also be pertinent if the plan's proposals were adopted.  Thus,
if companies were in compliance with the government regulation
as administered under this new process, then the level of safety
provided by the company would be efficient, thus meeting the safety
objectives of either a negligence or strict liability standard.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Under the revised plan review process, the
Device Certifying Bodies and Drug Certifying Bodies would have
a critical role in the review process.  What, however, would be
the ultimate liability of these certifying bodies?  In the absence
of specific legal exemptions, these bodies potentially could be
subject to the usual liability criteria notably negligence and
strict liability.  If, however, thh2>IV. Regulatory Reform and Lia
liability then there would be a substantial deterrent for any
firm to enter the market as a DCB.  Such companies would face
the prospect of being named as a defendant in any potential product
liability litigation involving a drug or medical device for which
they had been involved in the approval process.  Particularly
in a world of joint and several liability in which a DCB could
be potentially responsible for the entire liability burden if
the defendant company was unable to meet the cost involved in
the award, the DCBs would risk bankruptcy in much the same way
do many companies which face the prospect of mass toxic tort litigation
or punitive damages.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >In this instance, a reasonable proposal for
structuring the liability system would be to draw distinction
between potential liability with respect to negligence and strict
liability.  One would want to maintain incentives for the DCB
to exercise care in the approval of new drugs.  Thus, we would
not want the DCB to be negligent in overseeing the review process
for drugs or medical devices.  Thus, permitting suits against
the DCB by an injured plaintiff on the basis of negligence would
provide for the possibility of court sanctions against irresponsible
DCB behavior.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >This liability exposure could be coupled with
the provision of a legal exemption from strict liability.  Although
the experience of Underwriters' Laboratory and other certifying
bodies suggests that strict liability has not been of consequence
to date, a specific legal exemption from strict liability could
be beneficial in eliminating the small risk of catastrophic losses
that might otherwise deter entry of potential DCBs.  Would, for
example, a university hospital be willing to gamble its entire
financial resources on the opportunity to enter this novel and
potentially highly litigious area?  If it did so, the fees needed
to cover potential liability costs would provide a deterrent to
the testing of potentially beneficial new drugs.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The underlying rationale for strict liability
in the usual judicial context is that the company has a role beyond
not being negligent.  Rather, the firm should serve as the insurer
for the potential losses of accident victims and spread these
losses in much the same way as would an insurance company.  The
reasoning behind this is that the firm can pass along the cost
of the insurance to the customers who in effect will buy the insurance
for liability costs for pharmaceuticals or drugs as part of the
purchase price.  However, the additional insurance rationale is
not pertinent to whether the firm exercises appropriate care.
 The negligence doctrine alone is adequate to establishing these
incentives.  Moreover, it is not the DCB but rather the pharmaceutical
and medical device company that is marketing the product and has
the ability to spread the cost through the product price.  It
is, of course, true that the DCB can raise its fees to the companies,
which in turn can raise the product price.  Even in this instance,
however, this insurance analogy tends to break down in the case
of mass toxic torts and punitive damages.  Unanticipated awards,
such as those that resulted from the imposition of retroactive
liability, by their very nature cannot be recouped in the marketplace.
 Cases such as those that led to the bankruptcy or reorganization
of the affected firms likewise do not lend themselves to an insurance
role.  Moreover, the types of court awards that are made do not
simply provide insurance of medical costs and other income losses
of accident victims but instead provide for amounts well beyond
these losses.  Such awards will not be valued by prospective consumers
of the product since this is not the type of insurance they would
choose to purchase.  Consequently their cost will not be fully
reflected in the purchase price that consumers are willing to
pay.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The DCBs would, of course, have liability to
the companies as well as to potential consumers.  In particular,
the product certifier would have the responsibility of fulfilling
the terms of its contracts with its clients.  Thus, the certifier
would have the contractual duty to carry out these contract provisions
as well as the tort law duty to provide a workman-like service.<sup><a href="foot.html">34</a></sup>
 The DCB also is subject to the provisions of communicating the
results of its findings to the client.  If the DCB provides false
or inaccurate information, then it is subject to tort liability.<sup><a href="foot.html">35</a></sup>
 Under the theory of negligent misrepresentation the company could
potentially sue the DCB for providing false or inaccurate information.
 Thus, if the company suffered financial losses because of the
false information provided by the DCB and the DCB failed to exercise
reasonable care in obtaining and communicating the information,
then there is a potential basis for a negligence by the company
against the DCB.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The greater practical problem from the standpoint
of DCBs is not whether they are subject to potential liability
actions on the part of corporations purchasing its services but
rather whether third parties injured by the approved products
can obtain liability awards.  As a general rule, U.S. courts have
not found companies responsible for endorsing or certifying products
strictly liable for these defects.  However, a specific legal
exemption from strict liability could ensure that this is the
case and conclusively eliminate the threat of such suits.  The
underlying rationale that has been applied by the courts has been
that the product endorsers or testers are not directly involved
in the manufacturing or the distribution of the product so that
the usual rationales for strict liability are not appropriate.<sup><a href="foot.html">36</a></sup>
 For much the same reasoning, manufacturers have not been held
liable under the theories of breach of warranty.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >Our plan's proposal that the DCBs be exposed
to third party suits on grounds of negligence is also consistent
with current legal doctrine in this area.  In situations in which
the courts have first determined that the testers or product certifiers
owed a duty of care to the general public, then negligence rules
have been applied.<sup><a href="foot.html">37</a></sup><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The underlying reasoning that has led to the
courts determining that product certifiers and testers are potentially
liable can be traced to two principles.  If the individual who
is harmed took actions that were based on reasonable reliance
on the information provided by the certifier/tester and if the
certifier/tester is negligent either in obtaining accurate information
or in presenting it then there is potential liability for whatever
physical harm results from the use of these products.  As a general
rule, companies that are responsible for supplying information
to the public and which will be relied upon by the public in making
their purchasing decisions do have a duty to consumers.<sup><a href="foot.html">38</a></sup>  Of course
in the case of the role of DCBs with respect to product certification,
this aspect of liability will be complicated by the fact that
the FDA has the final sign-off in this review process.  Thus,
it must be the case that it is the DCB and not the FDA that is
responsible for the negligence.  The key issue is whether the
DCB has been careless or negligent in carrying out its responsibilities,
which is a much narrower basis for liability than is the case
for the pharmaceutical companies.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >To summarize, the major changes being proposed
with respect to the liability system pertain both to the current
liability regime as well as the proposed new regulatory structure.
 In particular, the proposal models a regulatory compliance defense
for pharmaceuticals and devices both with respect to punitive
damages and liability more generally.  The plan proposals to revise
the FDA drug and device approval process would not alter the pertinence
or applicability of these legal reforms.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT >The specific new legal issues that are raised
by the reform proposals pertain to the potential liability of
the DCBs.  If this potential liability is substantial, then entry
into this market will be discouraged and the desired competition
will not be forthcoming.  For the most part, the desired legal
changes needed to accompany this new regulatory mechanism simply
involve clarification of the existing legal structure to eliminate
residual uncertainties.  Potential contractual liability of the
DCBs to the companies purchasing their services would be present
and is entirely appropriate.  The greater dangers are those posed
by strict liability and negligence claims involving the products
tested by the DCBs.  Past legal precedent suggests that strict
liability claims are unlikely to be upheld by the court, but to
eliminate the risk of potentially catastrophic losses we propose
that there be a formal legal exemption from strict liability suits.
 As under the current legal regime, DCBs would be subject to potential
suits with respect to negligence, as indeed they should since
one would want to preserve the incentives for them to carry out
their duties in an efficient manner.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P><br></blockquote><center><small><a href="fdatoc.html">Report Contents</a></small><P><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
