Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>National Minority Politics - Washington Report - October 1995</title>
</head>
<body>
<center><table border>
<tr>
<img alt="Washington Report Logo" src="wlogo.gif"> </td>
</tr></table>
<p><h3>October 1995</h3><p>
<img src= "red-line.gif">
</center><p>

<a name="table"><b>Table of Contents</b></a>
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#general">General Colin Powell</a> and the Presidency
<li><a href="#jesse">Jesse Jackson</a> and the Presidency
<li><a href="#georgia">Georgia</a> Congressional Redistricting
<li><a href="#welfare">Welfare Reform</a>
</ul>
<P>
<hr>
<p><a name="general"></a><br><p>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<ul><li>	General Colin Powell is clearly in the throes of a media lovefest regarding his potential presidential candidacy.  His autobiography, My American Journey, was released Sept. 15 with an initial print run of 800,000 copies.  It is expected to shoot to the top of the bestsellers' lists almost immediately.
	<P>About 3,000 fans jammed into a large bookstore and lined up for blocks as Powell launched his book-promotion tour in McLean, Va., a wealthy Washington, D.C. suburb, by appearing to sign his autobiography.
	<P>In a new CNN/Time poll released Sept. 15, 53 percent said they wanted to see Powell run for president.  He ran ahead of President Clinton in a two-way match up and was in a statistical dead heat with Clinton in a hypothetical Dole-Clinton-Powell race.
	<P>An in-depth profile/interview with Barbara Walters on ABC's "20/20" aired the same day the poll was released.  Other television interviews with the major networks will follow.  Powell has been on the cover of Time, Newsweek and U.S. News & World Report in the last few weeks.  And, as he embarks on his multi-city book tour that runs through October, the media hype will continue.
	<P>But don't expect it to last.  Remember 1992 and Ross Perot's budding presidential bid?  Perot's potential candidacy was touted as the second coming--until he actually got into the race.  In particular, the poll showing Powell would best both Clinton and Dole is eerily reminiscent of a similar poll in 1992 showing Perot leading both Clinton and then President Bush.  Then the negative media barrage ensued with charges of "inspector Perot" and innuendos that the Texas businessman's elevator didn't go all the way to the top.  <P>
	Granted, Perot didn't help his cause with his on-again/off-again campaign.  But the media frenzy damaged his reputation, perhaps irreparably.
	<P>We did learn a few things about Powell that we didn't know, however, from the Walters interview.  For starters, Powell appears to be comfortable with the economic conservatives of the Republican Party, but not quite as comfortable with some of the more strident social conservatives.  Although, in the rush to judgment, his positions on the issues have already been mischaracterized by some conservatives and members of the press, Powell appears to be:
<ul><LI>Pro-choice, but not pro-abortion;
<li>Against quotas and racial preferences, but favors reaching out to economically and socially disadvantaged individuals, regardless of race;
<LI>Solidly for 2nd Amendment rights of gun ownership, but willing to be slightly incon-venienced with registration and/or waiting periods;
<LI>Supportive of a private moment in school for prayer at the students' choosing, but would not support mandatory school prayer; and
<LI>Uncomfortable with the Clinton administration's vacillations on foreign policy issues.
</ul>	<P>Powell has a commanding presidential presence.  He dwarfs the other candidates, both in terms of his life's achievements and the charisma he possesses.  
	<P>At least one of the other GOP presidential candidates has commented on Powell's chances to get the party nomination.  "Despite the political yearnings of pro-abortion Republicans and much of the national news media, retired Army Gen. Colin Powell has not a prayer of winning the GOP nomination," Alan Keyes told USA Today in an interview.  
	<P>Keyes concluded that Powell has a "good background and he's accomplished a lot in his life, but he doesn't seem to have thought through the public policy issues.  Being a good man and being a good president are not necessarily the same thing."
<p>	But it is likely, if Keyes had his druthers, he'd prefer to have poll numbers like Powell, than the 1 to 2 percent national support which the two-time U.S. Senate candidate currently garners.
	<P>Nevertheless, Powell should think long and hard before entering the race.  The media, in their rush to make mere mortals of men, have so tarnished the character of our political leaders that we have few, if any, heroes remaining--living or dead.  The former Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, with his reputation intact on the sidelines, may serve as much of a purpose for Americans as he would after being sullied by the whole campaign process.
<P>

<a name="jesse"></a><br>
<P><a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><P>
<LI>  Advisers to the Rev. Jesse Jackson disclosed recently that he has submitted his name to be included as a presidential candidate in a nonbinding urban presidential primary called City Vote, to be held in November, according to a report in the Wall Street Journal.
	<P>Jackson is contemplating a challenge to President Clinton from within the Democratic Party, but is giving more serious thought to running as an independent.  City Vote is a privately financed effort to give greater prominence to the urban issues Jackson advocates by allowing voters in some 20 cities to cast a nonbinding vote for presidential preference at the time they vote in local elections this November.
	<P>Jackson's aides said he is putting his name on the City Vote ballot both to raise the profile of urban problems and as a way to keep his personal political options open.
	<P>The head of the National Rainbow Coalition announced Sept. 9 that he had raised the $150,000 he owed the FEC from his 1988 presidential campaign, removing one of the obstacles to a potential return to the presidential trail next year.  Had he not paid the settlement, Jackson would not be eligible to receive federal matching campaign funds in future races.
<P>	"All options are alive," said Jackson at a press conference.  He outlined three possible political courses of action for himself in 1996--to stay out of the race, to challenge Clinton in the Democratic primaries or to run as an independent.  
	<P>He noted, however, that he second option was "remote" and that he would wait until the spring to decide on an independent run.  Jackson said that part of his decision would be based on whether Clinton "embraces an activist agenda" for urban development, education and health, as well as enforcement of affirmative action laws.
<P>

<a name="georgia"></a><br><p>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<Li>   Efforts by the Georgia legislature to redraw the state's congressional district map collapsed Sept. 12, leaving the task to a three-judge federal panel.
	After overwhelmingly rejecting two proposed compromise redistricting plans during that week, both houses of the General Assembly voted to adjourn, following a five-week special session that cost the taxpayers at least $500,000.  "I hate to admit failure, but I don't know anything else to do," state House Speaker Tom Murphy, a Democrat, was quoted as saying by the Associated Press.  And state House Reapportionment Committee Chairman Tommy Smith said earlier, "I see absolutely no hope of the conferees passing any plan out on this congressional exercise."
	<P>The special session was called Aug. 14 after the U.S. Supreme Court in late June ruled that the majority-black 11th District of Democratic Rep. Cynthia McKinney was unconstitutional.
	<P>The justices said the legislature had relied too heavily on race in creating the seat following the 1990 census.  The 11th District stretches 250 miles from Savannah to Atlanta in an effort to pick up black voters.
<P>	But, during the special session, the legislature found itself badly split among competing demands from white Democrats, black Democrats and Republicans.
	<P>The black Democrats wanted to retain at least two of the state's current three majority-black House districts.  The Republicans, who now control the other eight districts in the state, feared dilution of their numbers.
	<P>The latest compromise plan, rejected Sept. 11 by a 122-22 vote in the state House and 44-8 in the state Senate, would have left Democratic Rep. John Lewis as the only one of the state's three black incumbents with a majority-black district.
<P>	Republicans disliked the plan because it would have placed House Speaker Gingrich and GOP Rep. Bob Barr in the same Atlanta-area district.  And black legislators objected because it failed to keep McKinney's district from intruding on the 5th District represented by Democratic Rep. John Lewis, and because it removed a key part of the majority-black district of Democratic Rep. Sanford Bishop.
	<P>The new congressional map will now be drawn by the same three-judge federal panel that originally threw out the 11th District.
<P>
   
<a name="welfare"></a><br>
<P>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><P>
<LI>The prospects for ending welfare as we know it were dashed with the caving in of moderate Senate Republicans, joining with liberal Democrats, to fundamental changes in the current system.  Nearly everyone agrees that the welfare system has been a disaster.  
	<P>It has been particularly devastating for black communities throughout the U.S.  As late as 1958, 78 percent of black children were living with two-parent families.  That figure is now at 45 percent--and falling.  But the reverberations of the disastrous welfare system can be felt throughout virtually every segment of society.
	<P>The two most important aspects of welfare reform--denying additional benefits to women who have more children while on the welfare rolls and denying cash benefits to teen-agers who have children out of wedlock--should have been easy to implement.  Any idiot can see that if you pay women to have children without marrying and you set up house for teen-agers who have already shown that they are irresponsible and pay them to continue to make the same mistakes, you'll end up with what we've got right now.  After all, do women who are married and work receive a raise every time they have a baby?  And, if people are paid to have babies, why is anyone surprised when they do?<P>
	<P>But the battle was actually lost in the spring when the debate on welfare shifted from making parents responsible for their children to punishing children for their parents' mistakes.  Once the liberals took the latter argument and ran with it, moderates caved.  Although versions of those elements remain in the version passed March 24 by the House, which has generally been far more conservative in its approach to welfare, senior administration officials have made clear that the President would veto the House measure.
<P>	The Senate bill seeks to save $70 billion in welfare spending over seven years and, by the year 2000, would require that 50 percent of parents receiving welfare work for their benefits.  It would also impose a five-year limit on drawing welfare benefits, although states could offer hardship exemptions to a limited pool of recipients.  
	<P>These are good first steps, but they miss the point.  Welfare should not be an entitlement, but a contract between the recipient and his or her country that, in exchange for assistance during hard times, he or she will do the following: 1) Work and/or attend school; 2) Change irresponsible behavior; 3) Vow to make better decisions in the future.
	<P>The President and others will, however, claim victory for reforming the welfare system.  The Republicans have extolled the concept of block granting the welfare payments to the states in the form of lump sums.  This will allow the states more flexibility to see what works and what doesn't.  
	<P>But, politicians have a tendency, when given lump sum payments, to transfer those sums to areas where the politically powerful have exerted pressure.  And, with a lack of vision as to the principles upon which we would like our national welfare system administered, we'll end up with 50 different hybrids.
	<P>Five years from now, we'll look back on this period and say, "We should have done something in 1995.  The problem has gotten worse."
<P></ul>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>

[ <a href="home.html">NMP Home</a> | <a href="i-wr.html">Washington Report Index</a> ]
<p>
</body>
</html>

