<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>The Dole-Kemp Economic Plan</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>The Dole-Kemp Economic Plan</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Unshackling the American People<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<UL>
<LI>15% across-the-board tax rate cut.  Here are the tax brackets
before and after the Dole tax cut.
</UL>
<pre>
Current:		Dole tax brackets:
     39.6%                   33.67%
     36.0%                   30.60%
     31.0%                   26.35%
     28.0%                   23.8 %
     15.0%                   12.75%
</pre>
<UL>
<LI>$500 per child tax credit.  This tax credit allows parents
to subtract $500 off their tax bill for each child under 18 years
of age.  
<LI>Cut capital gains tax rate from 28% to 14%.  In 1992, 56%
of capital gains were from households with incomes of $50,000
or less.  Households with less than $100,000 income accounted
for 83% of the returns reporting capital gains.
<LI>Repeal the 1993 tax hike on Social Security benefits.  Due
to the 1993 Clinton tax increase on Social Security, 85% of Social
Security benefits became subject to federal taxation.  Retiree
incomes as low as $34,000 saw their taxes on Social Security benefits
rise.
<LI>American Dream Savings Accounts.  These accounts would expand
IRA's.  They would allow after-tax contributions and earn interest tax-free.
 They would also allow penalty-free withdrawals to help finance a first home, pay for
college expenses, or defray medical costs.  
<LI>IRA's for spouses who choose to stay at home.  A $2,000 per
year contribution can be 
put into an IRA on behalf of a spouse who works at home.
<LI>Education Investment Accounts.  These accounts allow up to
$500 per child per year to be put into tax-free account.  Parents who placed $500 per
year into the account would accrue $18,689 tax-free after 18 years.
<LI>Balanced Budget Amendment to the Constitution
</UL>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>Why Does America Need a Tax Cut?</FONT></B></CENTER>
<UL>
<LI>America is experiencing the slowest expansion in 100 years.
 The Clinton expansion is averaging 2.4% growth - not exactly
the best economy in the last 30 years.  The last five expansions
produced average growth rates of 4.4%.  The Reagan expansion during
the 1980's averaged over 5% growth.
<LI>Tax Freedom Day is now the latest ever.  The day Americans
work until to pay their share of federal taxes is now May 7, the
latest it's ever been.
<LI>Cost of Government day now July 3.  In 1996 Americans worked
until July 3 to earn enough money to pay off all direct and
hidden taxes (total federal, state, local government spending
plus the cost of regulation).
<LI>Real Median Household Income lower during Clinton than the
previous decade.  From 1983 to 1992, real median household income
was $33,119.  Under Clinton, it shrunk to $32,153.
<LI>Federal, State, and Local taxes account for 38% of a family's
budget (more than food, clothing, and health care combined). 
Today 26% of a family's budget goes to federal taxes, 12% to state
and local taxes, while 9% goes to food, 4% is spent on clothing,
and 10% goes for medical care.
<LI>Worker's real hourly wages have gone down under Clinton.  Bill
Clinton, the alleged protector of the working man, has presided
over a .4% drop in real hourly wages.  Wages went up 5.6% during
the decade before Clinton.  <BR>
</ul>
<P>
<CENTER><B>How to Balance the Budget with the Dole Tax Cut</B></CENTER>
<P>
The economic plan of Republican Presidential nominee Robert
Dole promises to enact a major tax reduction plan and to balance
the Federal budget by 2002.  Some have argued that the lost revenue
from the tax cut plan would make balancing the budget by 2002
impossible.  The following facts show that this is untrue.
<UL>
<LI>Even counting the reduced tax revenues from the Dole tax cut
plan, the budget can be  balanced by 2002 by holding the growth
in government spending to 2.1% per year.  This is only slightly
less than the rate of increase in Federal spending since 1992,
which has been 2.4%.
<LI>Between now and 2002, the Federal government would spend $10.8
trillion overall under current law.  Counting the reduced revenue
from the Dole tax cut plan, the Federal budget can be balanced
by 2002 while still spending $10.2 trillion between now and then.
<LI>Counting the reduced revenue from the Dole tax cut plan, the
budget can be balanced by 2002 if the government spends just 4%
less than it now plans to spend between now and then.
<LI>Counting the reduced revenue from the Dole tax cut plan, the
budget can be balanced by 2002 while increasing annual Federal
spending by 14% by that year compared to this year.  Under current
law, annual Federal spending will be 20% larger by 2002 compared
to today.
</UL>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> </FONT>
</BODY>
